UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Your practice management team has reviewed the clinic - wide cancer screening rates and found that the frequency of cervical cancer screening appears to have fallen behind other cancer screenings. You are asked to lead a quality improvement project to increase rates of cervical cancer screening for appropriate patients. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate first step?', explanation = 'Quality improvement is a key area for clinical practice, but initiating these projects can be challenging. Many different methodologies have been used, including the Plan - Do - Study - Act cycle or Plan - Do - Check - Act cycle, but clear identification of the current issues is critical in any framework. In order to plan appropriate interventions, it must first be determined what barriers are responsible for hindering performance in a certain area. If evaluation shows that there is a systemic issue in capturing data, rather than a clinician issue, no other interventions will be beneficial. When used as part of an organizational plan for staffing and clinical procedures, patient - specific reminders and use of the entire health care team are more likely to improve screening uptake than other methods, but the initial step should be delineating any current issues prior to implementing a change. Educating patients about preventive health care and screenings is essential and should be part of routine care. However, general materials such as clinic posters are less likely to increase screening rates than direct physician recommendations or conversations. Sending generalized reminders for preventive care may miss the patients in most critical need of services. General reminders that rely on clinician evaluation of every individual visit may be less effective than patient - specific reminders that can be addressed at the point of care.', options = '["Establishing a system for reviewing charts and contacting patients who are overdue for cervical cancer screening","Evaluating barriers to cervical cancer screening and reporting","Placing posters with information about cervical cancer screening inside the clinic","Sending generalized reminders to patients who may qualify for cervical cancer screening","Sending generalized reminders to all clinicians regarding cervical cancer screening guidelines"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'a4001085-d915-4ddb-bce9-f579abfbf6bd';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'You are seeing a 32 - year - old male in the office. His most recent hemoglobin A was 6.1≥, 1c indicating prediabetes. Which one of the following is most likely to prevent the development of diabetes?', explanation = 'Given the growing prevalence of diabetes mellitus, clinicians should be familiar with effective prevention strategies. Intensive lifestyle and behavior modification programs, such as the National Diabetes Prevention Program, are low - cost and can reduce the development of diabetes, with one U.S. study demonstrating a 27≥ reduction over 15 years. These programs help patients set weight loss goals ≥7≥ of their baseline, which is thought to be a key component of diabetes prevention. This is typically achieved through a caloric reduction of 500 – 1000 kcal per day, with activity goals ≥150 minutes per week, including up to 75 minutes per week of strength training. While a variety of dietary patterns are thought to be effective for diabetes prevention, including low intake of carbohydrates, the evidence for changes in dietary patterns is not as strong as that of intensive lifestyle programs.', options = '["Intensive lifestyle and behavior change program","Low - carbohydrate diet","Reduction in daily caloric intake by 250 kcal per day","Strength training for 90 minutes per week"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'f26f91da-37d8-477f-802b-b892d6d3c917';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An otherwise healthy 47 - year - old male presents to the urgent care clinic with pain and swelling of his right foot after sustaining an injury during a game of ultimate frisbee. He he landed, but jumped to catch the frisbee and landed on uneven ground. He is unsure of how thinks he may have twisted his right foot, causing him to trip and fall. He has significant pain and swelling of his right foot but is weight - bearing. He rates the pain as 10 on a scale of 10. On examination, his vital signs are unremarkable. His right lateral foot shows significant bruising and swelling. The skin is intact. Range of movement is impaired due to the swelling and discomfort, and sensation and circulation are intact. An x - ray of th e right foot is shown below. Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?', explanation = 'This patient''s imaging reveals a fifth metatarsal shaft fracture, which should be managed with a boot or hard - soled shoe for 3 – 6 weeks with weight - bearing. Foot fractures are typically caused by an axial or twisting force on the foot or a crush injury and account for about one - third of lower extremity fractures in adults. Patients present with swelling and bony point tenderness of the affected area, as seen in this patient. The ability to bear weight varies based on the patient''s pain tolerance and the extent of the fracture. Complications of foot fractures include infection, arthritis, nonunion, malunion, and compartment syndrome. A short leg cast is not appropriate because it is used to treat proximal fifth metatarsal and tarsal bone fractures. Physical therapy is not first - line management for this patient''s injury. If reduction is needed or if nonunion is present after 6 months, then referral to an orthopedic surgeon would be indicated.', options = '["Weight - bearing with a walking boot for 3 – 6 weeks","Non – weight - bearing with a walking boot for 3 – 6 weeks","Non – weight - bearing with a short leg cast for 6 weeks","Referral to a physical therapist","Referral to an orthopedic surgeon"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'dda216f2-f1f8-4495-b597-bddab68e6b34';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 78 - year - old female presents to the emergency department with a 2 - day history of cough and fever and a 2 - hour history of confusion. Her vital signs include a weight of 67 kg (148 lb), a temperature of 38.8 °C (101.8 °F), a pulse rate of 122 beats/min, and a blood pressure of 72/44 mm Hg with a mean arterial pressure (MAP) of 53 mm Hg. A chest x - ray shows left lower lobe pneumonia. She is given 2 L of lactated Ringer solution and started on broad - spectrum antibiotics for sepsis secondary to pneumonia. Her b lood pressure 3 hours later is 82/46 mm Hg with a MAP of 58 mm Hg. Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate next step in management?', explanation = 'This patient is in septic shock secondary to pneumonia. Surviving Sepsis Campaign guidelines recommend early goal - directed therapy (EGDT) consisting of initial fluid resuscitation with 30 mL/kg of crystalloid solution within the first 3 hours and appropriate antibiotics within 1 hour of evaluation, which have already been done for this patient. The guidelines also recommend initiating vasopressor therapy with norepinephrine as the first - line agent if the mean arterial pressure remains <65 mm Hg after fluid resuscitation. Norepinephrine is a more potent vasoconstrictor than dopamine. Additional fluid therapy is controversial and patient - specific, with some experts recommending discrete 500 - mL boluses with hemodynamic monitoring of response, and others recommending balanced crystalloids such as lactate Ringer solution over normal saline. Vasopressin should be added for adults with septic shock who are receiving norepinephrine but continue to have inadequate mean arterial pressure. Vasopressor therapy should not be delayed for placement of a central line.', options = '["A 1 - L bolus of normal saline","A dopamine infusion","A norepinephrine infusion","A vasopressin infusion","Placement of a central line"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '52e066e6-d267-4544-95a5-106bea7c0863';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'You are called to the emergency department (ED) to admit a 48 - year - old female with a past medical history of hyperthyroidism who presented with agitation, palpitations, and diarrhea. The ED team diagnosed thyroid storm secondary to the abrupt discontinuati on of the patient''s methimazole 2 weeks ago due to a lapse in insurance. On examination, she is tachycardic and hypertensive but can sustain a conversation without dyspnea. Laboratory studies are significant for elevated free T and T levels and an 3 4 undetectable TSH level. A urine pregnancy test is negative. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate initial step in management?', explanation = 'Thyroid storm is a medical emergency that must be treated promptly. The initial treatment for thyroid storm is propylthiouracil (PTU). While PTU has been shown to decrease circulating T hormone levels more quickly than methimazole, they have both been shown 3 to be equally effective clinically. Glucocorticoids can also be used to block the conversion of T to T . Hydrocortisone and dexamethasone, not prednisone, are the preferred 4 3 glucocorticoids if used in addition to PTU. While iodine is used to block the synthesis of new thyroid hormone, it should be started at least 1 hour after the initiation of PTU. Plasmapheresis is reserved for patients who do not respond to pharmacologic treatment.', options = '["Inorganic iodine","Prednisone","Propylthiouracil","Plasmapheresis"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'b2c8213b-c641-4c92-811b-f6a9917a0203';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'According to guidelines from the American Gastroenterological Association, which one of the following is recommended as the best pharmacologic treatment of typical symptoms in diarrhea - predominant irritable bowel syndrome?', explanation = 'According to the 2022 American Gastroenterological Association guidelines for diarrhea - predominant irritable bowel syndrome (IBS - D), the nonabsorbable antibiotic rifaximin has the best evidence for controlling diarrhea, discomfort, bloating, and abdominal pain. It has a broad spectrum with activity against gram - positive, gram - negative (including Clostridioides difficile ), and anaerobic bacteria. It is thought to work by reducing bacterial byproducts and altering the gut flora. It is prescribed as a 14 - day course for acute and recurrent symptoms. Rifaximin does not have any significant adverse effects, but it is a high - cost medication. Low - dose amitriptyline and dicyclomine are often effective in reducing symptoms, but the evidence is not as strong as that of rifaximin. Linaclotide is used for constipation - predominant IBS (IBS - C), but its chief side effect of diarrhea results in many patients discontinuing the medication. Lubiprostone is another medication used for IBS - C and for opioid - induced constipation, not IBS - D.', options = '["Amitriptyline","Dicyclomine","Linaclotide (Linzess)","Lubiprostone (Amitiza)","Rifaximin (Xifaxan)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '8f48aee1-e30d-4b86-91ee-25e8d104b91e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 56 - year - old female with moderately controlled type 2 diabetes presents with painful diabetic neuropathy in her feet. You address her diabetic control and other risk factors, but she says the pain continues and is affecting her life adversely. Which one of the following is considered a first - line treatment for pain relief in this condition?', explanation = 'First - line treatments for the relief of painful diabetic neuropathy include amitriptyline, duloxetine, gabapentin, and pregabalin. Second - line treatments include topical lidocaine and capsaicin, with less evidence of benefit. Opioids such as hydrocodone should be avoided in the treatment of neuropathic pain. Studies of peripheral transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation have shown modest benefit; however, it is not a first - line treatment.', options = '["Topical capsaicin","Topical lidocaine","Oral gabapentin","Oral hydrocodone","Peripheral transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'ac97f546-4204-4756-a35a-b7b460a94d1f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A generally healthy 60 - year - old female presents to your office because she is concerned about urinary leakage. Her symptoms started a couple of years ago and have worsened. The leakage occurs when she coughs or laughs, but can also happen if she waits too long to urinate. She hydrates throughout the day. She does not take any medications and does not smoke. She has a remote surgical history of a hysterectomy after delivering her third child. She does not have any fever or abdominal pain and has not been exp osed to any sexually transmitted infections. Recent laboratory studies, including a CBC, comprehensive metabolic panel, TSH level, and hemoglobin A , were unremarkable. Today she has a blood pressure of 120/70 mm Hg and a BMI of 32 kg/m . Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in the workup?', explanation = 'Urinary incontinence is common among women and can substantially diminish quality of life while contributing to increased financial strain. Risk factors include obesity, parity, increasing age, and a history of hysterectomy. The initial evaluation includes a thorough history and should establish whether the incontinence is transient or chronic. It should also identify the incontinence subtype as well as any red flags that would warrant subspecialist referral, such as pelvic organ prolapse or fistula. Urinalysis should be ordered for all patients with urinary incontinence. An incontinence screening questionnaire, cough stress test (SOR C), postvoid residual measurement, and a 3 - day voiding diary are helpful tools. Renal and bladder ultrasonography, urodynamic testing, and cystoscopy are not recommended for the initial evaluation of uncomplicated urinary incontinence. Treatments include weight loss, pelvic floor training, lifestyle modifications including appropriate fluid intake, smoking cessation, and pharmacologic therapy. Patients with refractory urinary incontinence can be referred for more invasive treatments, such as mechanical devices, intravesical onabotulinumtoxinA injection, and surgical procedures.', options = '["No testing","Urinalysis","Renal and bladder ultrasonography","Urodynamic testing","Cystoscopy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '5f603a08-b14d-4ab7-8157-ecfb39ed95b3';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 68 - year - old female with previously diagnosed immune thrombocytopenia presents to your office to establish care. She has no current bleeding. A CBC is normal except for a platelet count of 47,000/mm (N 130,000 – 400,000). You refer her to a hematologist for long - term management. Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient''s current thrombocytopenia?', explanation = 'Immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) is caused by autoimmune destruction of platelets in the spleen and causes chronic thrombocytopenia of varying severity. Although hematologists typically oversee care for patients with ITP, family physicians may need to make acute treatment decisions in collaboration with these patients. The American Society of Hematology recommends not to treat ITP unless there is active bleeding or very low platelet counts, defined as <30,000/mm . This patient does not require treatment at this time because she does not have any current bleeding and her platelet count is above the threshold for treatment. Corticosteroids and rituximab are both used to treat ITP, along with intravenous immunoglobulin. Hydroxychloroquine sulfate is not typically recommended in the treatment of ITP.', options = '["No treatment","Oral hydroxychloroquine sulfate (Plaquenil)","Oral prednisone","Intravenous methylprednisolone sodium succinate (Solu - Medrol)","Intravenous rituximab (Rituxan)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '144cd3d6-b110-4b04-80d6-03bb49b12361';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 45 - year - old male who is living with HIV and has been on highly active antiretroviral therapy (HAART) for the past 10 years presents for routine follow - up. Which one of the following would be part of an appropriate screening strategy for long - term complic ations associated with HAART?', explanation = 'The Infectious Diseases Society of America recommends performing urinalysis at least once yearly and obtaining a glomerular filtration rate at least twice yearly in stable patients on highly active antiretroviral therapy (HAART) to detect kidney function abnormalities and drug nephrotoxicity. While cardiovascular risk assessment is important in persons living with HIV, the Framingham Risk Score is not well validated in this population. The American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association recommend using traditional risk factors and clinical judgment for cardiovascular risk assessment in this population. Neurocognitive screening is typically performed based on clinical indications rather than as an annual routine screening for all patients on HAART. Liver fibrosis screening is appropriate in patients with coinfection with hepatitis B or C, but it is not a routine annual screening. Although bone mineral density screening is important in persons living with HIV, especially those at risk for osteoporosis, it is not recommended annually for all patients on HAART.', options = '["Calculation of the Framingham Risk Score now, and a fasting lipid profile annually","Neurocognitive screening annually","Transient elastography annually","A DXA scan annually","Urinalysis annually, and a glomerular filtration rate twice yearly"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '934e5c8b-35d4-4a75-b65e-77800b77ede4';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 40 - year - old male with type 2 diabetes presents to the emergency department with chest pain and shortness of breath. The patient has normal vital signs. A physical examination and laboratory tests, including serial troponin levels, are normal. Outpatient records from about 6 months ago include a normal cardiac stress test that was negative for myocardial ischemia. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in evaluation?', explanation = 'For this intermediate - risk patient with no history of coronary artery disease (CAD) who presents with angina and a negative workup for acute coronary syndrome plus negative stress testing within 1 year, coronary CT angiography would be the next step to determine if he has obstructive CAD or atherosclerotic plaques. A repeat stress test would not be indicated. Fractional flow reserve with CT is useful to help guide revascularization after an abnormal coronary CT angiogram reveals vessel stenosis. Cardiac MRI would be useful to determine structural abnormalities.', options = '["Stress echocardiography","Coronary CT angiography","Fractional flow reserve with CT","Cardiac MRI"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '1cb09656-f03f-4c43-a058-91492be31ddf';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 40 - year - old male with a history of alcohol use disorder presents to your office for help abstaining from alcohol. Until recently, he has been drinking at least 6 beers per day and often more on weekend days. He has 2 prior arrests for DUI, and his wife p lans to file for divorce if he does not change. Over the past 2 weeks, he has been able to wean himself off alcohol and has joined a sobriety group. He requests medication to help him maintain his sobriety. Which one of the following medications should you recommend for this patient?', explanation = 'This patient meets criteria for moderate alcohol use disorder (AUD). Although AUD is a leading cause of preventable death, less than 2≥ of patients with AUD are prescribed medications. Acamprosate is recommended for patients who have achieved abstinence and desire to maintain it (SOR A). Gabapentin is useful for the prevention of withdrawal and is safe for those who are still drinking (SOR A). Topiramate is useful in decreasing heavy drinking (SOR B). There is insufficient evidence to recommend disulfiram.', options = '["Acamprosate","Disulfiram","Gabapentin (Neurontin)","Topiramate (Topamax)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'c1ce64cb-d5cb-42d2-9eba-d7701f2acfb3';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 15 - year - old male presents to your office with an intensely pruritic rash 2 days after returning from a camping trip in the woods. On examination you observe a rash on the hands, arms, face, and genitals with vesicles and a few bullae. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment option?', explanation = 'Poison ivy is perhaps the most common cause of allergic contact dermatitis in the United States, causing up to 10 million persons annually to seek medical care. Caused by the oleoresin urushiol that is present in Toxicodendron species (poison ivy, sumac, oak), allergic contact dermatitis is a type IV delayed hypersensitivity reaction. Symptoms develop 12 – 72 hours after exposure. Prior sensitization is necessary. The rash has varying presentations, including irregular erythematous patches, linear streaks of vesicles, and larger fluid - filled bullae. T he blister fluid does not cause the rash to spread. This illusion of spreading is due to the time variability in when the rash develops (hours to days) based on how much resin was in contact with the skin. Systemic corticosteroids are indicated for facial, genital, or significant vesiculobullous involvement. In type IV hypersensitivity reactions, rebound inflammation occurs if treatment with corticosteroids is insufficient in dose or duration. The most effective treatment in this patient would be a 15 - day prednisone taper, starting with 1 mg/kg (60 mg at maximum). A single injection of triamcinolone has variable efficacy and often does not take effect as quickly as oral prednisone; however, if used, it should be administered intramuscularly, never subcutaneously, due to the likelihood of lipoatrophy. Topical corticosteroids, even the most potent formulations, do not work on bullous lesions and are contraindicated on the face and genitals. A common prescription for poison ivy dermatitis is a 5 - day dose pack of methylprednisolone. This provides temporary improvement but is frequently followed by a rebound in rash, which indicates an insufficient dose and duration of the corticosteroid. There is no indication for draining the bullae or vesicles in this patient.', options = '["Topical clobetasol, applied twice daily to affected areas until symptoms resolve","Oral methylprednisolone, starting at 1 mg/kg and tapering over 5 days","Oral prednisone, starting at 1 mg/kg and tapering over 15 days","Subcutaneous triamcinolone, 80 mg once","Draining the bullae and large vesicles"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'a1c032d5-1add-4c87-995f-4d87c0c32aa5';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 50 - year - old male sees you for follow - up of a pulmonary nodule. He recently presented to the emergency department (ED) after a motor vehicle accident in which he sustained a broken clavicle. A CT scan in the ED showed a 6 - mm, incidental, solid pulmonary n odule and he was advised to follow up with his primary care physician. Today the patient is asymptomatic other than muscle soreness. He does not have any history of smoking. An examination does not reveal any enlarged lymph nodes. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', explanation = 'Evaluation of a pulmonary nodule balances the benefits of minimal testing for benign nodules with the risks of malignant nodules. It requires knowledge of the factors associated with the probability that the nodule is malignant, the performance characteristics of additional testing, and the advantages and disadvantages of more or less intensive follow - up. The probability of malignancy and the effectiveness of diagnostic tests depend on the size and characteristics of the nodule, which can be classified into 3 categories: small solid nodules, larger solid nodules, and subsolid nodules. A solid nodule between 6 mm and 8 mm should be monitored with CT of the chest in 6 – 12 months. Flexibility in these time intervals (eg, 3 – 6 months, 6 – 12 months) is included in the guidelines to accommodate nodule features other than size, as well as clinician and patient preferences. A solid nodule that has remained unchanged in size on chest CT over a period of 2 years or longer is considered benign. Primary care physicians should consider referral to a pulmonologist for patients with a larger solid nodule (8 – 30 mm) or a subsolid nodule due to their higher risk of malignancy.', options = '["No additional follow - up","A repeat CT scan in 6 – 12 months","A repeat CT scan in 18 – 24 months","Biopsy of the nodule to determine pathology","Referral to a pulmonologist"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'bc24550f-dc01-4346-b046-de6c5d9e4990';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 35 - year - old female presents to your office with a 3 - day history of right - sided facial weakness. She has flattening of the nasolabial fold and is unable to elevate the right corner of her mouth. She is able to close her right eye and raise her eyebrows. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', explanation = 'This patient presents with a relatively acute onset of facial weakness affecting only the right side of the face, but she is able to close her right eye and raise her eyebrows. Sparing of the forehead muscles is consistent with a supranuclear lesion because the nucleus of cranial nerve VII receives fibers from both sides of the cortex for the upper face, meaning the forehead would be unaffected. Cranial nerve VII includes visceral efferent fibers (facial muscles and stapedius), visceral motor fibers (salivary and lacrimal glands), and special sensory fibers (taste to the anterior two - thirds of the tongue). In Bell palsy, which involves edema of this cranial nerve, the entire side of the face is affected, including the forehead. Therefore, this presentation is not consistent with Bell palsy and warrants further evaluation, including brain MRI, to assess for a central cause. Prednisone and valacyclovir are not appropriate for this patient, as they are treatments used for Bell palsy. Plasmapheresis is not indicated for Bell palsy, stroke, or tumor. Surgical decompression is not indicated.', options = '["Reassurance only","Prednisone plus valacyclovir (Valtrex)","MRI of the brain","Plasmapheresis","Surgical decompression"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'b39c1375-ca79-4234-b5e5-f5be6df70f47';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'You see a 6 - month - old infant for a routine visit. The child has started teething and the parents are concerned about preventing cavities, as their municipality does not fluoridate the water. In addition to providing daily oral fluoride supplementation, which one of the following should you recommend?', explanation = 'Fluoride is widely recognized for its role in preventing dental caries, and community water fluoridation remains a safe, effective, and evidence - based strategy for improving oral health. Dietary supplements are recommended for infants and children when the community water supply is nonfluoridated. It is also recommended for parents to brush the teeth of infants and toddlers once or twice daily with a rice - sized amount of fluoridated toothpaste, increasing to a pea - sized amount of toothpaste at age 3. At age 6, children are less likely to swallow toothpaste, which can lead to fluorosis (permanent brownish staining of teeth). Children may be more independent in toothbrushing starting at age 6, although some may still need assistance for adequate brushing. Mouthwash with or without fluoride should not be used in children younger than 6 years. It can be used after age 6 if the child can reliably spit out the mouthwash rather than swallow it. Starting at the emergence of the first tooth, fluoride varnish should be applied every 3 months for children at high risk of caries and every 6 months for all other children.', options = '["Brushing the emerging teeth daily with a rice - sized amount of fluoridated toothpaste","Using mouthwash as an adjunct to toothbrushing until age 5","Application of fluoride varnish to teeth annually, starting at age 1","Application of fluoride varnish to teeth twice yearly, starting at age 3"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '7eb2f1ca-211a-40e8-a2b5-539481785284';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 75 - year - old male presents to your office with his family. Although he is a long - term patient of yours, you have not seen him in more than 1 year. His family tells you that they have noticed a gradual progression of neurologic symptoms over the past 6 mon ths, including a noticeably slower gait and a tremor of his right hand. The patient says that he has noticed worsening short - term memory loss. On examination, the patient has a flat affect and speaks slowly. You observe a shuffling gait and a resting pill - rolling tremor of his right hand. You also note cogwheel rigidity of his right arm. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate initial medication for the treatment of this patient''s condition?', explanation = 'This patient likely presents with Parkinson disease based on the hallmark symptoms and physical examination findings. First - line medications for Parkinson disease are carbidopa/levodopa, monoamine oxidase - B inhibitors, and nonergot dopamine agonists. Amitriptyline is a tricyclic antidepressant that is commonly used for treatment of depression and neuropathic pain. It is on the Beers Criteria list and must be used with great caution in older patients. Fluoxetine is typically prescribed for major depressive disorder, which is likely not the primary diagnosis in this patient. Furthermore, the Beers Criteria list cautions against prescribing fluoxetine in older patients. Gabapentin is typically used for partial seizures and postherpetic neuralgia. Propranolol hydrochloride is effective for management of essential tremor, but this patient''s clinical picture is more indicative of Parkinson disease.', options = '["Amitriptyline","Carbidopa/levodopa (Sinemet)","Fluoxetine (Prozac)","Gabapentin (Neurontin)","Propranolol hydrochloride"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '01097ff4-68ba-4a32-8d4f-882386a089f8';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 26 - year - old female presents to your clinic because of headache and vision changes. She has also noticed an increase in the size of her hands and feet, changes to her facial features, carpal tunnel symptoms, proximal muscle weakness, fatigue, and menstrua l irregularities. MRI of the brain shows a 7 - mm pituitary adenoma. Which one of the following diagnostic tests is most likely to be abnormal in this patient?', explanation = 'Pituitary adenomas are classified according to their primary cell origin and the specific hormones they produce. Somatotroph adenomas secrete growth hormone and cause symptoms consistent with acromegaly, including an increase in hand and foot size, enlargement of the mandible, carpal tunnel symptoms, fatigue, proximal muscle weakness, and menstrual irregularities. Somatotroph adenomas are diagnosed by a high serum insulin - like growth factor 1 level. Corticotroph adenomas secrete corticotropin (°CTH) and cause symptoms consistent with Cushing disease such as mood changes, weight gain, proximal muscle weakness, easy bruising, and menstrual irregularity. Corticotroph adenomas can be diagnosed by an abnormal result on a dexamethasone suppression test. Lactotroph adenomas secrete prolactin and cause symptoms consistent with hyperprolactinemia such as galactorrhea, decreased libido, and oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea. Lactotroph adenomas can be diagnosed with an elevated serum prolactin level. Thyrotroph adenomas secrete TSH and cause symptoms consistent with hyperthyroidism such as weight loss, palpitations, heat intolerance, and anxiety. Thyrotroph adenomas can be diagnosed with elevated TSH, free T , and total T levels. 4 4', options = '["A dexamethasone suppression test","A serum prolactin level","A TSH level","A serum insulin - like growth factor 1 level"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '9586b73c-807e-43be-aef1-9e34e5b124f6';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An otherwise healthy 52 - year - old female with a past surgical history of hysterectomy for the treatment of uterine fibroids presents with increasing episodes of hot flashes lasting 3 – 5 minutes and occurring 5 – 10 times per day over the past 5 months. She fin ds the symptoms highly disruptive and is interested in options for medical therapy. Which one of the following would be the most effective therapy for this patient''s symptoms?', explanation = 'Oral or transdermal estrogen is the most effective treatment for vasomotor symptoms in menopausal women (SOR A). Antidepressants, including SSRIs and SNRIs, are effective alternatives to hormone therapy for the treatment of vasomotor symptoms in menopause (SOR A). The SSRI paroxetine is FDA approved for this indication. Testosterone therapy is not effective for vasomotor symptoms. Vaginal estrogen cream is recommended for women whose primary symptoms are vaginal rather than vasomotor. Phytoestrogen supplements such as soy have not been shown to consistently improve vasomotor symptoms associated with menopause (SOR B).', options = '["A transdermal estradiol patch (Climara)","Transdermal testosterone gel (AndroGel)","Vaginal estradiol cream (Estrace Vaginal)","Soy phytoestrogen supplementation","Paroxetine (Paxil)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'e387df96-9cd6-4e4a-b61c-39535dada46d';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 45 - year - old female presents with a 1 - year history of central facial erythema, telangiectasias, and inflammatory pustules and papules. The symptoms are worsened by alcohol and excessive sun exposure. You diagnose rosacea. She has not had any previous succ ess with moisturizers, aggressive sun protection, or mild facial soap. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate first step in the management of this condition?', explanation = 'Topical metronidazole is a first - line treatment for rosacea. The cost and side - effect profile of topical metronidazole make it most appropriate. Topical azelaic acid is also a first - line treatment for rosacea. Oral doxycycline is a reasonable next step if topical metronidazole is not successful in managing symptoms. The side - effect profile of doxycycline makes it less desirable than topical metronidazole. Additionally, increased sun sensitivity is a common side effect of doxycycline that is problematic for management because rosacea is generally clinically worse in the warmer months. Laser and light - based therapies are second - line treatments for rosacea. They are reasonable options for patients who have not had success with topical metronidazole or azelaic acid. Brimonidine is an α - 2 agonist that is another reasonable option in a patient who has not had success with topical metronidazole or topical azelaic acid. However, due to its cost and tendency to exacerbate skin irritation, it is considered a second - line treatment option. Topical cyclosporine is another second - line treatment that has been recalcitrant to first - line options.', options = '["Topical brimonidine (Mirvaso)","Topical cyclosporine","Topical metronidazole","Oral doxycycline","Laser or light - based therapy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '09e46ae0-681a-4daf-8384-733a5787429b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 25 - year - old male is brought to the level 1 trauma center with a gunshot wound. He is awake, alert, and oriented, and has full capacity for decision - making. The patient then becomes hemodynamically unstable with a blood pressure of 80/40 mm Hg, a heart ra te of 140 beats/min, and a hemoglobin level of 4.0 g/dL (N 14.0 – 18.0). Whole blood transfusion is indicated, but the patient refuses blood products as he is a practicing Jehovah''s Witness. An advance directive on file at the hospital confirms this. He is a ware that not administering blood will most likely cause his death. You disagree with the patient and would like to administer a whole blood transfusion as his condition is life - threatening. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'When a patient has either an advance directive or demonstrates decision - making capacity, their autonomous refusal of treatment must be respected, even if it leads to adverse medical outcomes or conflicts with the physician''s values or ethical beliefs. Blood refusal directives are considered legally binding and physicians have been found liable for violating religious freedom when violating these directives. Transfusion of blood products may be permissible for patients who are Jehovah''s Witnesses if they are incapacitated and require transfusion but do not have a blood refusal directive or surrogate decision - maker.', options = '["Presenting the case to the ethics committee","Respecting the patient''s wishes by avoiding transfusion","Consulting the patient''s family and administering whole blood with their approval","Administering packed RBCs","Administering whole blood"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'fc1e7787-95d3-43c7-b987-260ad1573c3a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 72 - year - old male presents with a 45 - minute history of persistent bleeding from his left nostril. He has a medical history of aortic stenosis with a mechanical aortic valve replacement, coronary artery disease, hypertension, and type 2 diabetes. His medic ations include hydrochlorothiazide, lisinopril (Zestril), metformin, and warfarin. A physical examination reveals a blood pressure of 170/100 mm Hg without orthostatic change and a heart rate of 90 beats/min. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate first step in the treatment of this patient''s nosebleed?', explanation = 'The initial treatment of a hemodynamically stable patient with epistaxis is to pinch the lower third of the nose for 15 – 20 minutes. If digital compression is not successful in stopping the bleeding and an anterior bleeding site is visualized on anterior rhinoscopy, then the next step would be to either apply topical vasoconstrictors or use chemical/electrical cautery. If bleeding continues after local measures fail, then anterior nasal packing would be indicated. Acute reversal of anticoagulation should be considered in a patient with ongoing bleeding who is hemodynamically unstable.', options = '["Digital compression of the lower nares for 20 minutes","Topical vasoconstrictors","Anterior nasal packing","Electrical cauterization","Reversal of anticoagulation"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'ddfc9cca-73cc-483d-a783-48d75f6e7e3f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An 80 - year - old male presents to your office for follow - up of stable angina. He has a medical history of coronary artery disease with placement of a single drug - eluting stent, and stage 4 chronic kidney disease secondary to hypertension. His most recent ech ocardiogram demonstrated a normal ejection fraction. He does not want additional cardiovascular intervention and prefers you to handle all of his care in the future. The patient’s current medications include the following: Aspirin, 81 mg daily Carvedilol (Coreg), 12.5 mg twice daily Empagliflozin (Jardiance), 10 mg daily Losartan (Cozaar), 50 mg daily On examination he has a blood pressure of 140/85 mm Hg, a heart rate of 52 beats/min, and an oxygen saturation of 98≥ on room air. A cardiopulmonary examination is within normal limits and an EKG is unchanged from past EKGs. Which one of the following changes to this patient’s medication regimen would be most appropriate to decrease his anginal symptoms?', explanation = 'β - Blockers, calcium channel blockers, and long - acting nitrates are first - line medications to decrease symptoms in patients with angina. If symptoms persist despite the use of a maximally tolerated dose of a single first - line medication, an additional drug from a different class should be introduced. Adding isosorbide mononitrate is the most appropriate option for this patient; however, it may decrease his blood pressure and will require close attention on follow - up. Ranolazine is another potential recommendation but is often more costly than alternatives. It is recommended in patients who are already taking medications from 2 other classes. Increasing the patient''s carvedilol is not recommended due to his relative bradycardia. Neither increasing empagliflozin nor adding clopidogrel helps to decrease anginal symptoms. Ivabradine is contraindicated in patients with chronic coronary disease and normal ejection fraction and is potentially harmful.', options = '["Increasing carvedilol","Increasing empagliflozin","Adding clopidogrel (Plavix)","Adding isosorbide mononitrate","Adding ivabradine (Corlanor)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'ab4d68aa-55f5-45db-a827-2f1fb384e232';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 35 - year - old female presents because of a 4 - week history of difficulty sleeping following the death of her partner of 2 years. She has difficulty initiating and maintaining sleep and reports daytime sleepiness. Her symptoms have not improved despite atten ding grief counseling sessions. She requests nonpharmacologic treatment for her insomnia. Which one of the following is a component of sleep hygiene education for cognitive behavioral therapy for insomnia?', explanation = 'Acute insomnia is a sleep continuity disturbance, defined as difficulty initiating and/or maintaining sleep, that occurs ≥3 days per week with a duration of 1 week to 3 months. It is often associated with a precipitating factor such as life events or psychological distress. The first step in the management of acute insomnia is identifying and treating the underlying cause. Cognitive behavioral therapy for insomnia (CBT - I) is an effective treatment for insomnia and may be offered as first - line therapy, especially in patients who wish to avoid pharmacotherapy. CBT - I has 3 categories: sleep hygiene education, sleep restriction, and stimulus control. Waking up at the same time every day and not napping during the day are among the 8 components of sleep hygiene education. Stimulus control strategies include going to bed only when sleepy and reserving the bedroom for sleep and sex. Sleep restriction techniques involve reducing time spent in bed followed by gradually increasing it by 15 minutes each week once sleep efficiency reaches 90≥.', options = '["Decreasing time spent in bed","Increasing daytime napping","Waking up at the same time every day","Placing a digital clock next to the bed"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '217cf443-9565-4db7-8f98-8ce7018bcb95';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 32 - year - old female presents with classic symptoms of mild hypothyroidism including cold intolerance, mild fatigue, and constipation. Her TSH level is 6.0 μ U/mL (N 0.4 – 4.2) and her level is within normal limits. A pregnancy test is negative. free T 4 Which one of the following factors, if present, would be an indication for prescribing levothyroxine (Synthroid)?', explanation = 'Hypothyroidism affects approximately 1 in 300 individuals in the United States, with a higher prevalence among women and older adults. Symptoms can range from mild to life - threatening. Because the signs and symptoms of hypothyroidism can be nonspecific, diagnosis is based on blood levels of TSH and free T . Subclinical hypothyroidism is defined 4 by a TSH level that is abnormal but <10 μU/mL while the free T level remains within the normal range. Nonpregnant patients with subclinical hypothyroidism should not be treated with thyroid hormone replacement therapy unless the thyroid peroxidase antibody level is elevated or the TSH level is >10 μU/mL (SOR A). level is not routinely indicated. Treatment - resistant Evaluating the total or free T depression is an indication for treating subclinical hypothyroidism; however, this is not the case for treatment - resistant constipation.', options = '["A repeat TSH level in 4 – 6 weeks remains at 6.0 μ U/mL","A repeat TSH level in 4 – 6 weeks increases to 8.0 μ U/mL","An elevated free T level 3","An elevated thyroid peroxidase antibody level","Treatment - resistant constipation"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'c6034a9b-e9f2-4046-b55d-3e7a5d89f3f5';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An otherwise healthy 15 - year - old female presents for evaluation of a 7 - month history of heavy menstrual bleeding. Her periods are 10 days long, irregular, and require 10 tampons per day. She sometimes passes large clots. Other than some fatigue, she feels well today and her vital signs are normal. A point - of - care hemoglobin level is 10.2 g/dL (N 12.0 – 16.0). Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in evaluation?', explanation = 'Heavy menstrual bleeding (HMB) is very common in adolescents and may be a sign of an underlying bleeding disorder. Although bleeding disorders affect 1≥ – 2≥ of the general population, the prevalence increases to 20≥ among adolescent girls with heavy menstrual bleeding. Platelet dysfunction and von Willebrand disease are most commonly identified. Evaluation for bleeding disorders is indicated when there is frequent pad or tampon use (>1 every 1 – 2 hours); menstrual bleeding lasting longer than 7 days; passage of clots larger than 1 inch in diameter; a personal history of anemia treatment, excessive bleeding with tooth extraction or surgery, or excessive bruising; or a family history of a bleeding disorder. The initial workup for HMB in an adolescent includes a CBC; a prothrombin time, partial thromboplastin time, and INR; a von Willebrand panel; and hCG, ferritin, fibrinogen, and TSH levels. Testing for chlamydia and gonorrhea should be considered in sexually active patients. Testosterone, prolactin, and DHEA levels should be obtained if there are signs of polycystic ovary syndrome or other endocrine disorders. Levels of FSH, LH, estrogen, and progesterone are not helpful in the evaluation of excessive uterine bleeding. Pelvic imaging is not routinely necessary but should be considered for HMB that does not respond to initial management. Hormonal contraceptives and tranexamic acid may be used for the treatment of HMB, but workup for a bleeding disorder is the most important first step.', options = '["Testing for a bleeding disorder","FSH and LH levels","Estrogen and progesterone levels","Pelvic ultrasonography","Pelvic MRI"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '3b2363fa-fa9d-4b23-8f84-4f5e5aacb5a2';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 65 - year - old male presents to your clinic with symptoms of flashing lights and increased floaters in his left eye. He does not have any pain, and he has no past medical history. His vital signs are normal. His visual acuity is at baseline when wearing his glasses, and you note a visual field defect on the left. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', explanation = 'Family physicians frequently evaluate ophthalmologic symptoms and should be familiar with conditions requiring emergent evaluation. Peripheral flashing lights and floaters are common symptoms of retinal detachment. This patient should be referred for urgent ophthalmologic evaluation including a dilated fundoscopic examination. While positive and negative visual features are seen with migraine with aura, these features should be transient and followed by a headache typical of migraine. New - onset migraine in a 65 - year - old is also uncommon and would require further evaluation. Central retinal artery occlusion, often ischemic or thromboembolic, typically occurs in those with risk factors such as diabetes mellitus, vascular disease, and tobacco use. Rapid, painless vision loss is often accompanied by afferent pupillary defect and the lesion can be visualized on a dilated fundoscopic examination as a cherry - red spot. Globe rupture is unlikely to occur without a history of trauma. Acute ischemic stroke may cause vision loss but is unlikely to cause ocular symptoms of flashing lights and floaters.', options = '["Migraine with aura","Central retinal artery occlusion","Retinal detachment","Globe rupture","Acute ischemic stroke"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '350a6b6d-5b69-4f7d-96fe-aa26bf358d44';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 67 - year - old female presents for a wellness examination. She has not been seen for medical care for several years and reports that her last Papanicolaou test was 15 years ago. She does not recall any medical problems and has no known history of abnormal c ervical cytology in the past. According to the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force, which one of the following should you recommend regarding further cervical cancer screening?', explanation = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommends against cervical cancer screening in women older than 65 years only if they have had adequate prior screening. Adequate screening is defined as 3 consecutive negative cytology results or 2 consecutive negative co - testing results within 10 years before stopping screening, with the most recent test occurring within 5 years. Because this patient has not had adequate prior screening, she requires either 2 consecutive negative co - testing results that are 5 years apart or 3 consecutive negative cytology results that are 3 years apart before stopping screening.', options = '["No further screening due to the patient''s age","Cervical cytology alone now, with no further screening if the result is normal","Cervical cytology alone now, then repeated in 3 years with no further screening if the results are normal","Cervical cytology with HPV co - testing now, with no further screening if the results are normal","Cervical cytology with HPV co - testing now, then repeated in 5 years with no further screening if the results are normal"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '5253e462-4d60-46fa-86f0-1b1853efbca5';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 46 - year - old male comes in for an acute visit for low back pain. During triage, a Patient Health Questionnaire – 2 (PHQ - 2) screen is positive. You then administer the PHQ - 9. You ask, "Over the last 2 weeks, how often have you been bothered by thoughts that you would be better off dead, or of hurting yourself- He responds, "Nearly every day." His total PHQ - 9 score is 19. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'Suicidal ideation is much more common than suicide attempts or suicide completions and should be carefully addressed; up to half of patients characterized as low risk ultimately complete suicide. Current recommendations for evaluating suicidal ideation suggest focusing on individual assessment and understanding certain risk factors that may exacerbate suicidal ideation for a given patient. This includes asking questions, such as whether the patient has a plan and means to complete the plan, as well as assessing for underlying mental illness, substance use, and life stressors. SSRIs and cognitive behavioral therapy are first - line treatments for the majority of people with depression and suicidality, but this patient requires further evaluation for suicide risk before initiating pharmacologic therapy. Lithium has been shown to decrease suicide attempts and all - cause mortality among patients with major depression and bipolar disorder, and SSRIs are often used in conjunction with lithium; however, an underlying diagnosis has not yet been established for this patient, so this treatment is not yet warranted. The use of ketamine for rapid improvement in depression has shown promise, with patients experiencing significant improvement in depression symptoms and suicidality within 24 hours, but the evidence quality is considered low, and effects dissipated after 2 weeks. Ketamine treatment is recommended only if depression is resistant to other medications. If the patient endorses suicide plans or any other factors that are consistent with high risk for suicide completion, transfer to an inpatient treatment facility may be indicated. Although, stabilization in a standard emergency department is often necessary while awaiting an inpatient bed due to facility limitations.', options = '["Suicidal ideation assessment and evaluation of risk factors for suicide completion","Escitalopram (Lexapro), and cognitive behavioral therapy","Escitalopram plus lithium, and cognitive behavioral therapy","Intravenous ketamine","Transportation to the emergency department"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'f9dd92b6-3088-4442-9475-1e75b2727996';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A healthy 58 - year - old patient presents for an annual health maintenance examination. They had an initial screening colonoscopy 3 years ago in which 2 polyps were removed. The polyps were found to be 6 - mm and 8 - mm tubular adenomas. The patient does not have a family history of colon cancer. Which one of the following is the most appropriate ongoing colon cancer screening for this patient?', explanation = 'For average - risk patients with 1 – 2 tubular adenomas <10 mm in size found on screening colonoscopy, repeat colonoscopy in 7 – 10 years is recommended. The risk of small adenomas progressing to malignancy is quite low and the rate of progression is slow, likely >10 years. Using GRADE (Grading of Recommendations Assessment, Development, and Evaluation) criteria in its consensus guidelines from 2020, the U.S. Multi - Society Task Force on Colorectal Cancer recommends follow - up in 7 – 10 years for 1 – 2 tubular adenomas <10 mm in size (moderate - quality evidence), 3 – 5 years for 3 – 4 tubular adenomas <10 mm in size (very low - quality evidence), 3 years for 5 – 10 tubular adenomas <10 mm in size (moderate - quality evidence), and yearly for >10 adenomas (very low - quality evidence). In the United States, only colonoscopy is recommended for follow - up of findings of colonic polyps. International guidelines allow for stool - based testing. This patient is healthy, and colon cancer screening should continue until at least age 75 (SOR A).', options = '["No further follow - up","Fecal immunochemical testing (FIT) now","Stool DNA testing (Cologuard) now","Repeat colonoscopy within the next 2 years","Repeat colonoscopy 7 – 10 years after the initial colonoscopy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '31118905-6460-4f35-959a-b5f87fe1d27a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 27 - year - old gravida 1 para 0 at 38 weeks'' estimated gestation based on a first - trimester ultrasound presents for routine prenatal care. Her pregnancy has been uncomplicated. You discuss the potential risks and benefits of inducing labor at 39 weeks compa red to expectant management. In this discussion, you should tell the patient that inducing labor at 39 weeks reduces', explanation = 'The 2018 ARRIVE (A Randomized Trial of Induction Versus Expectant Management) trial was a randomized, controlled trial that included more than 6000 low - risk nulliparous patients at 41 sites across the United States who were assigned to either induction of labor (IOL) between 39 weeks 0/7 days and 39 weeks 4/7 days or expectant management. The results showed no significant differences in a neonatal composite outcome, including perinatal mortality and severe perinatal morbidity between the intervention and control groups (4.3≥ compared to 5.4≥, relative risk [RR] 0.80, 95≥ CI 0.64 to 1.00). A significantly lower rate of cesarean delivery was found in the intervention group than the control group (18.6≥ compared to 22.2≥, RR 0.84, 95≥ CI 0.76 to 0.93). Other findings included: lower rates of gestational hypertension and preeclampsia (9.1≥ compared to 14.1≥, RR 0.64, 95≥ CI 0.56 to 0.74), increased length of stay in the labor and delivery unit (a median duration of 20 hours with an interquartile range [IQR] of 13 to 28 compared to a median duration of 14 hours with an IQR of 9 to 20), and reduced need for neonatal respiratory support within the first 72 hours of life (3.0≥ compared to 4.2≥, RR 0.71, 95≥ CI 0.55 to 0.93). The intervention group had significantly lower median birth weights than the control group (3300 g compared to 3380 g; P value <0.001); it did not reduce the risk of low infant birth weight. There were no significant differences in neonatal ICU admission and maternal risk of postpartum hemorrhage. This information should be shared with patients as part of a shared decision - making conversation regarding timing of delivery. Not all labor and delivery units can accommodate elective IOL at 39 weeks'' gestation for all patients. It is important that clinicians and hospital systems assess their policies and procedures on a regular basis to ensure equitable access to IOL for those who choose this approach.', options = '["the risk of low birth weight","length of stay in the labor and delivery unit","risk for neonatal ICU admission","the rate of cesarean delivery","the risk of postpartum hemorrhage"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'cc1aad84-fab9-44d0-9f71-f75c04fe3c8e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 75 - year - old female presents to your office with a 1 - year history of gradually worsening right - sided groin pain on standing. The pain improves with rest. These symptoms have been marginally relieved with ibuprofen and acetaminophen, but her use of these m edications has been limited by gastric irritation. A physical examination is most notable for pain in the groin with passive flexion, adduction, and internal rotation (FADIR) testing. Which one of the following treatments would be most helpful in relieving her symptoms?', explanation = 'This patient presents with hip osteoarthritis. Intra - articular corticosteroid injections have been shown to relieve hip and osteoarthritis pain for at least 4 months. In addition to pain relief, these injections may improve activity levels and quality of life. In contrast to intra - articular corticosteroid injections, intra - articular hyaluronic acid injections have not been shown to be substantially beneficial in relieving symptoms of hip osteoarthritis. Topical lidocaine patches have not been shown to be effective for management of pain due to hip osteoarthritis and are not a sustainable solution for this patient. Opioids such as hydrocodone are advised against for treatment of chronic osteoarthritis. They are not effective over the long term, have significant side effects, and carry a high risk of addiction and misuse. Tramadol is not effective for pain relief or functional improvement in hip osteoarthritis and carries similar risks as opioids.', options = '["A topical lidocaine patch (Lidoderm)","Hydrocodone","Tramadol","Intra - articular corticosteroid injection","Intra - articular hyaluronic acid injection"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '1298c9b5-8a92-4e20-972b-7bdbd7f14047';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 65 - year - old male is brought to the emergency department by his wife after developing confusion immediately after sexual intercourse. The wife reports that the patient does not remember anything from a few hours prior to the onset of symptoms. He repeated ly asks where he is, how he got here, and what time it is, despite having been given the answers to his questions. He is alert and knows his wife, his name, and his birth date. A neurologic examination is otherwise normal. A CBC and comprehensive metabolic panel are normal, an EKG is normal, and a CT scan of the head is unremarkable. It has now been 2 hours since the onset of his symptoms. Which one of the following would be most appropriate for treatment?', explanation = 'This patient has transient global amnesia (TGA), which is characterized by the abrupt onset of anterograde amnesia without other neurologic deficits or cognitive impairment. TGA can be triggered by intense physical or psychological stress such as sexual intercourse or acute illness. Symptoms usually resolve within approximately 6 hours. No intervention is indicated for TGA other than reassurance. The etiology of TGA is unrelated to seizure, TIA, or stroke. Anticoagulants, antiplatelet medications, antiseizure medications, and thrombolytic therapy are not indicated in the treatment of TGA.', options = '["Observation and reassurance","Oral apixaban (Eliquis)","Oral aspirin and clopidogrel (Plavix)","Intravenous lorazepam (Ativan)","Intravenous thrombolytic therapy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'a0ae09b4-7138-4a32-9706-7f82c5fc54ee';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 55 - year - old male presents to the urgent care clinic with a 24 - hour history of worsening fever, chills, and body aches. He tells you that he discovered a tick on his scalp during a camping trip last week. He does not have a rash, headache, or palpitations , and a neurologic examination is negative. A Lyme enzyme immunoassay and confirmatory Western blot are positive. When he has taken doxycycline in the past, he has developed headaches, severe nausea, and vomiting. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment option for this patient?', explanation = 'In the United States, multiple diseases are carried by ticks including Lyme disease, Rocky Mountain spotted fever, ehrlichiosis, anaplasmosis, and Colorado tick fever. Tick - borne illnesses should be considered in patients who present with influenza - like symptoms during the spring and summer months and who have spent time outdoors. Lyme disease can be diagnosed clinically in patients with erythema migrans (SOR C). In patients such as this who present without a rash, a 2 - tiered testing regimen is recommended. Doxycycline is the preferred first - line treatment, but for patients who are pregnant or do not tolerate it, an appropriate alternative is amoxicillin, 500 mg 3 times daily for 14 – 21 days. It is important to prescribe a medication that the patient can tolerate for its full course, as partial treatment of the infection could lead to more serious complications. Cefuroxime axetil is another treatment option. Intravenous ceftriaxone is indicated for patients with Lyme disease who present with late neurologic manifestations, but that is not the case for this patient. Chloramphenicol is the preferred treatment for Rocky Mountain spotted fever in patients with contraindications to doxycycline therapy.', options = '["Amoxicillin","Ceftriaxone","Chloramphenicol","Doxycycline plus promethazine"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'ad94a903-2c27-4597-945a-513879ed59af';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 66 - year - old female asks about options for shingles vaccine. She received the live zoster vaccine (Zostavax) previously. She underwent urgent cholecystectomy for acute cholecystitis 2 months ago and developed shingles in a dermatomal distribution soon aft er hospital discharge. She was given valacyclovir (Valtrex) and gabapentin (Neurontin) for treatment and symptom relief. The rash is gone but she still has mild postherpetic neuralgia. She would like to receive the recombinant zoster vaccine (Shingrix) as soon as it is safe to receive it. Which one of the following would be the earliest this patient can safely receive the first dose of recombinant zoster vaccine?', explanation = 'The recombinant zoster vaccine (RZV) is recommended for healthy adults ≥50 years of age, and this patient can receive it today. Because most studies of RZV effectiveness have excluded patients with a prior episode of shingles, direct evidence in this subgroup is limited; however, available data and expert reviews support vaccination after a prior episode because the risk for recurrence remains and RZV is safe and immunogenic. The CDC recommends that patients wait until the zoster rash has resolved prior to receiving RZV, but it is not necessary to wait until postherpetic neuralgia has resolved. Patients who have previously received live zoster vaccine should receive RZV as well.', options = '["Today","After resolution of the postherpetic neuralgia","12 months after her episode of shingles","Never"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '1145cbc6-57ed-46c0-ba9f-87ccdf11b039';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 40 - year - old male presents to the office with a 2 - day history of right eye pain associated with redness and swelling. He does not wear contact lenses. Pertinent findings on a physical examination include a temperature of 37.3 °C (99.1 °F), visual acuity o f 20/70 in the right eye and 20/20 in the left eye, erythema and edema of the right eyelid, and pain with extraocular movements. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'This patient''s unilateral orbital swelling, erythema, pain with extraocular movements, and decreased visual acuity are concerning for orbital cellulitis. Prompt recognition and early treatment are vital to avoid worsening outcomes associated with this ocular emergency. A patient who presents in the outpatient setting with clinical findings that are suspicious for orbital cellulitis should be promptly directed to the emergency department (ED) for expedited evaluation and anticipated hospitalization for urgent ophthalmology consultation and broad - spectrum intravenous antibiotics, if the diagnosis is confirmed. CT with intravenous contrast is the imaging modality of choice, although MRI is an alternative. Ordering noncontrast CT would potentially yield a less accurate diagnosis and could delay definitive treatment. Same - day outpatient evaluation by an ophthalmologist would cause a diagnostic delay, compared to transfer to the ED. Symptomatic treatment with warm compresses and close outpatient follow - up would cause a treatment delay with a risk of further clinical deterioration. Empiric treatment with an oral antibiotic would not provide adequate initial treatment of the infection compared to hospitalization for intravenous antibiotic treatment and closer clinical monitoring.', options = '["Frequent warm, moist compresses, and follow - up tomorrow","Empiric treatment with an oral antibiotic","A same - day evaluation with an ophthalmologist","Noncontrast CT of the orbits and sinuses","Transfer to the emergency department"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '819e8be2-f0ea-4962-b117-834b623af748';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 63 - year - old male presents with a 2 - day history of right lower extremity edema and pain. He has a past medical history of hypertension, stage 4 chronic kidney disease, and type 2 diabetes, for which he takes insulin. His last glomerular filtration rate wa s 22 mL/min/1.73 m . He does not report any trauma, chest pain, or shortness of breath. On examination he has a weight of 70 kg (154 lb) and the remainder of his vital signs are within normal limits. Examination of his right lower extremity reveals erythema, tenderness, and 2+ edema at the back of the knee. A Doppler venous duplex ultrasound of the right thigh shows a noncompressible right femoral vein. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient’s condition?', explanation = 'This patient has an acute deep vein thrombosis (DVT) with no evidence of pulmonary embolism. Outpatient treatment would be appropriate and a low - molecular - weight heparin such as enoxaparin is a reasonable option in this patient. Renal dosing is the reason for daily, rather than twice - daily, dosing for enoxaparin. Dabigatran is not preferred due to a higher risk for bleeding. Direct oral anticoagulants such as rivaroxaban are not appropriate in this patient due to his glomerular filtration rate <30 mL/min/1.73 m . Furthermore, the initial dose of rivaroxaban, 15 mg twice daily, should be 21 days, not 14 days. Warfarin is not recommended for the acute phase treatment of DVT in this patient. Admission for intravenous heparin is generally not indicated for uncomplicated DVT.', options = '["Oral dabigatran (Pradaxa), 75 mg twice daily","Oral rivaroxaban (Xarelto), 15 mg twice daily for 14 days, then 20 mg daily","Oral warfarin, 5 mg daily","Subcutaneous enoxaparin (Lovenox), 70 mg daily","Admission for intravenous heparin"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '8fa56a09-67cd-4f22-b23d-a398591302b7';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 65 - year - old male presents to your office with a 4 - month history of ill - defined lower pelvic pain. He is afebrile. An abdominal examination is unremarkable. A digital rectal examination yields a boggy prostate with moderate tenderness. Urinalysis is posit ive for leukocyte esterase and 10 – 20 WBCs/hpf, and testing for common sexually transmitted infections is negative. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', explanation = 'This patient has chronic bacterial prostatitis (CBP) and should be treated with a fluoroquinolone. Fluoroquinolones are the first - line treatment for CBP because they favorably cover the common uropathogens that cause CBP, penetrate prostatic tissue well, and have high oral bioavailability. Amoxicillin and ceftriaxone are not preferred for the treatment of prostatitis. CT is not necessary to make the diagnosis. Referral to a urologist is unnecessary in this clinical scenario because the diagnosis and management of CBP is within the scope of family medicine.', options = '["Amoxicillin","Ceftriaxone","Ciprofloxacin","CT of the abdomen and pelvis","Referral to a urologist"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'b06bc9cb-5e31-4e91-b382-63d7502fe80d';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 25 - year - old male presents to the emergency department with a sudden onset of right - sided chest pain that started about 2 hours ago while he was resting and playing video games. He reports feeling slightly short of breath. He has no history of lung diseas e, and he smokes 1 pack of cigarettes per day. On examination he has a blood pressure of 120/80 mm Hg, a heart rate of 115 beats/min, a respiratory rate of 20/min, and an oxygen saturation of 90≥ on room air. A chest x - ray reveals a pneumothorax involving <10≥ of the lung space. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', explanation = 'For patients who are stable with a small (<15≥ of the hemithoracic cavity) primary pneumothorax, conservative management with initiation of oxygen via nasal cannula and observation for at least 6 hours is recommended, followed by a repeat chest x - ray to assess for stability in size of the pneumothorax. If stable at 6 hours, patients can return home with a repeat follow - up in 24 hours. CT imaging can aid in diagnosis if the initial chest x - ray is nondiagnostic or equivocal; however, it is not needed to confirm definitive findings of pneumothorax on chest x - ray. Patients who are clinically unstable with a large pneumothorax or severe symptoms should receive emergent needle decompression, followed by an ipsilateral tube thoracostomy.', options = '["Reassurance and discharge home with return precautions for worsening symptoms","Initiation of oxygen via nasal cannula, and a repeat chest x - ray in 6 hours","CT of the chest to verify x - ray findings","Emergent needle decompression at the right second intercostal space in the anterior midclavicular line","Placement of a chest tube at the right fourth or fifth intercostal space in the midaxillary to anterior axillary line"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '5dbe3207-934a-4c51-a117-7c255a65000e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 4 - year - old male presents with a 6 - day history of fever, rash, and an enlarged lymph node. On examination, you note erythema of the lips, bilateral conjunctivitis, and a diffuse maculopapular rash on the trunk and extremities. The right anterior cervical lymph node is nontender and 2 cm in size. Which one of the following is the most serious complication of this patient''s condition?', explanation = 'This patient presents with Kawasaki disease, which commonly occurs in children <5 years of age. Classic Kawasaki disease presents with 4 of the following features: oral mucous membrane changes, bilateral conjunctivitis, diffuse rash, hand and foot edema, and unilateral cervical adenopathy ≥1.5 cm. Inflammation occurs and can affect multiple organ systems. The most serious complication is cardiac. If untreated, 15≥ – 25≥ of patients will develop cardiovascular abnormalities, including coronary artery dilation, aortic root dilation, cardiac aneurysms, tachycardia, hypotension, and shock. Echocardiography must be performed as soon as possible. Less serious complications of Kawasaki disease include anemia, elevated liver function test results, pyuria, and pulmonary edema.', options = '["Cardiac","Hematologic","Hepatic","Pulmonary","Renal"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '35ff5a7d-fe1f-44fd-bc85-6fb5c3f85fb5';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 17 - year - old female with well - controlled diabetes mellitus is brought to your office by her mother for a sports preparticipation physical evaluation prior to playing soccer. She has intermittent knee pain when running but no other symptoms. Which one of the following, if present in this patient, would be a CONTRAINDICATION to playing soccer?', explanation = 'A sports preparticipation evaluation is important for assessing health risks and ensuring an athlete is not unnecessarily restricted from play. An athlete with an acutely enlarged spleen or liver faces an increased risk of organ rupture during contact sports. This patient should be evaluated for a cause of the organomegaly, if present, prior to participation. Obesity in an athlete increases the risk for heat - related illness, but it is not an indication to restrict play. Exercise is beneficial for adolescents with diabetes mellitus and may require modification of insulin and eating regimens. Asymptomatic mild mitral valve prolapse is not a reason to deny participation. Tibial tubercle apophysitis is not a contraindication to play, and most experts encourage activity and conservative management.', options = '["A BMI >30 kg/m","An enlarged spleen","Insulin - dependent diabetes","Mitral valve prolapse","Tibial tubercle apophysitis"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'd62f9c16-ec7a-4b0c-8ba3-085c15f2ab42';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An otherwise healthy 26 - year - old female presents to your clinic with a history of 3 episodes of vertigo occurring over the last week. Each episode lasts for several hours. During the episodes, she notes fullness in the right ear with tinnitus and hearing l oss. She has not noticed anything specific that triggers the episodes, and reports consuming 1 glass of wine per night. She does not report headache, visual changes, fever, or upper respiratory symptoms. She is currently asymptomatic and a physical examina tion is unremarkable. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'Meniere disease is characterized by spontaneous recurring episodes of vertigo with associated unilateral hearing loss, tinnitus, and nystagmus. Even though there are no specific diagnostic tests, audiometry should be performed in patients suspected of having this condition. Sensorineural hearing loss may or may not be present on audiometric evaluation. Acute attacks should be treated with medication such as promethazine, diazepam, or prochlorperazine to suppress vestibular function. Lifestyle interventions, including salt restriction and reduction in alcohol and caffeine intake, have traditionally been recommended. However, there is no sufficient evidence to support these recommendations. The Epley maneuver is a repositioning treatment used for benign paroxysmal positional vertigo and not Meniere disease. There is no good - quality evidence that diuretics, antivirals, or corticosteroids treat or prevent Meniere disease.', options = '["Recommending a reduction in alcohol intake","Performing the Epley maneuver","Ordering audiometry","Initiating oral hydrochlorothiazide, 25 mg daily","Initiating oral prednisone, 20 mg daily for 5 days"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '0c142ccd-fc98-485f-a19a-e2e42e4f333a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A new lipid - lowering drug is being evaluated for its cardioprotective effects. The event rate for acute myocardial infarction is 0.085 in the low - intensity treatment group and 0.045 in the high - intensity treatment group, yielding an absolute risk reduction (ARR) of 0.04. Which one of the following is the number needed to treat (NNT)?', explanation = 'The number needed to treat (NNT) is the number of patients who need to receive a particular treatment in order for 1 patient to benefit. The NNT is the inverse of the absolute risk reduction (ARR), the amount by which a particular treatment reduces the risk of a negative outcome. The ARR must be calculated first in order to determine the NNT. To calculate the ARR, the experimental event rate (EER) is subtracted from the control event rate (CER). In this example, the low - intensity treatment group had a risk of acute myocardial infarction (bad outcome) of 0.085 (CER) whereas the high - intensity treatment group had a risk of 0.045 (EER). This would make the equation: 0.085 – 0.045 = an ARR of 0.04. The NNT is then calculated by dividing 1 by the ARR: 1 / 0.04 = 25. This means that 25 patients would need to receive the high - intensity treatment to prevent 1 additional myocardial infarction.', options = '["<1","25","40","50"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'd0a560fb-88a9-43c5-8d7c-027a715cfa71';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 75 - year - old female presents to your office with a 3 - month history of episodes of lightheadedness on standing. Orthostatic blood pressure testing in your office reveals an initial blood pressure of 134/76 mm Hg that drops to 104/46 mm Hg on standing. A la boratory evaluation is unremarkable and review of her medications does not show an obvious cause for her symptoms. Echocardiography and tilt table testing are unremarkable. You diagnose orthostatic hypotension. Monotherapy with which one of the following would be indicated for the management of this patient''s neurogenic orthostatic hypotension?', explanation = 'Midodrine has been found to be the safest and best - tolerated medication for the management of neurogenic orthostatic hypotension (SOR B). Atomoxetine is an adjunctive treatment for neurogenic orthostatic hypotension that is generally successful when added to medication such as midodrine, but it is not effective as monotherapy. Although fludrocortisone is sometimes used off - label for this indication, it should be used with caution because of the risk of left ventricular hypertrophy, renal failure, and hypokalemia. Methylphenidate has not been shown to have a role in the successful treatment of neurogenic orthostatic hypotension. Treatment with sodium tablets is usually inadequate, does not correct the neurogenic issue, and substantially increases the risk of hypernatremia and resultant renal injury.', options = '["Atomoxetine (Strattera)","Fludrocortisone","Methylphenidate (Ritalin)","Midodrine","Sodium bicarbonate"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '50557ac6-13ba-4392-a480-c7427f2a6e69';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 22 - year - old female with a past medical history of type 1 diabetes presents to the emergency department with multiple bouts of vomiting. She says that she is not consistently adherent to her insulin regimen. She has a plasma glucose level of 350 mg/dL, el evated ketones, and high anion gap metabolic acidosis. Treatment for diabetic ketoacidosis is initiated with intravenous fluids and insulin therapy. Glucose should be added to this patient’s saline infusion when her plasma glucose levels reach which one of the following ranges?', explanation = 'The mainstay of treatment for diabetic ketoacidosis is intravenous fluid replacement and insulin therapy along with careful monitoring and frequent reassessment. Once plasma glucose levels reach 201 – 250 mg/dL, glucose should be added to the saline infusion to maintain plasma glucose levels in the 150 – 200 mg/dL range. Because acidosis and ketosis resolve more slowly than hyperglycemia, glucose needs to be added while insulin and saline therapy are continued.', options = '["<150 mg/dL","150 – 200 mg/dL","201 – 250 mg/dL","251 – 300 mg/dL","301 – 350 mg/dL"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '4a1d99dc-ea85-48e6-b9af-eb388abd2e0c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 32 - year - old female with a recent diagnosis of posttraumatic stress disorder presents to your clinic with difficulty sleeping. She recently left an abusive relationship and has been attending trauma - focused psychotherapy. She has found the psychotherapy h elpful, but she continues to experience midsleep awakening due to hyperarousal and nightmares. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?', explanation = 'Prazosin is an α - agonist that decreases sympathetic nervous tone during sleep and has been found to be helpful for midsleep awakening due to hyperarousal and nightmares in patients with posttraumatic stress disorder. Amitriptyline, mirtazapine, and risperidone have significant side - effect profiles and would not be appropriate initial treatments for this patient''s sleep symptoms. Temazepam is a benzodiazepine and should be avoided if possible due to its potential for misuse and chronic long - term effects.', options = '["Amitriptyline","Mirtazapine (Remeron)","Prazosin","Risperidone (Risperdal)","Temazepam (Restoril)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'a3b8620b-f360-43d5-9572-2636f78aee2b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 58 - year - old female with type 2 diabetes controlled on metformin recently underwent bariatric surgery. Today, she reports feeling off balance and having a burning sensation in her bilateral hands and feet that is worse at night. She reports difficulty amb ulating and has fallen several times over the past few weeks. She has intermittent nausea, vomiting, and confusion, and reports aches and pains all over. A physical examination is significant for absent patellar and Achilles reflexes. Her strength is 4/5 i n the bilateral lower extremities with decreased pinprick sensation. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', explanation = 'This patient presents with a symmetrical peripheral neuropathy with sensory and motor components that are characteristic of beriberi caused by vitamin B deficiency. Risk 1 factors include alcohol use, bariatric surgery, older age, diabetes mellitus, and HIV infection. Severe thiamine deficiency can lead to heart failure. Blood and urine tests for thiamine levels are recommended to confirm the diagnosis. Diabetic peripheral neuropathy usually presents as a symmetric polyneuropathy, but it does not usually involve motor components, except in severe cases. Neurologic manifestations of Lyme disease include meningitis, facial nerve palsy, radiculoneuritis with radicular pain in a dermatomal distribution with accompanied weakness, sensory deficits, abnormal reflexes, other cranial neuropathies, and Lyme encephalomyelitis. Peripheral neuropathy is rare with Lyme disease and typically presents as a mononeuropathy, not a polyneuropathy. Myalgic encephalomyelitis/chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS) typically occurs after an acute infection, presenting with symptoms such as severe fatigue, sleep changes, and cognitive changes that are exacerbated by physical activity. ME/CFS is not associated with peripheral neuropathy. Secondary syphilis typically presents with a rash and constitutional symptoms. Neurologic symptoms associated with secondary syphilis include ocular symptoms and otosyphilis with vertigo, tinnitus, and hearing loss. Secondary syphilis is not associated with peripheral neuropathy.', options = '["Diabetic peripheral neuropathy","Lyme disease","Myalgic encephalomyelitis/chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS)","Secondary syphilis","Vitamin B deficiency (beriberi)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '4bcd79dd-b1c0-4a88-8011-b483deffe94b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 76 - year - old female with a past medical history of hypertension and major depressive disorder presents because of acute right knee pain that began after she sustained a mechanical fall and landed on her knee while taking a walk near her house yesterday. S he was able to walk home without difficulty. She applied ice to the area after the fall, but her knee was more painful this morning. When asked to point to the pain, she points to an area lateral to the inferior patella. Examination of the knee reveals no redness or swelling but minor warmth over the anterior knee. Lower extremity sensation is intact. The patient has full range of motion with pain. There is no tenderness of the patella or the fibular head with palpation. P rovocative testing including an Apley grind test, a McMurray test, a Lachman test, and anterior and posterior drawer tests is negative. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step to aid in diagnosis?', explanation = 'According to the Ottawa knee rules, a well - validated tool used to limit unnecessary radiography, a knee x - ray is indicated in this patient to rule out fracture because she is ≥55 years of age. Radiography is currently the preferred modality over ultrasonography for diagnosing a fracture in an adult. Because ligament and meniscal testing is negative, MRI is not indicated. Arthrocentesis with culture and Gram stain would be indicated if the history and physical examination suggest an infection of the joint space.', options = '["No further testing or imaging","Ultrasonography","Radiography","MRI","Arthrocentesis with culture and Gram stain"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '277c0aee-43fe-4771-85be-af2741715aa0';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 31 - year - old gravida 3 para 2 at 8 weeks'' gestation presents to the urgent care clinic because of a 2 - day history of headache and fever. This morning she removed an engorged tick from her leg. On examination she is ill appearing but alert and interactive. An HEENT examination is normal and there is no pain with neck flexion. A cardiopulmonary examination is normal. There is no rash. You suspect Rocky Mountain spotted fever. In addition to supportive care, which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?', explanation = 'Doxycycline is the recommended treatment for all individuals with presumed Rocky Mountain spotted fever (RMSF). RMSF can be fatal, so testing for the condition is not recommended because it would delay treatment. Short courses (5 – 10 days) of doxycycline have been shown to be safe in children and pregnant persons. Inpatient treatment with rapid desensitization is recommended for individuals with a true allergy to doxycycline. Chloramphenicol is another treatment option for RMSF, but it is associated with a higher risk for death than doxycycline. There is no role for amoxicillin or erythromycin in the treatment of RMSF.', options = '["No additional treatment","Amoxicillin","Chloramphenicol","Doxycycline","Erythromycin"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '8aa1c438-b1ab-441d-8324-8515121f3810';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 53 - year - old female with no significant past medical history presents to the emergency department with fatigue, pruritus, and right upper quadrant discomfort. A physical examination reveals mild hepatomegaly. Laboratory Findings Alkaline phosphatase 450 U/L (N 44 – 147) AST 70 U/L (N 10 – 40) Total bilirubin 1.5 mg/dL (N 0.1 – 1.2) Antimitochondrial antibodies positive Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', explanation = 'Primary biliary cholangitis is characterized by chronic cholestasis, positive antimitochondrial antibodies (AMA), and elevated alkaline phosphatase (ALP). The American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) guidelines state that the diagnosis of primary biliary cholangitis can be established with the presence of at least 2 of the following: biochemical evidence of cholestasis (elevated ALP), presence of AMA, and histopathologic evidence of nonsuppurative destructive cholangitis. Elevated AMA is particularly helpful as it is found in >95≥ of cases of primary biliary cholangitis. Autoimmune hepatitis usually presents with elevated aminotransferases and positive autoantibodies such as antinuclear antibodies or anti – smooth muscle antibodies, rather than AMA. It is not primarily a cholestatic disease and elevated ALP is typically not the predominant finding. Depending on the instigating agent, drug - induced liver injury can present with a variety of liver enzyme abnormalities; however, the presence of positive AMA and the chronicity of symptoms make it less likely in this patient scenario. Metabolic dysfunction – associated steatotic liver disease (MASLD) (formerly known as nonalcoholic fatty liver disease) typically presents with elevated aminotransferases and is associated with metabolic syndrome. It is not characterized by cholestasis or positive AMA. Primary sclerosing cholangitis typically presents with cholestatic liver enzyme abnormalities and is often associated with inflammatory bowel disease. It is diagnosed based on characteristic imaging findings of bile duct strictures using MRI cholangiography or endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography. Positive AMA is rarely found in primary sclerosing cholangitis.', options = '["Autoimmune hepatitis","Drug - induced liver injury","Metabolic dysfunction – associated steatotic liver disease (MASLD) (nonalcoholic fatty liver disease)","Primary biliary cholangitis","Primary sclerosing cholangitis"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'e5263e8d-2d61-413a-98a7-88650a4e5bbb';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A generally healthy 28 - year - old female presents to your office because she is concerned about changes in her mood. For the last few months she has been intermittently irritable and unable to sit still. She has had some weight loss, is not sleeping well, an d feels fatigued. She has been working extra hours to get ahead of her office deadlines. She has maxed out her credit card and repeatedly cheated on her husband, who filed for divorce 2 weeks ago. She now feels depressed and anxious, and has considered sui cide but does not have suicidal ideations today. She says that she has had similar episodes in the past. Her father left when she was an infant and her mother is incarcerated, and the patient is unsure of their medical history. Today the patient''s vital signs, a CBC, a comprehensive metabolic panel, and TSH and vitamin B levels are unremarkable. A urine pregnancy test and drug screen are negative. She is alert and oriented during the office visit. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate therapy at this time?', explanation = 'This patient has features of bipolar disorder, a mental health condition affecting >1≥ of the world''s population. The DSM - 5 criteria can be used to suggest a prognosis and determine episode severity. Patients with bipolar disorder have a high suicide rate, so proper diagnosis and prompt treatment are important. The risk of relapse increases in patients who are untreated. Treatment improves prognosis and medications are the mainstay of therapy. FDA - approved medications for the treatment of bipolar disorder include lithium, anticonvulsants, and atypical antipsychotics such as quetiapine. Although this patient has symptoms of depression, monotherapy with an antidepressant is contraindicated in patients with mixed features, manic episodes, or bipolar I disorder. Augmenting therapies such as omega - 3 fatty acids, light therapy, ketamine, and probiotics may be helpful but current evidence is insufficient. Cognitive behavioral therapy, exercise, and nutrition have been shown to be beneficial as well. Electroconvulsive therapy can be an effective treatment for psychotic depression, mania, refractory illness, catatonia, acute psychosis, and suicidal behavior. However, pharmacotherapy is the first - line treatment for bipolar disorder.', options = '["Bupropion","Paroxetine (Paxil)","Quetiapine (Seroquel)","Sertraline (Zoloft)","Electroconvulsive therapy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '2eac0329-4ff8-46d2-8988-75b88a4b1895';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 23 - year - old female presents for IUD removal because she wants to conceive. She has never been pregnant, is in good health, and takes no medications. Her blood pressure is normal and her BMI is 33 kg/m . Which one of the following should you recommend regarding aspirin prophylaxis for preeclampsia?', explanation = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force and the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommend aspirin prophylaxis for pregnant patients who are at increased risk for preeclampsia. Indications include 1 or more high - risk factors or 2 or more moderate - risk factors. High - risk factors include a history of preeclampsia, multifetal gestation, kidney disease, autoimmune disease, type 1 or type 2 diabetes, and chronic hypertension. Moderate - risk factors include first pregnancy, maternal age ≥35 years, BMI >30 kg/m , family history of preeclampsia, sociodemographic characteristics, and personal history factors. This patient is nulliparous and has a pre - pregnancy BMI >30 kg/m , giving her 2 moderate - risk factors. The recommended aspirin prophylaxis for preeclampsia is 81 mg per day and should be started at 12 weeks'' gestation. Low - dose aspirin has been shown to decrease the frequency of preeclampsia as well as other adverse pregnancy outcomes such as intrauterine growth restriction and preterm birth. It also has favorable fetal and maternal safety profiles.', options = '["No aspirin as she does not meet criteria","Aspirin for 1 – 3 months prior to conception","Aspirin at 12 weeks'' gestation","Aspirin if her blood pressure during pregnancy is >135/80 mm Hg"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'c4fcfb51-0deb-4633-8987-35e22a6cac5e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 74 - year - old female presents to your office for follow - up of cardioembolic stroke 1 day after being discharged from the hospital. She presented to the hospital with acute left - sided hand and face weakness. An evaluation in the hospital revealed new atrial fibrillation, mild mitral regurgitation, and a small right - sided cerebral infarction. Cardioembolic stroke was diagnosed. She was discharged 48 hours later after her left - sided weakness had almost completely resolved. Which one of the following therapeutic options is preferred for this patient?', explanation = 'This patient presents with a recent history of cardioembolic stroke. In patients who have a TIA or small cardioembolic stroke and nonvalvular atrial fibrillation, guidelines recommend starting anticoagulation without antiplatelet agents 2 – 14 days after the event. Nonvalvular atrial fibrillation is defined by the lack of moderate to severe mitral stenosis or a mechanical heart valve; direct - acting oral anticoagulants are preferred to warfarin in these patients. The 2024 Optimal Timing of Anticoagulation After Acute Ischaemic Stroke (OPTIMAS) trial confirmed the safety of starting anticoagulation within 4 days of a stroke. In patients with larger strokes that may be at high risk for hemorrhagic conversion, initiating anticoagulation may be delayed to 14 days.', options = '["Apixaban (Eliquis)","Aspirin","Clopidogrel (Plavix)","Warfarin","Aspirin plus clopidogrel"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '9d384907-6024-4c29-9be3-e7f26a61b054';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 24 - year - old gravida 2 para 2 presents to your office with melasma that has not resolved since she gave birth 6 months ago. She is eager to be treated. Which one of the following topical treatments would be the most effective for this patient''s melasma?', explanation = 'Melasma is a common condition in pregnancy that occurs in up to 75≥ of patients. It is caused by increased levels of progesterone, estrogen, and melanocyte - stimulating hormone. While it resolves in 90≥ of cases during the postpartum period, it can persist and may recur in subsequent pregnancies or with the use of oral contraception. Topical tretinoin, hydroquinone, and a corticosteroid such as fluocinolone can all be used in the treatment of melasma, and a combination of the 3 is the most effective. These may be prescribed as a single formulation, which may be cost prohibitive, or as individual components. Azelaic acid and benzoyl peroxide are used to treat acne and are not effective for treating melasma. Imiquimod is an immunomodulator that is helpful in the treatment of condyloma acuminata but has no role in the treatment of melasma.', options = '["Azelaic acid","Hydroquinone","Imiquimod (Aldara, Zyclara)","Benzoyl peroxide plus a corticosteroid","A combination of fluocinolone, hydroquinone, and tretinoin"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '9389ae98-2b22-478c-a322-de3cb88616ab';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 75 - year - old female with an ST - elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) diagnosed in the emergency department has been admitted to your service. She underwent a percutaneous coronary intervention with a drug - eluting stent to the circumflex artery and had b een recovering well until she developed acute shortness of breath on the fourth day of hospitalization. Today, her vital signs reveal a blood pressure of 91/55 mm Hg, a heart rate of 110 beats/min, and an oxygen saturation of 89≥ on room air. On physical e xamination, the patient appears moderately distressed and has no jugular venous pulse. Auscultation reveals a regular rate, normal S and S , and a systolic murmur over the mitral post. Crackles are heard in all lung fields. There is no lower extremity edema. Which one of the following is the likely etiology of this condition?', explanation = 'Advances in angiography, pharmacology, and systems of care have improved morbidity and mortality for acute myocardial infarction (AMI) over the last several decades. This has reduced the incidence of mechanical complications of AMI; however, the hospital mortality for these complications, such as acute papillary muscle rupture, remains high. Acute papillary muscle rupture occurs 3 – 5 days after a transmural infarction involving the right coronary artery or circumflex artery, depending on coronary anatomy. This leads to acute mitral regurgitation, resulting in flash pulmonary edema and shock, as seen in this patient. Cardiac tamponade can occur after an AMI if the ventricular free wall ruptures, which is rare. Clinical clues include chest pain, shortness of breath, muffled heart sounds, and distended neck veins. Chest pain is also a core feature of pericarditis, making it an unlikely diagnosis in this patient. Pulmonary embolism (PE) is a common complication seen in immobile hospitalized patients and can be reduced with appropriate mechanical prophylaxis and chemoprophylaxis. While astute clinicians may rule out PE in this patient, her admission has likely included anticoagulation, and lack of edema makes a venous thromboembolism etiology for PE less likely. Arrhythmias can also occur after an AMI. Supraventricular tachyarrhythmias such as atrial fibrillation may present similarly to this patient, but a ventricular rate of 110 beats/min is unlikely to result in hemodynamic compromise as described in this case.', options = '["Cardiac tamponade","Papillary muscle rupture","Pericarditis","Pulmonary embolism","Supraventricular tachyarrhythmia"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '58fdbda0-9243-405f-90d6-507abbd8b891';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 14 - year - old male sees you to establish care. He has a past medical history of asthma and uses an albuterol inhaler (Proventil, Ventolin) as needed. He normally has symptoms about 3 – 4 days per week. Recent pulmonary function tests showed mildly reduced lu ng function. Based on the Global Initiative for Asthma (GINA) guidelines, which one of the following would be the preferred treatment strategy for this patient?', explanation = 'Based on the Global Initiative for Asthma (GINA) guideline, patients who have symptoms <3 – 5 days per week with normal or mildly reduced lung function are classified as having mild asthma. For patients 12 years and older with mild asthma, the guidelines recommend treatment with as - needed low - dose inhaled corticosteroid plus formoterol (ICS/formoterol). As - needed low - dose ICS/formoterol reduces the risk of severe asthma exacerbations by 60≥ – 64≥ compared to as - needed short - acting β - agonists (SABAs) such as albuterol. ICS/formoterol also reduces the risk of severe exacerbations compared to other regimens that include a SABA reliever. Formoterol should not be used without an ICS.', options = '["Continuing as - needed albuterol","Switching to as - needed formoterol","Switching to an as - needed low - dose inhaled corticosteroid (ICS) plus formoterol","Continuing as - needed albuterol, and adding a low - dose ICS for maintenance","Continuing as - needed albuterol, and adding a low - dose ICS plus salmeterol for maintenance"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '87c8bd60-896e-445d-a6b8-7126d7e40c5f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 37 - year - old male who recently returned from a trip to Vietnam presents for evaluation of an intensely pruritic rash on his feet. Physical examination findings are normal other than an erythematous, serpiginous rash on his feet and lower legs. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', explanation = 'The most likely diagnosis is cutaneous larva migrans. The typical rash that occurs with this infection is an intensely pruritic, erythematous, serpiginous rash. It is typically seen on the feet and gluteal areas. There are no diagnostic tests for this infection and the diagnosis is made clinically. Infections are generally self - limited but can be treated with albendazole. Cutaneous larva migrans infections are mainly found in Asia and Africa where macaque monkeys are the reservoir. It has an incubation period of 1 – 5 days but can take up to 1 month. Cutaneous leishmaniasis generally presents with small papules that develop into nonhealing open sores with a raised border and central ulceration. The lesions are generally painless. Herpesvirus B presents with a vesicular rash near the site of inoculation and influenza - like symptoms. The clinical manifestations of Neisseria meningitidis range from asymptomatic dermatologic findings such as petechiae to severe systemic disease. Scabies presents with a very pruritic rash that is red with small bumps, typically appears along skinfolds, and often forms a line.', options = '["Cutaneous larva migrans","Cutaneous leishmaniasis","Herpesvirus B","Neisseria meningitidis","Scabies"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '815faa78-6f74-4104-b150-45a094f4e7ff';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 10 - year - old male is brought to your office by his mother for follow - up of treatment for a Cryptosporidium infection that he likely contracted during a camping trip after swimming in a freshwater lake. He has completed treatment and is asymptomatic. His mother asks when he is allowed to resume swimming. Because of concerns for ongoing asymptomatic shedding, you should recommend that the patient may return to swimming', explanation = 'Infection with Cryptosporidium is caused by ingesting oocysts, which can survive for up to 10 days in treated water. Diarrhea is the predominant symptom, and a stool sample is used for diagnosis. Treatment for infection with Cryptosporidium is supportive with fluid and electrolyte replacement. Nitazoxanide can be used in cases of severe or prolonged disease. Because shedding of oocysts continues even after symptoms resolve, it is recommended that patients refrain from swimming for 2 weeks after resolution of symptoms.', options = '["3 days after treatment is completed","1 week after treatment is completed","3 days after symptoms resolve","1 week after symptoms resolve","2 weeks after symptoms resolve"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '103f9daa-d1b4-4c9e-97f0-d6307428cd17';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A previously healthy 27 - year - old female at 36 weeks'' gestation presents to the emergency department (ED) in a rural town. She reports a 1 - week history of headaches, nausea, fatigue, and right upper quadrant pain. She has been taking acetaminophen for pain with minimal improvement in her symptoms, which have worsened today. On examination she has a temperature of 36.8 °C (98.2 °F), a blood pressure of 150/95 mm Hg, a respiratory rate of 18/min, and a pulse rate of 104 beats/min. There are no signs of distres s on neonatal tracing. Laboratory Findings WBCs 12,400/mm (N 4000 – 11,000) Hemoglobin 9.8 g/dL (N 12.0 – 15.0) Platelets 43,000/mm (N 150,000 – 400,000) AST 112 U/L (N 10 – 59) ALT 95 U/L (N 10 – 28) Serum creatinine 0.8 mg/dL (N 0.6 – 1.1) Urine protein to creatinine ratio 422 mg/g (N <300) Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'Hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelet count (HELLP) syndrome should be suspected in pregnant women presenting with malaise, headache, hypertension, and proteinuria. Women with HELLP syndrome have 10≥ – 15≥ maternal morbidity and mortality rates compared to those without. The elevated risks are due to the potential of severe complications such as cerebral hemorrhage, cardiopulmonary arrest, disseminated intravascular coagulation, acute respiratory distress syndrome, renal failure, sepsis, and hepatic hemorrhage. Early diagnosis and management are critical. Quick and targeted evaluation with urgent delivery in patients over 34 weeks'' gestation is key to avoiding maternal deaths. Corticosteroids can be used to treat low platelet count, but will not address the symptoms of liver failure. Acute liver failure due to HELLP is secondary to pregnancy. Although this patient has been taking acetaminophen, the examination and laboratory results are consistent with HELLP syndrome; therefore, treatment for acetaminophen overdose with N - acetylcysteine is not warranted.', options = '["Administering oral prednisone","Administering N - acetylcysteine","Consultation with a gastroenterologist","Arranging for urgent delivery"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '4168869c-f72f-4acc-bcc3-b1d6c21fe1c5';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 64 - year - old female with a history of hypertension and no prior evidence of kidney disease presents for follow - up of a recent basic metabolic panel that showed an estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) of 49 mL/min/1.73 m . Which one of the following would confirm a diagnosis of chronic kidney disease?', explanation = 'Before a diagnosis of chronic kidney disease can be made, evidence of renal impairment or damage must be present for 3 months in order to differentiate the renal abnormalities from an acute kidney injury (AKI). This is most often an estimated glomerular filtration rate <60 mL/min/1.73 m ; however, the Kidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes (KDIGO) guidelines do allow for other evidence of persistent renal damage or decreased function, such as albuminuria or proteinuria, that persists for at least 3 months. Previous documentation of kidney damage or impairment can also be sought. Renal imaging abnormalities such as decreased kidney volume, cortical thickening, or multiple cysts are also evidence of chronicity.', options = '["A urine albumin to creatinine ratio >30 mg/g at this time","A urine albumin to creatinine ratio >300 mg/g at this time","An additional eGFR <60 mL/min/1.73 m in 1 month","An additional eGFR <90 mL/min/1.73 m in 2 months","An additional eGFR <60 mL/min/1.73 m in 3 months"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'fbf3aaf5-d384-4d48-9ddd-5ce52829922f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'You see a newborn for a routine wellness check. The parents tell you that there is a family history of allergies to eggs and peanuts, and they ask how to reduce their child''s risk of developing these food allergies. Evidence supports exposing the patient to these potentially allergenic foods starting at which one of the following ages?', explanation = 'The lowest risk of developing future allergies to many foods, including peanuts and eggs, occurs with early exposure at 4 – 6 months of age. Peanut butter can be thinned with water, breast milk, cow’s milk, or formula. Peanuts should not be given in their original hard form because it is a choking hazard. Eggs should be cooked well prior to eating.', options = '["4 – 6 months","9 – 12 months","1 – 2 years","3 – 5 years",">5 years"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '47d65bbc-09ec-449e-bc17-1432c21dd56c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 40 - year - old female presents for a health maintenance examination. Her medical history is unremarkable, but her family history is significant for colorectal cancer in her father, thyroid cancer in her paternal aunt, and endometrial cancer in her maternal grandmother. The patient says that her friend was diagnosed with breast cancer 2 weeks ago and is BRCA2 positive. She is anxious about her risk of breast cancer and requests a mammogram and BRCA testing. According to the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force guidelines, which one of the following would be most appropriate for this patient regarding genetic testing for BRCA1/2 ?', explanation = 'For this patient, reassurance only is indicated. The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommends against routine screening, risk assessment, counseling, and testing in all women for BRCA1/2 mutations (D recommendation). Only women with a personal or family history of breast, ovarian, tubal, or peritoneum cancer or specific susceptibility to BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations should be formally evaluated with a risk assessment tool. Furthermore, genetic testing for BRCA1 and BRCA2 is indicated only after a positive risk assessment score is calculated and subsequent genetic counseling is received.', options = '["Reassurance only","Risk assessment using the 7 - Question Family History Screening Tool","Testing for BRCA1/2 mutation","Genetic counseling"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '4a924e71-f7dc-44f2-ba44-77e0c6799a09';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'You are seeing a patient at 12 weeks'' gestation for prenatal care. She has a family history of neural tube defects and is taking 4 mg of high - dose folic acid supplementation daily. Her pregnancy is progressing normally, and she has no concerns. Which one of the following should you recommend for this patient regarding ongoing folic acid supplementation?', explanation = 'Supplementation with folic acid leading up to and during pregnancy can significantly reduce the risk of neural tube defects (NTDs). Ideally, supplementation should be started 1 – 3 months prior to conception. Those with pregnancies at higher risk of NTDs are candidates for high - dose folic acid supplementation, which is more effective at prevention. This patient is considered high risk as she has a family history of NTDs. The recommended dose of folic acid is 4 mg per day until 12 weeks after conception, and then 0.4 mg per day after 12 weeks. The rationale for decreasing the dose after 12 weeks is that organogenesis is largely complete by this stage and there is theoretical concern for fetal toxicity. Folic acid supplementation is recommended in addition to the usual dietary sources of folic acid.', options = '["Continuing with 4 mg daily for the remainder of the pregnancy","Decreasing the dosage to 1 mg daily for the remainder of the pregnancy","Decreasing the dosage to 0.4 mg daily for the remainder of the pregnancy","Discontinuing folic acid"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '29d29973-9cdb-4e54-b9ee-3a8bf39b6c25';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 55 - year - old male with a history of diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and stage 3 chronic kidney disease presents for management of recurrent gout. He has had multiple attacks this year despite dietary changes. His uric acid level is 8.6 mg/dL (N 4.5 – 8.0) and he would like to start gout prophylaxis. Which one of the following would be most appropriate to initiate at this time?', explanation = 'Gout is a common crystalline arthropathy. Long - term treatment with urate - lowering medications is effective in preventing recurrent attacks and is generally well tolerated. Allopurinol is typically used as first - line treatment for gout in all patients, even in those with kidney disease. The American College of Rheumatology (°CR) strongly recommends that an anti - inflammatory medication, such as colchicine, be given when allopurinol is initiated to prevent an acute flare. The allopurinol dosage should be adjusted to target a uric acid level <6 mg/dL. Colchicine alone is useful in the setting of an acute flare, as are NSAIDs or corticosteroids. Febuxostat is a urate - lowering medication that works by inhibiting xanthine oxidase, which interferes with the conversion of hypoxanthine and xanthine to uric acid. While this medication is indicated for chronic gout, it is not a first - line choice. The °CR strongly recommends against pegloticase as a first - line therapy due to cost, lack of evidence regarding safety, and other options with more favorable benefit to harm ratios.', options = '["Allopurinol (Zyloprim)","Colchicine (Colcrys)","Febuxostat (Uloric)","Pegloticase (Krystexxa)","Allopurinol plus colchicine"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '7acfcc2e-5dad-432d-a730-dc293ee7058f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'In a patient with aortic stenosis, which one of the following is an indication for referral for possible valve replacement?', explanation = 'Once symptoms occur in patients with aortic stenosis, the clinical outcome is extremely poor, with 2 - year survival rates below 50≥. It is well established that this prognosis can be reversed by valve replacement, which has acceptable levels of operative morbidity and mortality, and postoperative survival rates similar to those of age - matched normal adults. Angina could be an indication of the seriousness of aortic valve stenosis. Patients should also be evaluated for coronary artery disease.', options = '["Calcification of the valve on an echocardiogram","Development of mitral insufficiency on an echocardiogram","Left ventricular hypertrophy noted on a chest x - ray","A systolic ejection murmur that has increased from grade 1/6 to grade 2/6","New - onset angina"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '10fac44d-b82a-484b-993f-830a33fc35f1';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 23 - year - old male presents on a spring day with a 2 – 3 - day history of mild nasal congestion, sneezing, and slight watery discharge. He does not have a fever or other significant concerns. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?', explanation = 'This patient has mild allergic rhinitis. Intranasal corticosteroids are considered first - line therapy. Intranasal or oral antihistamines may be considered given the patient''s mild symptoms, but they are less effective. Intranasal cromolyn is less effective and requires multiple dosing. Since there is no apparent infection, oral antibiotics are not indicated. Oral corticosteroids are also not indicated at this time. Some experts recommend nasal saline irrigation to remove allergens from the nares, but this approach has limited evidence and would augment, not replace, pharmacotherapy.', options = '["Intranasal antihistamines","Intranasal corticosteroids","Intranasal cromolyn","Oral antibiotics","Oral corticosteroids"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'c31467ae-ec56-47b1-9ff9-e56f1b22c48c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 30 - year - old female presents for follow - up of infertility. She and her husband have been trying to conceive for the past 12 months. She reports a history of irregular menstrual bleeding over the past several years. A physical examination is unremarkable e xcept for a BMI of 29 kg/m . You suspect polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) and recommend diagnostic testing with fasting laboratory studies scheduled for 8:00 a.m. An elevation in which one of the following hormones would most strongly support a diagnosis of PCOS in this patient?', explanation = 'While there is no single test to diagnose polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), the diagnosis can be made based on the presence of at least 2 of the 3 Rotterdam criteria: oligoanovulation, hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovaries on ultrasonography. Other conditions that may mimic PCOS must be excluded, including an androgen - secreting tumor, exogenous androgen exposure, Cushing syndrome, nonclassical congenital adrenal hyperplasia, primary hypothalamic amenorrhea, primary ovarian insufficiency, acromegaly, thyroid disease, prolactin disorders, and genetic disorders that impede insulin action. Hyperandrogenism may be diagnosed clinically with evidence of hirsutism, androgenic alopecia, acne, or seborrhea. Additionally, it may be diagnosed biochemically with elevated androgen levels, such as an elevated free testosterone level. An elevated 17 - hydroxyprogesterone level would not suggest PCOS, but rather a possible diagnosis of congenital adrenal hyperplasia, which may share overlapping clinical features with PCOS. An elevated cortisol level would similarly suggest an etiology other than PCOS, such as Cushing syndrome or adrenal tumor, which may also share overlapping clinical features with PCOS. Although insulin resistance is often part of the complex pathophysiology of PCOS, neither elevated insulin nor glucose levels are part of the Rotterdam criteria for PCOS.', options = '["17 - Hydroxyprogesterone","Cortisol","Glucose","Insulin","Testosterone"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'ed10f7fd-aaac-4fd5-b38d-098c960ff658';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A generally healthy 36 - year - old male presents to your clinic with a 36 - hour history of dizziness and nausea. He says he feels as though the world is spinning and he tends to fall to the left when he tries to walk. The episodes of dizziness occur spontaneou sly and can last from minutes to hours. He does not have any recent illness, hearing loss, or tinnitus, and he does not take any medications. An HEENT examination is normal. On neurologic testing, he exhibits horizontal nystagmus with left lateral gaze. Head - impulse testing reveals a rapid movement of both eyes. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'This patient''s vertigo is caused by vestibular neuritis, as evidenced by its spontaneity, rotatory vertigo, nausea, and listing to the affected side with walking. In this scenario, head - impulse testing shows saccade, and the head - impulse, nystagmus, test of skew (HINTS) examination is significant for horizontal nystagmus to the affected side. Vestibular neuritis is most often found in patients 30 – 50 years of age and is thought to have a viral etiology. It involves prolonged, continuous vertigo, while benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV) is characterized by brief, episodic vertigo associated with head movements. Vestibular neuritis usually resolves on its own within a few days, although some patients have recurrent symptoms for months. The treatment for vestibular neuritis is reassurance. Antiemetics can be used for up to 3 days. Patients with symptoms that last longer should be referred for vestibular rehabilitation. Home Epley maneuvers are appropriate for vertigo caused by BPPV, but are neither indicated nor effective for vestibular neuritis (SOR A). Corticosteroids and antiviral medications have not been shown to be effective in treating vestibular neuritis. MRI of the brain is indicated for patients who exhibit signs of central vertigo or those with hearing loss (SOR C).', options = '["Home Epley maneuvers","Reassurance and antiemetics","Prednisone, 40 mg daily for 5 days","Valacyclovir (Valtrex), 1000 mg twice daily for 7 days","MRI of the brain"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '41a0a950-26ae-4a47-ab5d-e3077cc6d1cc';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 23 - year - old female presents after a sexual assault that occurred the prior evening. She reports nonconsensual penetrative vaginal intercourse. The assailant was an acquaintance with unknown medical history. The patient takes no medications and is up to d ate on vaccinations, including tetanus, HPV, and hepatitis B, although her hepatitis B serology status is unknown. She elects to undergo a medical forensic examination, which is completed with the help of a certified Sexual Assault Nurse Examiner. A urine pregnancy test is negative, and sexually transmitted infection testing is performed. Which one of the following would be most appropriate to offer at this time?', explanation = 'In addition to trauma - informed evaluation and counseling, women who experience sexual assault should be offered forensic examination, emergency contraception, and screening and prevention for sexually transmitted infections. Empiric treatment for Neisseria gonorrhoeae , Chlamydia trachomatis , and Trichomonas vaginalis is appropriate and should include ceftriaxone, azithromycin, and either metronidazole or tinidazole. Postexposure prophylaxis for HIV should be made available with triple therapy for 28 days, rather than the double therapy regimens used in pre - exposure prophylaxis. Sofosbuvir/velpatasvir is used to treat hepatitis C infection, but routine postexposure prophylaxis is not recommended. Long - term contraception may be offered, but patients should first be provided with effective emergency contraception, such as ulipristal, levonorgestrel, or the copper IUD.', options = '["Emtricitabine/tenofovir alafenamide (Descovy)","Norgestimate /ethinyl estradiol (Sprintec)","Sofosbuvir/velpatasvir (Epclusa)","Azithromycin (Zithromax), ceftriaxone, and metronidazole (Flagyl)","The etonogestrel implant (Nexplanon)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '6b5f2376-279c-45fd-84bb-7214654fd7f9';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 29 - year - old female presents with a long - standing history of episodes of depressed mood, headaches, and irritability that occur in the 1 – 2 weeks preceding her menses. She has a history of anxiety that is well controlled on fluoxetine (Prozac), 60 mg daily . She has a copper IUD (Paragard) for contraception. She has tried combined oral contraceptives to control the premenstrual symptoms, but found that they worsened her irritability. Which one of the following treatments would be most effective for this patient''s symptoms?', explanation = 'Symptoms of premenstrual syndrome (PMS) with mood instability can be reduced with 1000 – 1200 mg of calcium carbonate daily (SOR B). Patients with PMS symptoms have been found to have cyclic changes in calcium levels that may account for the symptoms, but the mechanism of action is still unknown. All SSRIs are first - line treatments for symptoms of PMS and premenstrual dysphoric disorder (PMDD), but bupropion has not been shown to be effective. Continuous combined oral contraceptives are also first - line treatment (SOR A). High - dose dutasteride (2.5 mg daily) has been shown to alleviate PMDD symptoms, but it can have a deleterious effect on mood and is teratogenic. Low - dose dutasteride has not demonstrated beneficial effect on PMDD symptoms. Patients with PMS have not been found to have low levels of vitamin D, and supplementing with vitamin D (cholecalciferol) has not been clearly demonstrated to 3 alleviate PMS symptoms. There is insufficient evidence to prove the benefit of acupuncture in reducing PMS symptoms.', options = '["Extended - release bupropion, 150 mg daily","Calcium carbonate, 600 mg twice daily","Dutasteride (Avodart), 0.5 mg daily","Vitamin D (cholecalciferol), 1000 IU daily","Acupuncture"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'baba8098-a76d-48a3-ad2e-cf9be2918423';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 72 - year - old female with osteoporosis (T - score – 2.8) is seen in your office for the first time. She was prescribed alendronate (Fosamax), 70 mg weekly, by her previous physician. The patient took the medication but discontinued it after 4 weeks because of gastrointestinal symptoms. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate action at this time?', explanation = 'Women ≥65 years of age should be tested for osteoporosis. A bone mineral density score ≤ – 2.5 indicates the need for treatment, as seen in this patient. Oral bisphosphonates, such as alendronate, are considered first - line treatment. To minimize gastrointestinal irritation, oral bisphosphonates should be taken on an empty stomach with 8 oz of water, and the patient should remain upright and avoid food and beverages other than plain water for at least 30 minutes afterward. If oral bisphosphonates are not tolerated despite correct administration, intravenous bisphosphonates should be considered. In this case, the patient should discontinue alendronate and transition to intravenous bisphosphonate therapy. Raloxifene is not the preferred initial treatment.', options = '["Discontinuing the medication only","Instructing the patient to take the medication before bed","Instructing the patient to take the medication with food","Discontinuing the medication and starting raloxifene (Evista)","Discontinuing the medication and arranging for intravenous bisphosphonates"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '4a105eac-d311-4b22-a7bf-db9d64ae9bb4';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 27 - year - old patient presents to the emergency department with a fever, headache, and stiff neck. You diagnose sepsis and perform a lumbar puncture. The results are consistent with bacterial meningitis. In addition to antibiotics, which one of the following intravenous therapies is most likely to improve mortality?', explanation = 'Despite optimal therapy, the mortality and loss of quality - adjusted life - years from bacterial meningitis is significant. Empiric therapy for adults includes vancomycin and ceftriaxone. Intravenous (IV) dexamethasone, when given shortly before or at the time of administration of IV antibiotics, has been shown to improve mortality (odds ratio 0.90) and neurologic sequelae. Bactericidal antibiotics help to reduce inflammation. Acyclovir would be indicated if there is clinical concern for herpes simplex virus or symptoms of encephalitis. While optimal fluid management for meningitis should be tailored based on clinical evaluation, this patient has also been diagnosed with sepsis and should receive appropriate fluid resuscitation; therefore, IV furosemide would be inappropriate. Glycerol is a hyperosmolar agent intended to reduce intracranial pressure in bacterial meningitis, but it cannot be recommended for treatment due to an increased risk of death according to available data in adults with a high prevalence of HIV. IV immunoglobulin is not a recognized treatment for bacterial meningitis.', options = '["Acyclovir","Dexamethasone","Furosemide","Glycerol","Immunoglobulin"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '31d93fdd-1c83-4976-b32d-94799dd35c7a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 33 - year - old male presents for follow - up of long - standing heartburn. His symptoms have been present for 3 years and recent treatment for 1 month with pantoprazole (Protonix) has only provided partial relief. He has a history of allergic rhinitis that is t reated with fluticasone propionate nasal spray (Flonase). He has had dysphagia with solids, and a food impaction 3 months ago that resolved spontaneously. Upper endoscopy reveals eosinophilic esophagitis. Which one of the following is most likely to improve this patient’s symptoms?', explanation = 'Eosinophilic esophagitis is an inflammatory condition triggered by food antigens in sensitive individuals. Endoscopic findings of linear grooves, concentric rings, and whitish exudates may suggest its presence, but the diagnosis is confirmed histologically based on the presence of >15 eosinophils/hpf and the exclusion of other causes of eosinophilia. The diagnosis should be suspected in patients with heartburn who have atopic illnesses such as allergic rhinitis, asthma, or eczema and who do not respond to proton pump inhibitor therapy. Eosinophilic esophagitis is more common in men in their 20s and 30s, and dysphagia may be present for 4 or more years before diagnosis. More than half of patients with this condition may have a history of food impaction. First - line pharmacologic treatment is oral budesonide. Alternatively, inhalant corticosteroids may be sprayed into the oral cavity during a breath hold and then swallowed to minimize pulmonary deposition. Treatment with proton pump inhibitors may help, but they do not provide complete relief in two - thirds of cases. Dietary changes can be very helpful, but consultation with an allergist may be needed. Immunosuppressed individuals such as patients with HIV or diabetes mellitus may have Candida esophagitis, which is treated with fluconazole rather than clotrimazole. Adding an H - blocker such as famotidine would help in cases of erosive esophagitis. Metoclopramide 2 was previously used to treat severe GERD, but it is no longer encouraged due to side effects. While montelukast is used to treat asthma and allergic rhinitis, it is not as effective for eosinophilic esophagitis.', options = '["A clotrimazole oropharyngeal lozenge","Budesonide oral suspension (Eohilia)","Oral famotidine (Pepcid)","Oral metoclopramide (Reglan)","Oral montelukast (Singulair)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '5deba645-00b4-46b2-b06c-d8e07671545b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 45 - year - old male with a recent diagnosis of Crohn disease presents to your office for a health maintenance examination. His gastroenterologist advised that he ask you about vaccine updates. He has not seen a primary care physician in over 15 years. His c urrent medications include methotrexate and azathioprine (Imuran). He received a Tdap vaccine 6 years ago at an urgent care clinic and recently received a seasonal influenza vaccine and an updated COVID - 19 vaccine at his gastroenterologist’s office. He is confident that he received all of his childhood vaccines. Which one of the following vaccines should you recommend today?', explanation = 'Adults with inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) should receive a pneumococcal vaccine. Meningococcal vaccine is currently recommended for adolescents with IBD. The MMR vaccine is contraindicated in patients already on immunosuppressive treatment. Because this patient''s Tdap vaccine was administered <10 years ago, he is not due for another dose. Similarly, his next dose of zoster vaccine will be due when he is 50 years of age, and there is no recommendation to administer the next vaccine before the age of 50 in patients with IBD.', options = '["20 - valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV20, Prevnar 20)","Meningococcal","MMR","Tdap","Zoster vaccine (Shingrix)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '9e0ff20f-ccfd-4004-b639-f1cc1db0e026';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 2 - year - old child is brought to the urgent care clinic by their parents with a 2 - day history of abdominal pain and vomiting. The child has been irritable over the past 2 days with intermittent abdominal pain and several episodes of associated emesis, and just had a bloody stool that the parents describe as resembling jelly. The child appears uncomfortable but is alert and afebrile, with normal blood pressure. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', explanation = 'Intussusception is a condition in which a part of the intestine slides or "telescopes" into an adjacent section. It presents with a classic triad of intermittent abdominal pain, emesis, and blood - tinged mucous stools that are sometimes called "red currant jelly" stools. It most commonly occurs at the ileocolic junction and typically affects infants and toddlers. The initial evaluation begins with ultrasonography. An enema with air or contrast can both confirm the diagnosis and reverse the intussusception. If this procedure does not relieve the condition, surgical correction is necessary. Necrotizing enterocolitis is a severe intestinal infection that typically presents with severe abdominal pain, lethargy, and unstable vital signs. Pyloric stenosis is notable for projectile vomiting, but not bloody stools. Volvulus typically involves a sudden onset of vomiting and abdominal pain and even distension, but without bloody stools.', options = '["Intussusception","Necrotizing enterocolitis","Pyloric stenosis","Volvulus"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '5de8a730-b128-48fc-9237-f2ce69501440';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 37 - year - old female is brought to the emergency department by ambulance after collapsing while standing in line at a bookstore. Her friend witnessed the episode and describes it as "fainting." A history and physical examination were performed at the bedsi de while triaging the patient. The patient''s past medical history and a physical examination, including vital signs and a neurologic assessment, are unremarkable. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in the evaluation of this patient with suspected syncope?', explanation = 'Electrocardiography (EKG) is a primary evaluation tool, along with a comprehensive history and physical examination, to investigate the etiology of a syncopal episode (SOR C). Electroencephalography (EEG) is not recommended as a routine test. Carotid ultrasonography is not recommended for evaluation of syncope in patients with a normal physical examination (SOR B). Similarly, head CT and MRI are not recommended as neurologic imaging studies in patients with a normal neurologic examination after a syncopal episode (SOR B). If the patient were noted to experience syncope with exertion, an exercise stress test would be appropriate (SOR C). However, this patient was observed to be at rest when the "fainting" occurred.', options = '["No further testing","An EKG","An EEG","Carotid ultrasonography","Head CT"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'a49266f6-1172-46a2-a6ca-74d9a5add6ef';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 64 - year - old male presents with urinary frequency. His symptoms have been ongoing for months, but he says they have acutely worsened in the last 6 – 8 weeks. His symptoms are predominantly storage - related with daytime frequency, nocturia, urgency, and even infrequent incontinence. He also reports difficulty voiding, noting a weak stream and hesitancy. He does not have erectile dysfunction. Urinalysis is negative. In addition to behavioral and lifestyle alterations, which one of the following medications should you recommend for initial therapy?', explanation = 'Men with lower urinary tract symptoms may have overactive bladder, bladder outlet obstruction, or both. Differentiating overactive bladder and bladder outlet obstruction can be difficult due to significant symptom overlap. Overactive bladder is most often due to detrusor overactivity, and bladder outlet obstruction is most often secondary to benign prostatic hyperplasia. The most appropriate initial treatment for these symptoms is an α - blocker, such as tamsulosin, alfuzosin, or terazosin (Evidence Level A), regardless of the predominance of storage symptoms (eg, daytime frequency, nocturia, urgency, incontinence) or voiding symptoms (eg, weak stream, hesitancy, straining, dribbling). The American Urological Association recommends 5 - α - reductase inhibitors if prostate volume is ≥30 mL on imaging, the prostate is enlarged on examination, or PSA levels exceed 1.5 ng/mL. 5 - α - Reductase inhibitors can take up to a year to take full effect. Anticholinergics (oxybutynin) and β - agonists (mirabegron) may be used alone or in 3 combination with α - blockers for patients with predominantly storage - related symptoms if α - blockers are not adequately effective. Some guidelines recommend assessing postvoid residual volume before initiating these agents. A daily phosphodiesterase - 5 inhibitor (typically tadalafil) can be used as initial monotherapy or as combination therapy in patients with erectile dysfunction, although it is not generally recommended as first - line treatment. The mechanism of action is not fully understood.', options = '["A 5 - α - reductase inhibitor","An α - antagonist","An anticholinergic","A β - agonist","A phosphodiesterase - 5 inhibitor"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '5a4858fc-5a15-4ba4-8a80-0e4b0efe1c8d';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 5 - day - old male is brought to your office by his mother for an initial well child visit. After an uncomplicated, full - term pregnancy, the mother gave birth 102 hours ago through vaginal delivery and was discharged 48 hours ago. She shares that this is her first child, and she is concerned that he is not getting enough milk despite exclusively breastfeeding 10 – 12 times per day. Which one of the following factors, if present, would indicate inadequate breastfeeding at this time?', explanation = 'Recognition of adequate newborn feeding and parental lactation counseling is important in the care of mothers and infants. An infant who is feeding adequately should produce 6 or more wet diapers and 3 or more stools after 4 days of life. Infant weight loss is normal in the first 3 days of life, but a weight loss of more than 7≥ from birth weight or ongoing weight loss after 3 days of life should raise concern. Maternal breasts that appear smaller or less full do not necessarily indicate poor feeding; however, lack of any breast changes or leaking of milk by day 5 post partum may indicate a problem with milk supply. Maternal nipple pain is normal with breastfeeding, but pain that persists beyond the first 30 – 60 seconds should prompt evaluation and counseling. If supplementation with formula is deemed medically necessary, protocol from the Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine should be followed.', options = '["Four green stools per day","Four wet diapers per day","Infant weight loss of 5≥ from birth weight","Maternal breasts that appear small and not full","Maternal nipple pain during the first 15 seconds of each feed"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '920fa3cb-a557-46bd-8c2f-476ec751053e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 25 - year - old male presents to the urgent care clinic with a 4 - day history of fever, chills, myalgias, and cough. He lives with a roommate and works remotely from home. His last influenza vaccine was 5 years ago, and his most recent COVID - 19 vaccine was 2 years ago. His temperature is 38.3 °C (100.9 °F), and his heart rate and blood pressure are within the normal range. A physical examination is normal except for occasional rhonchi. Rapid antigen testing is positive for influenza B and negative for influenz a A and COVID - 19. Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient''s influenza B?', explanation = 'According to the CDC, antiviral treatment for influenza is not recommended for non – high - risk individuals who present more than 48 hours after symptom onset. Thus, supportive therapy is most important for this patient who is at low risk for hospitalization and death. Methylprednisolone is not recommended to treat influenza. The risk for hospitalization and death is not reduced in adults and children treated with a neuraminidase inhibitor in the outpatient setting, as supported by systematic and unpublished randomized clinical trials. While oseltamivir is recommended as first - line therapy for high - risk patients, it is not indicated for this patient, who has no underlying medical conditions or known exposure to high - risk individuals and presents more than 48 hours after symptom onset. Rimantadine is not active against influenza B and is also not considered first - line medical therapy for influenza.', options = '["Supportive therapy","Methylprednisolone (Medrol)","Oseltamivir (Tamiflu)","Rimantadine"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '33c40e9c-48e9-486b-a60d-e4ed747795e8';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 30 - year - old male with a long - standing history of obsessive - compulsive disorder presents for follow - up to discuss potential pharmacotherapy due to an inadequate treatment response to psychotherapy. Which one of the following medications would be most like ly to improve this patient’s symptoms while minimizing the risk of adverse side effects?', explanation = 'The most effective medication therapy options for obsessive - compulsive disorder (OCD) are SSRIs. Fluoxetine, fluvoxamine, sertraline, and paroxetine all have approval from the FDA for the treatment of OCD. Dosages that are higher than usual are often required to achieve symptom control. Clomipramine, a tricyclic antidepressant, has an indication from the FDA for treatment of OCD, but a higher toxicity risk makes it less favorable for first - line treatment. Bupropion (a norepinephrine - dopamine reuptake inhibitor), buspirone (an atypical anxiolytic), and quetiapine (an atypical antipsychotic) are not first - line treatment for OCD.', options = '["Bupropion","Buspirone","Clomipramine (Anafranil)","Quetiapine (Seroquel)","Sertraline (Zoloft)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '350d1088-a0fc-42c0-9b85-79e9434262e7';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 76 - year - old female with hypertension sees you for a routine follow - up visit. She fell about 2 weeks ago while hurrying to answer her home telephone, and sustained bruising and ed before the fall, swelling of the left lower leg. She does not recall feeling dizzy or lighthead and she did not hit her head or lose consciousness. She was able to get up and walk afterward without any limitations but developed a large bruise over the lateral hip. She has not had any previous falls and she feels well today. She li ves alone and performs activities of daily living independently. Which one of the following has the best evidence to prevent future falls and associated serious injury?', explanation = 'Falls are a common cause of serious injury and death in older adults in the United States. A 2018 study found that 27.5≥ of adults ≥65 years of age had fallen at least once in the past year (714 falls per 1000 community - dwelling older adults). More than 300,000 older adults are hospitalized each year for hip fracture, which is one of the most serious potential complications from falls in older adults. Falls are also the leading cause of injury - related death in older adults. A history of a fall is a key risk factor for future falls. Other risks include sensory and cognitive deficits, acute and chronic health conditions, alcohol and drug use, and certain other medication use. In community - dwelling older adults who are identified as being at higher risk of falls, the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force found that exercise interventions lower the risk of falls and should be recommended. Both individual and group exercise programs are beneficial and there is no data to recommend any single type of exercise over others. Multifactorial interventions to reduce falls typically include an assessment of modifiable risk factors followed by a customized approach to reducing risk. Evaluations may include balance, gait, vision, cognition, postural blood pressure, medication use, and the home environment. This assessment differs from a focused diagnostic assessment of a patient with a specific concern such as vision change, dizziness, or numbness in the feet. Interventions to address risk factors identified in a multifactorial screening program may offer benefit to high - risk individuals, although studies have found a small net benefit on average. A 2023 Cochrane review comprising 22 studies on environmental interventions found evidence of benefit for reducing fall hazards at home by using a validated tool to identify and address hazards, usually via a home visit. Patient education, assistive devices, vision impairment correction, and footwear selection were not found to be beneficial.', options = '["Patient education on fall harms and prevention","Use of a cane while walking","Referral to a group exercise program, including gait, balance, and functional training","Referral to an ophthalmologist for a comprehensive vision assessment","Referral to a podiatrist for footwear assessment"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '451739be-9bd6-47ef-a12c-34814e4e7087';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following would be most appropriate for initial treatment of Helicobacter pylori infection?', explanation = 'Infection with Helicobacter pylori should be treated when it causes symptoms. Several regimens exist for the treatment of H pylori infection. Guidelines currently recommend optimized quadruple therapy with bismuth, metronidazole, omeprazole, and tetracycline. This combination is approximately 91≥ effective at eradicating H pylori infection. Dual therapy with vonoprazan and amoxicillin is an option for patients who are unable or unwilling to take quadruple therapy, but its eradiation rates only range from 70≥ to 80≥. Regimens containing clarithromycin or levofloxacin should be limited to infections with documented susceptibility to macrolides or fluoroquinolones, respectively.', options = '["Dual therapy with vonoprazan (Voquezna) and amoxicillin","Triple therapy with omeprazole, amoxicillin, and clarithromycin","Triple therapy with omeprazole, amoxicillin, and levofloxacin","Quadruple therapy with bismuth, omeprazole, metronidazole, and tetracycline"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'fd9fc0eb-fcdf-4942-8cb1-30be6c6f742b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'The parent of a 5 - year - old male calls your office after the child sustains burns to his arms and chest while helping his father boil pasta in the kitchen. The father tells you that the burned areas of skin are red without any open areas. He estimates the s ize of the burns on the arms at 2 – 3 cm in diameter and those on the chest at 5 – 6 cm. The child is crying in pain and the father asks what he should do. Which one of the following immediate interventions has the best evidence of reducing burn depth, improving healing time, and decreasing skin graft requirements?', explanation = 'Burns are a common cause of injury in the United States, but most are minor and can be treated in the outpatient setting. The initial treatment goals for burn injuries include limiting the extent of the injury, cleaning the area, and managing pain. Removing clothing limits the injury related to scalding. The most effective way to limit the extent of injury is to cool the burn surface by running cool tap water over the burn surface for at least 20 minutes. This intervention has been shown to reduce burn depth, improve healing time, and decrease skin graft requirements. Ideally, burns should be cooled within the first 30 minutes of injury, but some evidence suggests benefit up to 3 hours after the initial injury. Applying ice to the burn surfaces is not recommended as a cooling strategy due to the risk of vasoconstriction, which can contribute to tissue damage. Wet dressings are not effective as a cooling strategy and are not recommended. For superficial burns such as those described in this patient, aloe vera and NSAIDs can be used to address pain after the initial cooling strategy, but these are not the recommended first step. Burns are classified by their depth: superficial (first degree), partial thickness (second degree), and full thickness (third degree). Superficial burns are limited to the epidermal layer. They are painful and appear red (blanchable), with intact skin and no blistering. Partial - thickness burns are deeper and involve injury to the dermis. Superficial partial - thickness burns may blister and be exudative, whereas deep partial - thickness burns are drier and do not blanch. Full - thickness burns involve the entire dermis and extend into the fat and connective tissue layers. They appear white rather than red, and are dry with a waxy appearance. Patients often experience less pain due to the destruction of nerve endings. Deep partial - thickness and full - thickness burns should be evaluated and treated at a burn center.', options = '["Cooling the burn surfaces with running tap water","Applying ice to the burn surfaces","Covering the burn surfaces with cool, wet gauze","Applying aloe vera gel to the burn surfaces and leaving them uncovered","Applying diclofenac gel to the burn surfaces and leaving them uncovered"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '8eb393c6-2c27-49c2-8c2a-bdb2d2c280d2';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 45 - year - old female with a past medical history of obesity and cigarette smoking presents with a popliteal deep vein thrombosis of the right leg, confirmed on ultrasonography. She urgery, trauma, has no prior history of venous thromboembolism and has not had any recent s or immobilization. She does not take any medications. Which one of the following anticoagulation regimens would be the most appropriate initial treatment?', explanation = 'Direct - acting oral anticoagulants (DO°Cs) are now recommended as monotherapy for outpatient management of deep vein thrombosis. DO°Cs reach therapeutic levels quickly; therefore, concomitant initiation of unfractionated or low - molecular - weight heparin (LMWH) is not necessary. DO°Cs have less major bleeding and require less monitoring, making them preferred over warfarin. Previously, unfractionated heparin was administered during hospitalization while warfarin was simultaneously initiated; however, subcutaneous LMWH can now be started with warfarin as an outpatient and continued until the goal INR is reached if a DO°C is unaffordable.', options = '["A direct - acting oral anticoagulant (DO°C) only","Low - molecular - weight heparin (LMWH) only","Warfarin only","LMWH for 7 days, followed by warfarin","Unfractionated heparin for 48 hours, followed by a DO°C"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '8b39da6d-cf92-4fcc-b44e-40274da96f14';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following puts a patient at the highest risk of developing breast cancer?', explanation = 'Women who received chest radiotherapy as children are at increased risk for breast cancer as adults, with those who received whole lung radiation at especially high risk. Other risk factors for breast cancer include the onset of menopause at >55 years of age, a first pregnancy at >35 years of age, and a first - degree relative with breast cancer. Patients with dense breasts have a higher amount of glandular and stromal tissue compared with adipose tissue on mammography and are at higher risk for breast cancer.', options = '["A first pregnancy at <30 years of age","Onset of menopause at <50 years of age","Fatty breasts on mammography","A grandmother with a history of breast cancer","Chest radiation therapy as a child"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'd1e7ab31-3750-4929-b204-1b1c047bf9f2';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An 83 - year - old female sees you for follow - up 2 weeks after being discharged home from an acute rehabilitation facility. She experienced an acute ischemic stroke 6 weeks ago and spent several weeks in the rehabilitation setting after an initial hospital sta y. Home health services have been assisting her since she returned home. Today she reports improved mobility, speech, and swallowing, but persistent difficulties with low mood. She finds it difficult to enjoy hobbies and avoids visiting with family and fri ends. She has been sleeping more than usual and finds it difficult to get out of bed in the morning. You diagnose poststroke depression. In addition to talk therapy, which one of the following is recommended as first - line therapy for this condition?', explanation = 'Poststroke depression (PSD) is a common complication that occurs in 20≥ – 60≥ of patients with stroke, depending on the definition used in diagnosis and the timing of symptom onset. The exact pathophysiology of PSD is unknown but appears complex and multifactorial. The incidence of PSD varies with the location of the stroke. Abnormal neurotransmitter and inflammatory marker levels have been associated with PSD. SSRIs such as escitalopram are considered first - line therapy for PSD. Other options include SNRIs, tricyclic antidepressants (TCAs), and newer multimodal agents such as vortioxetine. Bupropion may be considered if SSRIs are ineffective or cannot be tolerated. As a class, TCAs have a higher anticholinergic effect than SSRIs and are therefore not preferred, although nortriptyline has been evaluated in randomized, controlled trials and found to be effective in treating PSD. There is a growing body of evidence to support the use of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation, but it is not recommended as first - line treatment at this time.', options = '["Bupropion","Escitalopram (Lexapro)","Nortriptyline (Pamelor)","Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '160ccb59-e5d4-436b-9c37-4001846dc4c1';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Patients with which one of the following should be provided opioid overdose education and a prescription for naloxone?', explanation = 'The 2022 CDC clinical practice guideline for prescribing opioids recommends that clinicians offer naloxone to patients at increased risk of overdose, including patients with a history of substance use, overdose, and sleep - disordered breathing, as well as patients who take higher dosages of opioids (≥50 MME/day), take benzodiazepines with opioids, or are at risk of returning to higher opioid dosages with loss of tolerance, such as when tapering opioid dosages.', options = '["A history of substance use disorder","A prescription for alprazolam (Xanax), 1 mg nightly as needed","A 3 - day prescription for hydrocodone/acetaminophen, 5/325 mg twice daily","A prescription through hospice treatment for morphine, 10 mg as needed"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '7625f911-7836-4cdf-9a60-a27abd4c1889';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 55 - year - old female with a medical history of hypothyroidism, hypertension, and morbid obesity with a recent gastric bypass surgery presents with a history of dizziness, sweating, shaking, fatigue, and occasional fainting, occurring 1 – 2 hours after consum ing beverages containing dairy products or a high sugar content. Her blood glucose levels, measured with her husband''s glucometer during each episode, range between 50 mg/dL and 55 mg/dL. Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient''s symptoms?', explanation = 'The most likely cause of this patient''s symptoms is late dumping syndrome. Dumping syndrome is a common postbariatric surgery complication occurring in about 40≥ of patients. There are 2 types of dumping syndrome: early dumping syndrome and late dumping syndrome. Early dumping syndrome is caused by the rapid passage of nutrients into the small bowel, resulting in intestinal hormonal release and fluid shift. Symptoms occur within 30 – 60 minutes of eating and include abdominal pain, diarrhea, bloating, nausea, flushing, palpitations, sweating, tachycardia, hypotension, and syncope without chemical evidence of hypoglycemia. Late dumping syndrome is caused by the rapid absorption of carbohydrates, leading to exaggerated insulin secretion, resulting in chemical evidence of hypoglycemia occurring 1 – 3 hours after eating. Gastroparesis, unlike dumping syndrome, results from significantly delayed gastric emptying without hypoglycemia, often due to complications of diabetes mellitus. Idiopathic postprandial syndrome describes hypoglycemic - like symptoms that occur after eating without chemical evidence of hypoglycemia. Insulinoma is a rare insulin - producing tumor of the pancreas that causes hypoglycemia regardless of food intake timing.', options = '["Gastroparesis","Idiopathic postprandial syndrome","Insulinoma","Late dumping syndrome"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '01ada2cc-199d-4f0e-b786-935c2246d8b0';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 10 - month - old male is brought to your office with a 1 - day history of fussiness and tugging at his ear. The child''s mother says that he has had a fever this morning. He is up to date on all immunizations, and he does not have a history of previous ear infe ctions or recent illness. He has a history of hives after being given amoxicillin. On examination the child has a temperature of 39.2 °C (102.6 °F) but seems to be only slightly uncomfortable. When you examine his ears you note moderate bulging of the left tympanic membrane and normal findings in the right ear. All other findings are nor mal. According to the American Academy of Pediatrics guidelines, which one of the following would be the most appropriate initial management?', explanation = 'The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends antibiotic therapy for children ≥6 months of age with severe signs and symptoms of acute otitis media (AOM), including moderate or severe otalgia, otalgia lasting longer than 48 hours, or a temperature ≥39 °C (102 °F), whether the AOM is unilateral or bilateral (SOR B). Children younger than 24 months without severe symptoms should receive antibiotic therapy for bilateral AOM, whereas older children or those with unilateral AOM can be offered the option of observation and follow - up. The usual treatment for AOM is amoxicillin, but an antibiotic with additional β - lactamase coverage, such as amoxicillin/clavulanate, should be given if the child has received amoxicillin within the past 30 days, has concurrent purulent conjunctivitis, or has a history of AOM unresponsive to amoxicillin (SOR C). Penicillin - allergic patients should be treated with an alternative antibiotic such as cefdinir, cefuroxime, cefpodoxime, or ceftriaxone. Ciprofloxacin should not be used in children. Sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim is no longer effective for the treatment of acute otitis media due to evidence of Streptococcus pneumoniae resistance.', options = '["Amoxicillin","Amoxicillin/clavulanate (Augmentin)","Cefdinir","Ciprofloxacin (Cipro)","Sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '5c21a498-7751-4b99-9f8c-cb603bf7ea49';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 5 - year - old male is brought to the emergency department (ED) by his parents for evaluation after falling from a kitchen table just prior to arrival. The mother states that the child climbed onto the table and fell off before she could reach him. He landed directly on the right side of his head and did not lose consciousness. She witnessed 1 episode of vomiting after the fall but no additional episodes since then. On physical examination, the patient is tearful but consolable. You note a right - sided parieta l hematoma. There are no palpable skull fractures or signs of altered mental status. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', explanation = 'This patient likely has a mild traumatic brain injury (mTBI), or concussion, based on the mechanism of injury and the presence of vomiting. This patient''s TBI would be classified as mild due to the lack of worsening symptoms or additional concerning findings on examination, such as the child being fussier or holding his head. For these reasons, reassurance and outpatient observation with follow - up is the most appropriate next step. Routine imaging is not recommended for mTBI in children. There is no role for radiography of the skull in the management of mTBI or concussion. CT of the head or neck would only be indicated if the patient were experiencing acutely worsening symptoms, reporting or showing signs of headache, or had a suspected head or neck injury. There is no need to contact child protective services because there has been no delay in seeking care or the presence of other unusual physical findings or behaviors between the parents and child.', options = '["Providing reassurance and recommending outpatient follow - up","Observation in the ED for worsening symptoms","Radiography of the skull","CT of the head and neck","Contacting child protective services"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'b875834c-7902-4d6c-8084-d01854cb7eab';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 32 - year - old male presents for advice on smoking cessation. He has smoked 10 cigarettes per day for the past 10 years. His grandmother was recently diagnosed with lung cancer, and he is motivated to quit. You advise him that smoking cessation is the most important action that he can take for his health, and you counsel him about effective behavioral interventions. Which one of the following behavioral changes would improve this patient''s chances of smoking cessation?', explanation = 'Behavioral interventions are effective treatments for smoking cessation. Advising a patient who wishes to stop smoking to create a smoke - free home and car environment is a highly effective behavioral intervention. This advice is an important aspect of a brief 3 - step tobacco cessation intervention model (Ask, Advise, Assist/Connect). Caffeine intake does not play a role in smoking cessation. Switching to menthol cigarettes does not have a role in supporting smoking cessation. There is no high - or moderate - quality evidence to support hypnotherapy or acupuncture for smoking cessation. In addition to behavioral interventions, the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force also recommends providing FDA - approved pharmacotherapy such as nicotine replacement therapy, sustained - release bupropion hydrochloride, or varenicline. Combined interventions result in increased tobacco - cessation rates.', options = '["Creating a smoke - free home","Increasing his caffeine intake","Switching to menthol cigarettes","Undergoing hypnotherapy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'fdf65ed5-e20a-4dbe-9382-e800d5559150';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following medications is the recommended initial management of COPD in patients who are classified as GOLD group A?', explanation = 'Long - acting muscarinic antagonists (LAMAs) such as umeclidinium are recommended as the preferred initial management of COPD that is classified as GOLD group A. Long - acting β - agonists (LABAs) such as formoterol may be used as an alternative for these patients. LAMA/LABA combinations such as aclidinium bromide/formoterol are recommended as initial management of COPD that is classified as GOLD group B. LAMA/LABA combinations are also recommended for management of COPD that is classified as GOLD group E. Inhaled corticosteroid (ICS)/LAMA/LABA combinations such as fluticasone furoate/umeclidinium/vilanterol can also be considered for initial management of COPD that is classified as GOLD group E, especially if blood eosinophil levels are ≥300 cells/μL.', options = '["Inhaled umeclidinium (Incruse Ellipta)","Inhaled aclidinium bromide/formoterol (Duaklir Pressair)","Inhaled budesonide/formoterol (Symbicort)","Inhaled fluticasone furoate/umeclidinium/vilanterol (Trelegy Ellipta)","Nebulized formoterol (Perforomist)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'fd0bcee2-30f9-4d0c-a39f-3a6439ea2de7';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 29 - year - old female with type 2 diabetes is brought to the emergency department by her family, who state that she has grown increasingly confused over the last few days, with additional symptoms of polyuria and polydipsia. Her initial vital signs demonstr ate hypotension and tachycardia. Laboratory Findings Serum glucose 750 mg/dL Serum osmolality 350 mOsm/kg H O (N 275 – 295) Urine ketones trace Arterial pH 7.3 Anion gap normal Which one of the following would be the most appropriate initial treatment?', explanation = 'This patient presents with acute confusion, dehydration, hyperglycemia, and hyperosmolality. The appropriate diagnosis is hyperglycemic hyperosmolar state (HHS), rather than diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), given her lack of significant ketonuria and acidosis. She is hypovolemic and dehydrated as evidenced by her change in vital signs. Initial treatment consists of intravenous fluids with isotonic solutions, such as 0.9≥ normal saline or lactated Ringer solution. She will also need an intravenous insulin infusion of short - acting insulin at a dose of 0.05 units/kg/hr. After the initial fluid bolus, potassium chloride can be added to intravenous fluids to correct her total body potassium depletion. Sodium bicarbonate should only be considered if the arterial pH is <7.0 (see Figure 4 of the American Diabetes Association guideline for treatment pathways of DKA and HHS).', options = '["Subcutaneous short - acting insulin","Subcutaneous long - acting insulin","Intravenous isotonic fluid hydration","Intravenous isotonic fluid hydration with sodium bicarbonate"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '59328d2d-5daa-4207-8dc4-6fd94627f332';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 65 - year - old male with symptomatic heart failure presents for follow - up. He currently has no symptoms of dyspnea at rest, but has moderate to significant limitations with ordinary activity. His most recent echocardiogram showed a left ventricular ejection fraction of 38≥. His last hemoglobin A was the highest it has ever been at 6.3≥, and he does not take any glucose - lowering medications. His current medications include losartan (Cozaar), carvedilol (Coreg), furosemide (Lasix), and spironolactone (Aldact one). On examination he has a blood pressure of 120/75 mm Hg and an oxygen saturation of 94≥ on room air, and there are no pulmonary crackles or peripheral edema. Adding which one of the following would be most likely to further reduce this patient’s mortality risk?', explanation = 'Treatment with an SGLT2 inhibitor is recommended to decrease all - cause mortality in patients with heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF), regardless of the presence or absence of diabetes mellitus. According to guidelines from the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association, first - line medical management for symptomatic HFrEF is angiotensin receptor/neprilysin inhibitor (ARNi) therapy. If ARNi therapy is not feasible, an °CE inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker is second - line therapy. These patients should also receive therapy with a cardioselective β - blocker, a loop diuretic (for pulmonary congestion or edema), and a mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist. Neither calcium channel blockers (CCBs) nor thiazide diuretics provide mortality benefits in HFrEF; although thiazide diuretics may be used for the adjunctive management of symptomatic congestion and edema, CCBs may lead to worse cardiac outcomes. The potential mortality benefits of GLP - 1 receptor agonists in patients with HFrEF are still being investigated. Metformin has been shown to improve mortality in patients with heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (left ventricular ejection fraction >50≥).', options = '["A calcium channel blocker","A GLP - 1 receptor agonist","An SGLT2 inhibitor","A thiazide diuretic","Metformin"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'c60df00e-8b1d-4e35-8ed0-29c1b59348ef';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 45 - year - old male with a past medical history of hyperlipidemia and obesity presents with concerns of polydipsia and polyuria that have progressively worsened over the last 2 weeks. His older sister was recently diagnosed with type 2 diabetes and your pat ient asks to be tested. Which one of the following test results would be sufficient to diagnose diabetes in this patient?', explanation = 'According to guidelines from the American Diabetes Association, diabetes mellitus can be diagnosed with a random blood glucose level ≥200 mg/dL in patients with classic symptoms of hyperglycemia, such as polyuria and polydipsia, as seen in this patient. An 8 - hour fasting plasma glucose level ≥126 mg/dL, a hemoglobin A ≥6.5≥, or a 2 - hour plasma 1c glucose level ≥200 mg/dL on 75 - g oral glucose tolerance testing can also indicate diabetes but would require confirmatory testing with a second abnormal laboratory value to confirm the diagnosis. A fasting plasma glucose level 100 – 125 mg/dL or a hemoglobin A 5.7≥ – 6.4≥ suggests a diagnosis of prediabetes. A 1 - hour plasma glucose level ≥140 mg/dL on 50 - g oral glucose testing is an abnormal first step in a 2 - step screening approach for gestational diabetes mellitus in pregnant individuals.', options = '["A hemoglobin A ≥6.0≥ 1c","A 1 - hour plasma glucose level ≥140 mg/dL on 50 - g oral glucose testing","A fasting plasma glucose level ≥120 mg/dL","A random blood glucose level ≥200 mg/dL"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'd4b04143-1480-4c7c-a831-df9eb830c568';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 36 - year - old male presents to your office with continued pain in his right arm after sustaining a right forearm fracture 6 weeks ago that was treated with cast immobilization. At the time of the injury, he noted a severe, throbbing pain in his right forea rm that improved with NSAID therapy. Now, he feels a severe, sharp pain with burning and numbness throughout the arm and hand that worsens with any pressure, including clothing. He reports weakness in his right hand and notes that he drops objects such as cups. He is afebrile and his vital signs are within normal limits. An examination reveals pain to light touch in the right arm. The right arm is warmer to the touch than the left arm with trace edema noted. The patient''s right - hand grip is 4/5, and his lef t - hand grip is 5/5. You note 2+ radial and brachial pulses and normal bilateral reflexes. Which one of the following is the most likely etiology of this patient''s pain?', explanation = 'This patient meets the Budapest criteria for complex regional pain syndrome (CRPS) including hyperalgesia, temperature asymmetry, evidence of edema, and motor weakness following trauma to the limb. CRPS is a clinical diagnosis. The absence of fever or other signs of infection makes cellulitis unlikely. The examination findings make factitious disorder and functional neurologic symptom disorder (conversion disorder) unlikely. The absence of the characteristic stocking - glove altered sensation makes peripheral neuropathy unlikely.', options = '["Cellulitis","Complex regional pain syndrome","Factitious disorder","Functional neurologic symptom disorder (conversion disorder)","Peripheral neuropathy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'c90d33fd-6839-4a2b-bfe9-b7abcb11952a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 28 - year - old nulligravida has a 2 - to 3 - day history of severe lower abdominal pain. On examination the patient’s temperature is 37.7 °C (99.9 °F), bowel sounds are normal, and there is diffuse lower abdominal tenderness without rebound. On pelvic examinat ion there is adnexal tenderness and pain on cervical motion. Vaginal discharge shows leukocytes. A pregnancy test is negative. In addition to sexually transmitted infection testing and empiric treatment, which one of the following should you recommend?', explanation = 'This patient''s likely diagnosis is pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), and the diagnosis can be made clinically in most cases. In women at risk of PID, treatment should be initiated if any of the following are present: cervical motion tenderness, uterine tenderness, or adnexal tenderness. These criteria are considered sensitive for the diagnosis, but the clinician should be mindful to evaluate for other causes, such as appendicitis or tubo - ovarian abscess (TOA) as indicated by the history and physical examination. Appendicitis would likely cause unilateral pain. TOA often presents acutely with unilateral pain on examination and an adnexal mass. These findings may prompt the clinician to pursue additional testing such as pelvic ultrasonography. A pelvic ultrasound may show fluid - filled or thickened tubes in the setting of PID, but it is not routinely indicated. MRI may be necessary if an ultrasound were to demonstrate TOA or findings other than simple PID. CT of the abdomen may be completed to evaluate complications above the pelvis. Laparoscopy would not be the initial evaluation. This patient is acutely ill and repeating a pregnancy test a week later would not be appropriate.', options = '["No further testing","A repeat pregnancy test in 7 days","Pelvic ultrasonography","Pelvic MRI","Laparoscopy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '373b4c51-cba6-40c0-a87c-8b267d1c2bda';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 65 - year - old male with a past medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia presents to the urgent care clinic approximately 20 hours after experiencing an episode of sudden - onset right - hand weakness. He was suddenly unable to grasp his utensils whil e eating dinner. These symptoms resolved after about 20 minutes. His wife had encouraged him to seek urgent evaluation, but he declined because his symptoms had resolved. Today the patient''s vital signs include a blood pressure of 124/72 mm Hg, a heart rate of 80 beats/min, and a respiratory rate of 12/min. The neurologic examination findings are normal. An EKG shows normal sinus rhythm. The ABCD score is 4. Further management includes which one of the following regimens?', explanation = 'In patients presenting with a moderate - to high - risk TIA or minor stroke within 24 hours of symptom onset, dual antiplatelet therapy (DAPT) for 21 days prior to transitioning to a single antiplatelet agent decreases the 90 - day stroke risk from 7.8≥ to 5.2≥ compared to aspirin alone. This patient has symptoms consistent with a high - risk TIA based on an ABCD score (age, blood pressure, clinical features of TIA, duration, and diabetes mellitus history) of 4. Recommended management includes loading doses of clopidogrel (300 – 600 mg) and aspirin (50 – 325 mg) within 24 hours of symptom onset followed by clopidogrel (75 mg) and aspirin (50 – 325 mg daily) for 21 days. The patient can then transition to a single antiplatelet agent. Initial treatment with a single antiplatelet agent or with DAPT for less than 21 days does not reduce stroke risk compared to DAPT for 21 days.', options = '["Aspirin, 81 mg daily","Clopidogrel (Plavix), 300 mg on day 1, followed by 75 mg daily","Clopidogrel, 300 mg on day 1, followed by 75 mg daily on days 2 – 10; plus aspirin, 81 mg daily","Clopidogrel, 300 mg on day 1, followed by 75 mg daily on days 2 – 21; plus aspirin, 81 mg daily"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '58fea514-6f4e-4c48-9626-edbe4b2ec80a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 55 - year - old patient with a previous history of opioid use disorder and untreated hypertension presents to your office to establish care. They are now in recovery and would like to catch up on screening laboratory studies. Their blood pressure today is 16 0/90 mm Hg. Laboratory studies show elevated AST, ALT, and alkaline phosphatase levels and are positive for hepatitis C antibody and hepatitis C viral load. Testing for hepatitis B and HIV is negative. Lipids are elevated. You calculate an atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease 10 - year risk score of 10≥. A right upper quadrant ultrasound shows fibrotic changes of the liver. The patient is surprised that they have liver damage, as they feel well and have never consumed much alcohol. In addition to referring the patient to a gastroenterologist, which one of the following should you begin now to improve fibrotic changes?', explanation = 'Treatment of hepatitis C in patients with metabolic dysfunction – associated steatohepatitis (formerly known as nonalcoholic steatohepatitis) can improve fibrotic changes, as can bariatric surgery. Prophylactic antibiotics should be initiated to prevent spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) in patients with a history of SBP; low ascitic fluid protein levels (<1.5 g/dL); advanced hepatic disease as indicated by a Child - Pugh score ≥9 or a bilirubin level ≥3 mg/dL; or renal disease as indicated by a serum creatinine level ≥1.2 mg/dL or a serum sodium level ≤130 mEq/L. Nonselective β - blockers should be started in patients with significant varices seen on upper endoscopy. Coinfection with hepatitis C virus and HIV increases a patient''s risk of fibrotic progression to cirrhosis. A conversation regarding risks and benefits of initiating pre - exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) would be beneficial; however, PrEP has not been shown to improve fibrotic changes. Offering treatment for viral hepatitis along with PrEP increases access for patients who are at risk of coinfection. In individuals with metabolic dysfunction – associated steatotic liver disease (MASLD) (formerly known as nonalcoholic fatty liver disease) and cirrhosis, antibiotic prophylaxis is recommended in specific scenarios: in patients with a history of SBP, during episodes of acute upper gastrointestinal bleeding, and in select high - risk patients with low ascitic fluid protein levels (<1.5 g/dL) along with either advanced liver disease (Child - Pugh score ≥9 and a bilirubin level ≥3 mg/dL) or signs of renal impairment (a creatinine level ≥1.2 mg/dL, a BUN level ≥25 mg/dL, or a sodium level ≤130 mEq/L).', options = '["Treatment of hepatitis C","Prophylactic antibiotics","A nonselective β - blocker","Pre - exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) for HIV","Upper endoscopy with banding of any varices"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '320a86e0-7c6e-48a5-b036-d969164c3a23';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 46 - year - old female sees you for an annual well woman visit. Her only concern is pelvic pressure that becomes more bothersome throughout the day. She notes occasional urinary incontinence of small amounts when coughing or running. She says these symptoms mildly bother her, and mostly wants to make sure there is not a more serious problem. On physical examination, using the lower half of a bivalve speculum, you note a prolapse of the anterior wall, 0.5 cm proximal to the hymenal ring. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step for this patient?', explanation = 'Pelvic organ prolapse is a common problem, and can be described as apical, of the anterior wall, or of the posterior wall. The Pelvic Organ Prolapse Quantification system can be used to evaluate the prolapse and determine grading. A grade 2 prolapse indicates a prolapse that extends within 1 cm above or below the hymenal ring. Pelvic floor muscle training can reduce prolapse by 1 – 2 cm and provide subjective improvement in symptoms. There is no clear evidence of the benefit of estrogen alone for pelvic organ prolapse. Surgical management is often the ultimate treatment for pelvic organ prolapse, but it is important to note that urinary incontinence can worsen after repair. This patient is minimally bothered by her symptoms; therefore, surgical treatment would not be recommended at this time but may be indicated in the future. Pelvic organ prolapse is generally progressive until menopause, after which it can alternate between regression and progression.', options = '["Reassurance only","Pelvic floor muscle training","Topical estrogen","Surgical consultation"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '661a4a4f-550d-4d3f-876e-706394baa035';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 72 - year - old male with a past medical history of coronary artery disease, COPD, and hyperlipidemia sees you because of an acute onset of left lower leg pain 1 hour ago. He was in his usual state of health when the pain occurred. His left foot is numb and cold, and he is having difficulty walking. He has a 60 - pack - year smoking history. Physical examination findings include a mottled appearance of the left lower leg and foot. Posterior tibial and dorsalis pedis pulses are absent. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate first step in management?', explanation = 'This patient''s presentation is concerning for acute limb ischemia and he requires immediate transfer to an emergency facility with vascular surgeon accessibility (SOR C). Anticoagulation with unfractionated heparin should be started soon after arrival. Acute limb ischemia is a vascular emergency as skeletal muscle can only survive 4 – 6 hours without blood flow. Acute limb ischemia is characterized by the 6 P ’s: pain, pallor, poikilothermia, pulselessness, paresthesia, and paralysis. Direct - acting oral anticoagulants can be used to manage symptomatic peripheral artery disease (PAD), but not for acute management of limb ischemia. While duplex ultrasonography or CT angiography can be used to determine the presence and location of the obstructed vessel, transfer to an emergency facility should not be delayed for imaging. Referral to a vascular surgeon would delay treatment and would be more appropriate for chronic PAD symptoms.', options = '["Rivaroxaban (Xarelto)","Stat duplex ultrasonography","Stat CT angiography","Expedited outpatient referral to a vascular surgeon","Transfer to the nearest emergency department with access to a vascular surgeon"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'bfadec1a-8e15-40b4-b2a3-e8655a3683a0';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 22 - year - old male presents with a 5 - day history of left lower leg pain over the midshaft of his tibia. Two months ago, he started training for a half marathon. Radiographs performed yesterday at an urgent care clinic were normal. You suspect a bone stress injury. Which one of the following is the preferred definitive imaging modality to evaluate for a bone stress injury?', explanation = 'Bone stress injuries are typically overuse injuries that are caused by an accumulation of bone microdamage. They often occur after an increase in the intensity, frequency, or interval of training. They can also occur when there is structurally compromised bone (osteoporosis, tumors, infections) as normal physiologic loads can damage such compromised bone. Radiography is the initial imaging modality because of its high specificity, despite its low sensitivity. If the radiograph is negative and the patient remains symptomatic, then MRI is the preferred follow - up study for definitive diagnosis. It is preferred over CT and nuclear bone scintigraphy because it has higher sensitivity and specificity and avoids the use of radiation. Repeat radiography is not the preferred definitive imaging modality because radiographs are often negative when taken within the first 2 – 3 weeks of symptoms. Point - of - care ultrasonography can be used by trained clinicians as an adjunct modality, but its sensitivity is not as high as the sensitivity of MRI.', options = '["Repeat radiography in 1 week","Point - of - care ultrasonography","CT","MRI","Nuclear bone scintigraphy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'c957b7f4-e86b-41ad-99e0-6ee2ffa8767f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 32 - year - old female presents to an urgent care clinic with a flare - up of her usually well - controlled chronic urticaria. She takes cetirizine (Zyrtec), 10 mg daily. Which one of the following should you recommend?', explanation = 'The first - line treatment of chronic urticaria is an oral second - generation H - antihistamine. If that is not effective, a reasonable next step is to increase the H - antihistamine, up to 4 1 times the usual FDA - recommended dosing. Current evidence does not strongly support the effectiveness of a pseudoallergen - free diet in managing chronic urticaria. Nasal corticosteroids are effective for allergic rhinitis but have not been found to be useful for chronic urticaria. A short course of oral corticosteroids, such as prednisone, can be effective as a short - term solution for a flare - up but is not recommended for chronic control. Cyclosporine is only recommended for patients with severe refractory symptoms that have not responded to increased dosages of second - generation antihistamines and a trial of H - blockers. Omalizumab is effective for chronic urticaria and would be indicated if 2 aggressive antihistamine therapy is unsuccessful.', options = '["A pseudoallergen - free diet","Doubling the cetirizine dosage","A nasal corticosteroid","Cyclosporine (Sandimmune)","Omalizumab (Xolair)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '477d7d68-6807-4fde-a240-f46796dc4e5b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 35 - year - old female comes to your office with an 8 - day history of nasal congestion, rhinorrhea, and cough. Based on guidelines from the Infectious Diseases Society of America, this patient should be treated with antibiotic therapy if she has which one of the following additional symptoms?', explanation = 'It is difficult to adequately distinguish between viral sinusitis and acute bacterial rhinosinusitis. However, most instances of acute bacterial rhinosinusitis improve without antibiotics. Major symptoms of sinusitis include purulent nasal discharge, nasal congestion, facial pain or pressure, decreased smell, and fever. Minor symptoms include headaches, cough, fatigue, ear pain or pressure, halitosis, and tooth pain. If adequate follow - up can be ensured, watchful waiting and symptomatic management is recommended for up to 10 days. Patients with severe symptoms (fever ≥39 °C with purulent nasal discharge and/or facial pain) or those with double sickening (new symptoms following improvement of an upper respiratory infection) should be treated immediately with empiric antibiotics.', options = '["A fever up to 38.0 °C (100.4 °F)","Halitosis and tooth pain","An increase in nasal discharge after an initial improvement of symptoms","Purulent rhinorrhea"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '52940675-859c-48e9-8855-853807ce606a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'You are seeing a 44 - year - old female who has a 25 - pack - year smoking history. She quit smoking 6 years ago after a friend received a diagnosis of lung cancer. According to U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommendations, lung cancer screening should be initiated at what age in this patient?', explanation = 'Lung cancer is the leading cause of cancer death in the United States, with approximately 90≥ of cases linked to smoking. In 2021, the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommended annual screening with low - dose CT in adults 50 – 80 years of age who have a 20 - pack - year smoking history and either currently smoke or have quit within the past 15 years.', options = '["No screening is indicated","45","50","55","60"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '666d79f3-f9fe-466f-9d29-56e227a9128d';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 25 - year - old male presents with a 5 - day history of dysuria and mucopurulent penile discharge. On examination the urethral meatus is erythematous and a small amount of discharge is noted. A urine dipstick is positive for leukocyte esterase and a nucleic ac id amplification test is negative for Neisseria gonorrhoeae and Chlamydia trachomatis . Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?', explanation = 'This patient has nongonococcal urethritis, which should be treated with azithromycin. Symptoms of urethritis include dysuria, purulent or mucopurulent urethral discharge, and urethral discomfort and/or erythema. Diagnostic criteria include typical signs and symptoms or a history of exposure along with ≥10 WBCs/hpf on a first - void urinalysis, ≥2 WBCs/oil immersion field found on Gram stain of the discharge, or a positive leukocyte esterase with first - void urine. At least half of nongonococcal urethritis cases have no known etiologic agent. Of the cases with known etiologies, Mycoplasma genitalium is responsible for 15≥ – 20≥. Treatment options for M genitalium include azithromycin, 1 g orally; doxycycline, 100 mg twice daily for 1 week; or moxifloxacin, 400 mg orally for 7 – 14 days. If the results of nucleic acid amplification testing for gonorrhea and chlamydia are unavailable, then intramuscular ceftriaxone plus a 7 - day course of oral doxycycline would be appropriate and can be used for empiric therapy while awaiting results. Intramuscular gentamicin plus oral azithromycin is used as an alternative treatment regimen for Neisseria gonorrhoeae . Metronidazole is used to treat Trichomonas, which represents 1≥ – 8≥ of cases in men and should be diagnosed using a molecular - based test. Levofloxacin is a treatment option for chlamydia and is not first line.', options = '["Azithromycin (Zithromax), 1 g orally once","Levofloxacin, 500 mg orally for 7 days","Ceftriaxone, 500 mg intramuscularly once","Gentamicin, 240 mg intramuscularly once, plus azithromycin, 2 g orally once","Metronidazole, 2 g orally once, plus doxycycline, 100 mg orally twice daily for 7 days"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '7a6d746a-9484-4838-8c7b-0fe90b5e919f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 55 - year - old female presents to the emergency department with what she describes as the worst headache of her life that began suddenly 1 hour ago. Her medical history is significant for tobacco use and uncontrolled hypertension. She indicates that she has had a few headaches over the last month, but today''s headache came on suddenly and is extremely intense, unlike the previous headaches. There is no history of head trauma. Her accompanying relative adds that the patient has been experiencing waxing and waning levels of consciousness since the sudden onset of the headache. She has vomited several times, secondary to pain from the headache. Which one of the following is the most important, immediate next step in management?', explanation = 'This patient''s clinical picture is most consistent with a subarachnoid hemorrhage. Patients typically describe this as a sudden onset of the worst headache they have experienced. The most immediate and meaningful next step is to order a CT scan of the head to verify the diagnosis of subarachnoid hemorrhage. The diagnosis and management of subarachnoid hemorrhage is time sensitive. Neurosurgery should be consulted immediately if subarachnoid hemorrhage is verified. Brain MRI would likely take longer to obtain than head CT and is not diagnostically advantageous in subarachnoid hemorrhage compared to a head CT. Pain and nausea control are reasonable, but a CT scan of the head should take precedence because of the time sensitivity of diagnosis and management. A lumbar puncture should be considered if the head CT scan is negative but clinical suspicion for subarachnoid hemorrhage remains high, especially if the presentation occurs >6 hours after onset.', options = '["Morphine","Ondansetron","Head CT","Brain MRI","Lumbar puncture"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '23cd0664-c133-40fb-ab01-56e68512c755';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 28 - year - old male who uses cannabis daily presents with a 2 - week history of persistent nausea and vomiting. He notes little relief from previously prescribed ondansetron but does feel better during a hot shower. While tapering his cannabis use, which one of the following would be most likely to improve this patient''s nausea?', explanation = 'This patient has cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome, characterized by heavy chronic cannabis use and nausea that improves with hot baths or showers. Current evidence suggests that haloperidol is more effective than more traditionally used antiemetics, such as metoclopramide or prochlorperazine, or corticosteroids in managing nausea associated with this syndrome. Topical capsaicin has also been shown to be effective. Topical capsaicin, when applied to the upper abdomen, may help alleviate symptoms by activating transient receptor potential vanilloid 1 (TRPV1) receptors. This mechanism can lead to desensitization of sensory nerve fibers, potentially reducing the need for antiemetic medications. Benzodiazepines may help acutely, and tricyclic antidepressants may have efficacy for longer - term management. Cessation of cannabis use is necessary for definitive treatment. Diclofenac gel is not appropriate pharmacotherapy for cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome.', options = '["Topical diclofenac gel","Haloperidol","Metoclopramide (Reglan)","Prednisone","Prochlorperazine"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '06cd4eb0-82c9-4e74-9dbc-353347b98e9c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 30 - year - old female with fibromyalgia sees you for follow - up. Her symptoms include widespread pain and prominent fatigue. At your advice, she has engaged in a trial of multidisciplinary, nonpharmacologic treatment including structured exercise, cognitive behavioral therapy, and therapeutic massage, and has experienced only partial improvement in her symptoms. She expresses interest in trying a medication to treat her pain. Which one of the following medications would be most likely to improve this patient''s pain?', explanation = 'Duloxetine is an SNRI that is effective for treating fibromyalgia pain (SOR A). Other medications with level A evidence of effectiveness in reducing fibromyalgia - related pain include amitriptyline, cyclobenzaprine, and pregabalin. The SNRI milnacipran also has level A evidence for reducing fibromyalgia - related pain and has evidence for reducing fatigue and improving cognition in patients with fibromyalgia. Other SNRIs, including venlafaxine, have not been studied as extensively. Current evidence is insufficient to support acetaminophen or gabapentin use to treat fibromyalgia pain. Similarly, there is insufficient evidence to support the routine use of opioids such as hydrocodone, which are associated with a significant risk of adverse effects, dependence, misuse, and worsening hyperalgesia. NSAIDs such as ibuprofen are no better than placebo and introduce significant risk of adverse effects.', options = '["Acetaminophen","Duloxetine (Cymbalta)","Gabapentin (Neurontin)","Hydrocodone/acetaminophen","Ibuprofen"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '7bc90868-e2d7-44b1-ad1a-7c99256479ae';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An 8 - year - old male is brought to your office by his parents because of concerns about ongoing nocturnal enuresis. He wets his bed several nights per week despite behavioral interventions. He has no daytime urinary symptoms. Physical examination findings an d urinalysis are normal. You discuss treatment options and the parents indicate a preference for medication, as the patient will be attending an overnight summer camp in several weeks. Which one of the following would be the preferred pharmacologic treatment for this child’s nocturnal enuresis?', explanation = 'Behavioral methods and enuresis alarms are first - line treatments for monosymptomatic nocturnal enuresis without an identifiable cause. If pharmacotherapy is initiated, intranasal or oral desmopressin is acceptable. Imipramine and oxybutynin are additional options if there is no response to oral desmopressin. Tamsulosin is not recommended for this indication.', options = '["Desmopressin (DDAVP)","Imipramine","Oxybutynin","Tamsulosin (Flomax)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '141a578a-e4d0-4864-a1f1-16d17770229b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 25 - year - old male with a childhood diagnosis of attention - deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) presents for re - evaluation of ADHD. He did not take medication for ADHD as a child. He is now having problems with attention and concentration that are affecti ng his work. He was recently placed on a stimulant medication, but had to discontinue it when his blood pressure and heart rate became elevated. He is still interested in pharmacologic therapy. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next medication?', explanation = 'Stimulants are first - line pharmacotherapy for adults with attention - deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) given the extensive data supporting their effectiveness. However, there are potential adverse effects that can prevent patients from taking them, such as headaches, insomnia, poor appetite, weight loss, anxiety, depression, elevated heart rate, and elevated blood pressure. When stimulants are not tolerated or do not provide an adequate response, the second - line therapy would be an SNRI such as atomoxetine or viloxazine. Clonidine and guanfacine are only approved for the treatment of ADHD in children and adolescents. Although they are sometimes used off - label in adults, there is limited evidence to support such use. Tricyclic antidepressants such as nortriptyline have limited evidence and are not approved for ADHD treatment. Escitalopram is not effective for treating ADHD.', options = '["Atomoxetine (Strattera)","Clonidine","Escitalopram (Lexapro)","Guanfacine","Nortriptyline (Pamelor)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '097323ca-6026-4cc1-b409-61d485b6ad8e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 19 - year - old college basketball player consults you for follow - up after sustaining an anterior shoulder dislocation for the first time. He initially presented to the emergency department where his shoulder was reduced and immobilized in a sling. Which one of the following is most likely to decrease the risk of future recurrence?', explanation = 'Although anterior shoulder dislocations have a high rate of recurrence (up to 90≥), evidence from cohort studies has consistently found a lower rate of recurrence in active patients <25 years of age who have received surgical treatment for first - time dislocations. Because of this patient''s age and activity level, referral for surgical repair would be appropriate. Other treatment options for anterior shoulder dislocation include the use of a sling for 2 – 4 weeks with graduated rehabilitation of passive and active range of motion. If no surgery is warranted, athletes can return to play when they are pain free with symmetrical shoulder range of motion and able to perform sport - specific motions, which can be as early as 2 – 3 weeks after injury. Intra - articular corticosteroids are not advised after a shoulder dislocation.', options = '["Continued sling use for 4 weeks","Completion of a course of physical therapy","Administration of an intra - articular corticosteroid injection","Surgical repair"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'cf9869f6-c86b-47f7-bea0-a95ff4c51a3e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Of the following cognitive biases, which one best describes the practice of prioritizing data that supports an initial impression, even when the initial impression is incorrect?', explanation = 'Anchoring bias describes the practice of physicians prioritizing information and data that supports their initial impressions, even when these impressions are incorrect. In other words, it is when physicians are biased toward their first impression. Availability bias describes the likelihood of a diagnosis being erroneously linked to how easy it is to think of examples. Implicit bias is defined as attitudes and beliefs about race, ethnicity, age, ability, gender, or other characteristics. Implicit bias operates on an unconscious level and can only be measured indirectly. Outcomes bias refers to the attribution of all results to prior decisions, regardless of whether there is a reason to do so.', options = '["Anchoring","Availability","Implicit","Outcomes"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '0eeb4627-95e6-42fc-9739-a66448916b04';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 32 - year - old gravida 2 para 2 female who is 3 weeks post partum presents to the local urgent care center for left breast pain, swelling, and redness that started a few hours ago. She does not have fever or chills. A breast examination is significant for w arm, tender, and mildly erythematous nodules localized to the upper outer quadrant of the left breast. In addition to initiating NSAIDs, which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', explanation = 'Mastitis is a spectrum of inflammatory breast conditions, which includes lactational or inflammatory mastitis, bacterial mastitis, breast abscess, postpartum breast engorgement, and more. Patients with inflammatory mastitis exhibit unilateral breast erythema, swelling, and pain and may experience systemic inflammatory responses such as fever, malaise, or headache. The initial steps in managing inflammatory mastitis are supportive care with NSAIDs, cold compresses, and watchful waiting. Inflammatory mastitis is diagnosed clinically and does not require laboratory testing or imaging. If a patient''s symptoms worsen or do not improve within 24 – 48 hours with conservative measures, narrow - spectrum antibiotics targeting the most common organisms ( Staphylococcus species and Streptococcus species) should be empirically initiated for bacterial mastitis. Warm compresses and frequent breast pumping for complete breast emptying to avoid milk stasis are no longer recommended. CBC and C - reactive protein testing are not helpful as these levels can be elevated in both inflammatory and bacterial mastitis. Breast milk cultures are seldom necessary because they may produce false - positive results caused by normal skin bacteria colonization.', options = '["Applying cold compresses to the affected breast","Applying warm compresses to the affected breast","Using a manual breast pump on the affected breast for complete breast emptying","Obtaining a CBC and C - reactive protein levels","Obtaining a breast milk culture"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'f5a61548-0a98-48e6-8f1c-407d949dae77';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A young couple in your practice presents for preconception counseling. Both partners are known carriers of cystic fibrosis (CF). They ask what risk this poses to their future children. Which one of the following accurately reflects the risk of CF disease transmission to any potential offspring of this couple?', explanation = 'Cystic fibrosis is a genetic disorder with an autosomal recessive pattern of inheritance. People who are affected by the disease are homozygous for the condition, with 2 copies of the mutated gene. Carriers are heterozygous for the condition with 1 mutated gene and 1 normal gene. When both partners in a couple are carriers, any potential offspring has a 25≥ chance of being affected, a 50≥ chance of being an unaffected carrier, and a 25≥ chance of being an unaffected noncarrier.', options = '["25≥ risk of being affected and 25≥ risk of being a carrier","25≥ risk of being affected and 50≥ risk of being a carrier","50≥ risk of being affected and 25≥ risk of being a carrier","50≥ risk of being affected and 50≥ risk of being a carrier"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'a0e1cc1c-0085-4cf7-8d34-8492757edda1';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 47 - year - old nurse presents with a 9 - month history of fatigue and brain fog that has kept them from working. Their symptoms began after a confirmed diagnosis of COVID - 19. They report sleeping at least 7 hours per night but wake unrefreshed and experience lightheadedness throughout the day. They used to run 4 miles 5 days per week but now report feeling exhausted and experience energy crashes after showering and getting dressed. The patient''s vital signs and BMI are normal. A physical examination is unremar kable. Their Patient Health Questionnaire – 9 (PHQ - 9) score is 3. A CBC, TSH level, basic metabolic panel, and erythrocyte sedimentation rate are within the normal range. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', explanation = 'Based on the National Academy of Medicine criteria for myalgic encephalomyelitis/chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS), this patient has demonstrated the core symptoms of ME/CFS (unrefreshing sleep, new - onset fatigue, and postexertional malaise) for at least 6 months, in addition to brain fog and lightheadedness. Notably, their symptoms developed after a previous COVID - 19 infection, an illness that is commonly associated with ME/CFS. A Patient Health Questionnaire – 9 (PHQ - 9) score of 3 indicates no or minimal depression, which would not account for severe fatigue or energy crashes after minimal exertion. Exercise may actually improve depression. Secondary causes of fatigue, such as fibromyalgia and systemic lupus erythematosus, typically improve with exercise. Although obstructive sleep apnea may cause unrefreshing sleep, it is not associated with profound fatigue and postexertional malaise.', options = '["Depression","Fibromyalgia","Myalgic encephalomyelitis/chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS)","Obstructive sleep apnea","Systemic lupus erythematosus"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '2d229d86-b1b9-416d-9e10-330ce93048f3';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 62 - year - old male is brought to the clinic by his wife for fatigue. His wife says he has been sleeping in the recliner rather than in bed and has been less active over the last several weeks. He reports that his clothes have been fitting tightly and he ha s gained weight despite feeling full early in a meal. He also notes difficulty bending over to tie his shoes and pet the dog. He has no chest pain or pressure and has not traveled recently. His past medical history is notable for a myocardial infarction 5 years ago treated with a stent, and elevated cholesterol. He has a 30 - pack - year smoking history but quit 20 years ago. His medications include aspirin, 81 mg daily; lisinopril (Zestril), 20 mg daily; and metoprolol succinate (Toprol - XL), 50 mg daily. On examination he has a blood pressure of 110/65 mm Hg, a pulse rate of 89 beats/min, and an oxygen saturation of 95≥ on room air. You also note mildly increased work of breathing, a regular heart rate, and a laterally displaced apical impulse. Which one of the following tests would most likely confirm this patient’s underlying diagnosis?', explanation = 'Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF) is a major public health concern affecting more than 6.5 million U.S. adults. Family physicians should be familiar with its typical clinical presentations and diagnosis, which is best established using echocardiography. Symptoms vary and may include dyspnea, ankle edema, and fatigue. Orthopnea, as evident by modification of sleeping from supine to reclined or semi - reclined, is also common. Symptoms of right - sided heart failure, such as early satiety, abdominal bloating, ill - fitting clothes, and shortness of breath when bent forward, are also frequently encountered, but are less specific. Physical examination may reveal signs of congestion such as elevated jugular venous pressure, S gallop, or a laterally displaced 3 apical impulse. Some predictors of HFrEF include increased heart rate, coronary artery disease (hazard ratio [HR] 1.73), and previous myocardial infarction (MI) (HR 3.49). The diagnosis is made by documenting left ventricular systolic dysfunction with a left ventricular ejection fraction ≤40≥ and an elevated BNP level. An EKG is a key component of the workup and evaluation of contributing factors, such as arrhythmia or acute MI, but not diagnosis. A chest x - ray, while quick and readily available, may identify cardiomegaly or vascular congestion but is normal in approximately 20≥ of those with acute HFrEF, limiting diagnostic utility. Given this patient''s history of MI, CT angiography would be inappropriate and is typically reserved for evaluating coronary artery disease in low - risk patients. CT angiography is used to evaluate for pulmonary embolism, which is less likely, given this patient''s lack of immobility, prolonged travel, or other risk factors, as well as a history and physical examination that favor heart failure (displaced apical impulse, orthopnea, abdominal distention/weight gain).', options = '["EKG","Echocardiography","X - ray of the chest","CT angiography of the heart","CT angiography of the lungs"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '41a27c0b-06ad-4593-8c67-4a68f24399cf';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 3 - year - old male is brought to your office by his parents for a routine well child visit. He is up to date on vaccines and the parents have no concerns to discuss today. According to the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force, this child should be screened for which one of the following conditions?', explanation = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) recommends vision screening at least once in all children 3 – 5 years of age to detect amblyopia or its risk factors (B recommendation). Screening may be performed using visual acuity testing with picture identification, Snellen or "tumbling E," or by an automated device that assesses visual acuity. Early identification of vision disorders can help prevent permanent vision loss due to amblyopia. Anemia screening is recommended for all children at 1 year of age by the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP), but this approach was found to have insufficient evidence of benefit by the USPSTF (I recommendation). Screening for autism spectrum disorder is recommended by the AAP at 18 and 24 months of age, but the USPSTF found insufficient evidence that universal screening results in improved care in families without concerns about their child''s development (I recommendation). The USPSTF found insufficient evidence of benefit of screening for dental caries in children <5 years of age (I recommendation). Instead, it recommends that fluoride varnish be applied every 3 – 6 months in all children 6 months to 5 years of age to prevent dental caries (B recommendation). This should be performed in the family physician''s office if it has not been applied by a dentist. Additionally, an oral fluoride supplement is recommended to prevent dental caries in children without adequate fluoride in their water supply (B recommendation). Universal hearing screening is recommended for newborns, but screening at this age is not recommended.', options = '["Amblyopia","Anemia","Autism spectrum disorder","Dental caries","Hearing loss"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '54175f24-87dc-4be0-95ba-1e854d9308db';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 50 - year - old female comes to your clinic for an annual wellness examination. Her past medical history is notable for dermatomyositis diagnosed 2 years ago. She is otherwise healthy and her BMI is normal. Patients with dermatomyositis are at increased risk of which one of the following conditions?', explanation = 'While counseling on diet and exercise and screening for diabetes mellitus and hyperlipidemia are important, malignancy screening is the most important component of the wellness visit in this patient with dermatomyositis diagnosed after the age of 40. Cancer is a leading cause of death in this patient population and is diagnosed in up to 25≥ of these patients within 3 years of their dermatomyositis diagnosis. The most likely cancers in this population include adenocarcinomas of the ovary, lung, pancreas, stomach, and colon as well as non - Hodgkin lymphoma. Population - level cancer screening recommendations are generally insufficient for this population, and advanced cancer screening modalities, including CT scans and PET scans, may be recommended based on the patient''s individual risk factors to target these types of cancers. Chronic kidney disease and obesity have not been observed to have an increased risk in patients with dermatomyositis.', options = '["Chronic kidney disease","Diabetes mellitus","Hyperlipidemia","Malignancy","Obesity"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '93d414e1-df85-4c91-9ad1-d474cb188f0e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An otherwise healthy 15 - year - old female presents for evaluation of a 7 - month history of heavy menstrual bleeding. Her periods are 10 days long, irregular, and require 10 tampons per day. She sometimes passes large clots. Other than some fatigue, she feels well today and her vital signs are normal. A point - of - care hemoglobin level is 10.2 g/dL (N 12.0 – 16.0). Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in evaluation?', explanation = 'Heavy menstrual bleeding (HMB) is very common in adolescents and may be a sign of an underlying bleeding disorder. Although bleeding disorders affect 1≥ – 2≥ of the general population, the prevalence increases to 20≥ among adolescent girls with heavy menstrual bleeding. Platelet dysfunction and von Willebrand disease are most commonly identified. Evaluation for bleeding disorders is indicated when there is frequent pad or tampon use (>1 every 1 – 2 hours); menstrual bleeding lasting longer than 7 days; passage of clots larger than 1 inch in diameter; a personal history of anemia treatment, excessive bleeding with tooth extraction or surgery, or excessive bruising; or a family history of a bleeding disorder. The initial workup for HMB in an adolescent includes a CBC; a prothrombin time, partial thromboplastin time, and INR; a von Willebrand panel; and hCG, ferritin, fibrinogen, and TSH levels. Testing for chlamydia and gonorrhea should be considered in sexually active patients. Testosterone, prolactin, and DHEA levels should be obtained if there are signs of polycystic ovary syndrome or other endocrine disorders. Levels of FSH, LH, estrogen, and progesterone are not helpful in the evaluation of excessive uterine bleeding. Pelvic imaging is not routinely necessary but should be considered for HMB that does not respond to initial management. Hormonal contraceptives and tranexamic acid may be used for the treatment of HMB, but workup for a bleeding disorder is the most important first step.', options = '["Testing for a bleeding disorder","FSH and LH levels","Estrogen and progesterone levels","Pelvic ultrasonography","Pelvic MRI"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'ff0d258d-edbe-4fb0-b2ec-aac0668d4f71';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 45 - year - old patient presents with a 6 - month history of epigastric burning pain that occurs several days per week. The pain does not seem to have a clear correlation to eating. There has been no substernal pain or regurgitation and no weight loss, vomitin g, diarrhea, constipation, fever, night sweats, or fatigue. The patient has no prior medical history and takes no medications, but has tried calcium carbonate occasionally without benefit. A physical examination reveals normal vital signs and no abdominal abnormalities or enlarged lymph nodes. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'This patient presents with symptoms of dyspepsia. Dyspepsia is a diagnosis of exclusion and should be considered if at least 1 of the following symptoms is present: early satiety, epigastric pain, epigastric burning, and postprandial fullness. The majority of patients diagnosed with dyspepsia have functional dyspepsia with no evidence of organic disease on endoscopy. Testing for and treating Helicobacter pylori infection is recommended in patients with dyspepsia, with evidence of improvement 1 year after treatment. The stool antigen test and the urea breath test are the preferred noninvasive options for detecting H pylori . Serum testing for H pylori is not recommended because it has lower sensitivity and specificity than other noninvasive tests. Sucralfate has not been shown to be effective for dyspepsia. Abdominal ultrasonography, particularly of the upper abdomen, is indicated when evaluating for liver pathology or gallbladder disease but is not useful for investigating dyspepsia. Endoscopy is recommended for patients >60 years of age with new dyspepsia, and for patients <60 years of age with multiple or severe alarm symptoms, such as marked weight loss, rapidly progressive dysphagia, an epigastric mass, or supraclavicular lymphadenopathy.', options = '["Sucralfate (Carafate)","Stool antigen testing for Helicobacter pylori","Serum testing for H pylori","Abdominal ultrasonography","Referral for upper endoscopy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'ae767d50-3d59-406c-8cd7-31ffd211281c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 48 - year - old female comes to your office for a health maintenance examination. She is currently asymptomatic but has a medical history of renal calculi. Laboratory studies reveal a serum calcium level of 12.1 mg/dL (N 8.7 – 10.2), confirmed by an ionized ca lcium level. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step at this time?', explanation = 'Hypercalcemia is commonly identified through a metabolic panel and should be confirmed with a corrected or ionized calcium level. The most common cause of hypercalcemia is primary hyperparathyroidism, but any underlying malignancy should be ruled out. A thorough history should assess for symptoms such as arrhythmias, hypertension, abdominal pain, arthralgias, fractures, mental status changes, anxiety, depression, and nephrolithiasis. Dietary intake of calcium and phosphorus, use of medications such as lithium, and a family history of multiple endocrine neoplasia are also important to evaluate. After confirming hypercalcemia, the initial test should be a parathyroid hormone (PTH) level. If the PTH level is elevated, then 25 - hydroxyvitamin D, creatinine, and 24 - hour urinary calcium levels should be measured in addition to ordering a bone density test. Imaging of the parathyroid glands is not necessary for diagnosis, but is useful if surgical management is indicated. A low PTH level could suggest malignancy and may indicate the need for a CT scan.', options = '["A 24 - hour urinary calcium level","A parathyroid hormone level","A vitamin D level","CT of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '0a9d389d-e4c0-4d00-948b-cbd07f257188';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 35 - year - old female presents to your office with a 3 - day history of right - sided facial weakness. She has flattening of the nasolabial fold and is unable to elevate the right corner of her mouth. She is able to close her right eye and raise her eyebrows. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', explanation = 'This patient presents with a relatively acute onset of facial weakness affecting only the right side of the face, but she is able to close her right eye and raise her eyebrows. Sparing of the forehead muscles is consistent with a supranuclear lesion because the nucleus of cranial nerve VII receives fibers from both sides of the cortex for the upper face, meaning the forehead would be unaffected. Cranial nerve VII includes visceral efferent fibers (facial muscles and stapedius), visceral motor fibers (salivary and lacrimal glands), and special sensory fibers (taste to the anterior two - thirds of the tongue). In Bell palsy, which involves edema of this cranial nerve, the entire side of the face is affected, including the forehead. Therefore, this presentation is not consistent with Bell palsy and warrants further evaluation, including brain MRI, to assess for a central cause. Prednisone and valacyclovir are not appropriate for this patient, as they are treatments used for Bell palsy. Plasmapheresis is not indicated for Bell palsy, stroke, or tumor. Surgical decompression is not indicated.', options = '["Reassurance only","Prednisone plus valacyclovir (Valtrex)","MRI of the brain","Plasmapheresis","Surgical decompression"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'b3c7e175-f0da-4c69-bc56-960dc2f79bde';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A previously healthy 70 - year - old yoga instructor is brought to the emergency department (ED) by her students after falling while practicing yoga. Her students report that she struck her head on the floor and was unresponsive for a few seconds, but recovered quickly. S he was slightly confused after the injury, but was able to stand and describe the incident. On initial assessment in the ED, she is holding her head in obvious discomfort and a hematoma is developing on her forehead. She is alert and oriented, with a Glasg ow Coma Scale score of', explanation = 'In an older adult, head trauma with a loss of consciousness, vomiting, anterograde amnesia, or a previous history of head trauma requires CT of the head. Being older than 65 years is considered an independent risk factor for head trauma. Older adults with a traumatic brain injury experience higher morbidity and mortality due to age - related changes in vasculature that leave vessels more vulnerable to rupture and changes in white matter that render white matter tracts more susceptible to shear injury. As a result of these physiological changes, older patients are more susceptible to injury, and even those with minor mechanisms of injury and no abnormalities on a neurologic examination may still have subdural or epidural bleeding. NSAIDs carry a risk of bleeding and should be avoided following a traumatic brain injury.', options = '[]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'a770d878-28da-4d6c-90e1-7b43fdbf643c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 3 - day - old infant presents to your clinic for a routine check - up. The parents report that the infant has been feeding well but has had fewer wet diapers than expected. On examination, the infant appears slightly lethargic with dry skin. You need to assess the hydration status of the infant. Which one of the following would be the most reliable clinical sign for assessing dehydration in this 3 - day - old infant?', explanation = 'Capillary refill time is the most reliable clinical sign for assessing dehydration in infants. An abnormal capillary refill time (>2 seconds) is a strong indicator of dehydration and has been shown to have a high likelihood ratio for predicting dehydration in children. While decreased urine output is a sensitive indicator of dehydration, it is not specific and can be influenced by other factors such as feeding patterns and ambient temperature. Dry mucous membranes are a useful sign but can be subjective and less reliable compared to capillary refill time. Abnormal skin turgor is more commonly used in older children and is less reliable in neonates due to their higher skin elasticity. A sunken fontanelle can indicate dehydration, but it is less specific and can be influenced by other factors, such as the patient''s position during the examination.', options = '["Capillary refill time","Decreased urine output","Dry mucous membranes","Skin turgor","Sunken fontanelle"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '21946185-fc91-4d48-8aee-9646e758a162';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 16 - year - old female presents with her parents because she has been experiencing a loss of interest in her usual activities, trouble sleeping, difficulty concentrating, and low energy over the last month. After a discussion with the patient and her parents , you refer her for cognitive behavioral therapy and start an antidepressant. Which one of the following medications is approved by the FDA to treat depression in patients such as this?', explanation = 'Two SSRIs, fluoxetine and escitalopram, have been approved by the FDA for the treatment of depression in adolescents. Other SSRIs such as sertraline, NDRIs such as bupropion, and SNRIs such as venlafaxine are often used off - label for this purpose but have not been approved by the FDA for use in adolescents. Esketamine is a ketamine nasal spray used in conjunction with an oral antidepressant for treatment - resistant depression in adults.', options = '["Esketamine nasal spray (Spravato)","Bupropion","Fluoxetine (Prozac)","Venlafaxine"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '5612ae49-aa62-400e-b1d2-095376ad33e4';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 35 - year - old patient presents with a 14 - day history of a productive cough and green sputum. They report they initially had a fever but that it resolved after a few days. The cough is interfering with their sleep and daily activity, and they have tried cough drops without relief. They have a history of hypothyroidism for which they take levothyroxine (Synthroid), and do not have a history of asthma. They do not smoke, and their immunizations are up to date. On examination, the patient is afebrile and has an oxygen saturation of 98≥ on room air, a heart rate of 82 beats/min, and a blood pressure of 120/82 mm Hg. A lung examination reveals mild rhonchi that clear with cough, and you do not note any wheezing or egophony. Which one of the following treatments would be the most effective in reducing this patient''s cough?', explanation = 'Acute bronchitis is a lower respiratory tract infection that is most commonly caused by a virus. Treatment is generally supportive as it is a self - limited illness. Guaifenesin, honey, and dextromethorphan have been shown to decrease the frequency of cough (SOR B). In otherwise healthy patients without evidence of pneumonia, acute bronchitis can last 2 – 3 weeks. Patients may exhibit purulent sputum, rhonchi, and wheezing with acute bronchitis but are typically afebrile with normal oxygen saturation. β - Agonists such as albuterol are not recommended for the treatment of acute bronchitis unless wheezing is present (SOR B). While 90≥ of acute bronchitis cases are caused by viruses, a significant percentage are treated inappropriately with antibiotics. Antibiotics can decrease the duration of cough by 0.46 days, but the overall net benefit of antibiotics is negligible and often outweighed by potential side effects (SOR A). Studies show codeine has no benefit in the treatment of acute bronchitis and has rather significant side effects.', options = '["An albuterol inhaler (Proventil, Ventolin)","Amoxicillin/clavulanate (Augmentin)","Azithromycin (Zithromax)","Codeine/guaifenesin syrup","Dextromethorphan (Delsym)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'f42c5c56-f9ef-4ef6-b1be-f49a1364d48b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 20 - year - old male presents to the urgent care center for left ankle pain and swelling following an ankle inversion injury that occurred a few hours earlier. A physical examination reveals mild swelling of the left ankle joint. Using the Ottawa foot and ankle rules, which one of the following findings, if present, would be an indication for radiography for an acute ankle inversion injury?', explanation = 'When a foot or ankle fracture is suspected, a weight - bearing foot and ankle x - ray should be obtained. The Ottawa foot and ankle rules are a useful tool for determining the need for an x - ray for an acute ankle inversion injury. According to the Ottawa foot and ankle rules, a foot x - ray should be obtained if any of the following requirements are met: bone tenderness at the posterior edge or the tip of the lateral or medial malleolus, bone tenderness at the base of the fifth metatarsal or navicular bone, or inability to bear weight on the affected leg or foot for at least 4 steps after the injury.', options = '["Bone tenderness at the anterior edge of the lateral malleolus","Bone tenderness at the anterior edge of the medial malleolus","Bone tenderness at the base of the fourth metatarsal","Bone tenderness of the navicular bone","Inability to bear weight on the left foot for at least 10 steps after the injury"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'b9d5b51f-8c32-472d-8f02-7ac394f086e1';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A generally healthy 13 - year - old male presents with his parents because they are concerned that he has very large - volume stools that clog the toilet. The patient says that he averages fewer than 2 bowel movements per week and they are sometimes painful. He does not have any abdominal pain and has not seen any blood in his stools. Examination findings are unremarkable. His height, weight, and BMI percentiles have remained steady for years. A CBC, comprehensive metabolic panel, ferritin level, and TSH level ar e all normal. An abdominal x - ray is normal. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'This patient meets 3 of the Rome IV diagnostic criteria for functional constipation (≤2 bowel movements per week, painful hard stools, and stools that clog the toilet). There is good evidence that polyethylene glycol is effective for treating functional constipation in children and adolescents. There is no evidence that probiotics are effective. This patient does not have any red flag symptoms that would prompt a need for either magnetic resonance enterography to evaluate for inflammatory bowel disease or a colonoscopy to evaluate for a structural lesion.', options = '["Polyethylene glycol (MiraLAX) daily","Probiotics daily","Magnetic resonance enterography","Colonoscopy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '9983309b-4360-474a-95ab-87bf89859a1d';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 45 - year - old male sees you for routine follow - up of diabetes mellitus. He smokes 1 pack of cigarettes per day and does not have any other medical conditions. His diabetes is well controlled on liraglutide (Victoza) and metformin. He has an LDL - cholesterol level of 120 mg/dL, an HDL - cholesterol level of 55 mg/dL, and a triglyceride level of 300 mg/dL. His 10 - year atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease risk is 8.2≥. According to 2018 guidelines from the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association, the most appropriate recommendation for this patient would be', explanation = 'Patients 40 – 75 years of age with diabetes mellitus and an LDL - cholesterol level ≥70 mg/dL should be treated with a moderate - intensity statin without calculating a 10 - year risk of atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease. However, high - intensity statin therapy should be considered to lower the LDL - cholesterol level by at least 50≥ for patients such as this one who are at elevated risk, especially those 50 – 75 years of age or with multiple risk factors. Of the options listed, atorvastatin, 40 – 80 mg daily, is the only therapy that is considered high - intensity statin therapy. Pravastatin, 20 mg daily, is low - intensity statin therapy. Simvastatin, 20 – 40 mg daily, is considered moderate - intensity therapy and is not recommended at doses >40 mg daily. Ezetimibe and fenofibrate are not recommended first - line medications for the treatment of hyperlipidemia and the prevention of cardiovascular disease.', options = '["atorvastatin (Lipitor), 40 mg daily","ezetimibe (Zetia), 10 mg daily","fenofibrate, 160 mg daily","pravastatin, 20 mg daily","simvastatin (Zocor), 40 mg daily"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '9a0240b2-34c1-4fb9-ae8e-a1f941c23daa';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 20 - year - old female presents for a routine health maintenance examination and has no medical concerns today. She does not have a history of sexual activity, and screenings for alcohol and substance use, intimate partner violence, anxiety, depression, and suicidality are negative. An examination reveals fair skin, an elevated BMI of 31 kg/m , and normal blood pressure. According to the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force, you should recommend screening for which one of the following?', explanation = 'This patient is a healthy young adult female who presents with an elevated BMI but no other identified risk factors. The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommends HIV screening for all persons 15 – 65 years of age (A recommendation). Cervical cancer screening is not recommended in women before age 21 (D recommendation), thus precluding the patient from screening. Chlamydia screening is recommended for all sexually active females under 25 years of age (B recommendation), but this patient has no history of sexual activity. Diabetes mellitus screening is recommended for persons 35 – 70 years of age with overweight or obesity (B recommendation). While the patient''s age precludes her from this screening, she should be offered intensive multicomponent behavioral intervention for weight loss. Preventive counseling for skin cancer is recommended for persons with fair skin types who are 6 months to 24 years of age (B recommendation), but screening examinations are not recommended (I recommendation). This patient should also be offered screening for hepatitis C.', options = '["Cervical cancer","Chlamydia","Diabetes mellitus","HIV","Skin cancer"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'eb0b4af8-6067-45cc-999a-f8c47fead1b3';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 37 - year - old male comes to the primary care clinic with a several - month history of worsening paresthesia in his right foot. He says that he sometimes has numbness and a hot sensation in his feet and has difficulty using the pedals of his car. Sometimes, h e has pain that wakes him up at night but eases when he walks around the room. He has no significant past medical history but did sustain a severe right ankle sprain about 1 year ago. His vital signs are unremarkable. Examination of the ankle reveals pain along the medial malleolus and a positive Tinel sign at the ankle. An x - ray of the ankle is unremarkable. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', explanation = 'Tarsal tunnel syndrome is an entrapment neuropathy of the foot caused by compression of the tibial nerve or one of its branches in the fibro - osseous tunnel under the flexor retinaculum and within the abductor hallucis muscle of the foot. It may occur following an injury, such as a fracture or sprain of the ankle. Patients can present with paresthesias, local pain behind the medial malleolus, and loss of sensation in the sole. Paresis of the small muscle of the foot can lead to impaired abduction. There is no criterion standard for the diagnosis of tarsal tunnel syndrome. The most helpful clinical diagnostic sign is a positive Tinel sign at the ankle, and electrophysiologic studies can help in making the diagnosis. MRI can be useful in cases of compression due to a mass lesion. Patients can begin a trial of conservative management, but advanced cases are better treated surgically. Achilles tendinopathy causes posterior heel pain that is localized at the site of insertion of the Achilles tendon and worsens with increased activity or pressure on the area. Haglund deformity presents with pain in the upper part of the posterior calcaneus and is more common in middle - aged women who repeatedly wear ill - fitting shoes. X - rays demonstrate the deformity on the superior aspect of the posterior calcaneus. Patients with heel pad syndrome report a deep - seated pain that feels like a bruise in the middle of the heel. The pain can be reproduced by palpating the area. It is typically an inflammatory response to damage of the heel pad secondary to walking barefoot for prolonged periods of time. Plantar fasciitis causes tenderness along the medial calcaneal tuberosity and along the plantar fascia. Patients typically report pain with their first steps after getting out of bed in the morning.', options = '["Achilles tendinopathy","Haglund deformity","Heel pad syndrome","Plantar fasciitis","Tarsal tunnel syndrome"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '58d68b92-c72d-453d-ab5e-2ed1db254c18';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 36 - year - old female comes to your office for a health maintenance examination. She mentions that she engages in amateur rifle target shooting matches. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate advice concerning this patient’s physical safety?', explanation = 'Hearing protection is essential while shooting firearms because noise exposure often exceeds 140 dB. Even a single gunshot can cause permanent hearing loss. Earmuffs and earplugs with a noise reduction rate of 28 – 31 dB are common and inexpensive protective devices. Electronic hearing protection can amplify quiet sounds such as a range safety officer''s instructions, but also safely protect against loud sounds. Many ranges require their use. Noise - canceling headphones do not provide enough noise reduction for gunshots. Wearing loose - fitting clothing can trap the ejected hot brass casings, leading to unsafe gun handling. Safety eyeglasses that meet the necessary certifications can protect against shrapnel from the bullet striking the target or a malfunction. Regular glasses do not provide sufficient eye protection.', options = '["She should wear electronic hearing protection that amplifies quiet sounds","She should wear noise - canceling headphones","She should wear loose - fitting clothing","She should wear her regular glasses so that she has eye protection"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '33c80a74-04ca-47da-b440-85d2ae757b91';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 66 - year - old male presents to your office with a 2 - hour history of discomfort in the midsternal area that began while taking a walk earlier today. He says that he feels 90≥ better. He had a Welcome to Medicare visit 1 year ago, in which an EKG was normal. You order an EKG today. Which one of the following EKG findings, if present in this patient, should prompt urgent transport to the emergency department?', explanation = 'Approximately 1≥ of primary care office visits are for evaluation of chest pain, in which 2≥ – 4≥ of these patients have unstable angina or myocardial infarction. Twelve - lead EKG is recommended to look for ST - segment changes, new - onset left bundle branch block, presence of Q waves, and new T - wave inversions. The presence of new - onset left bundle branch block increases the likelihood of acute coronary syndrome (°CS) and acute myocardial infarction. Patients with suspected °CS or the aforementioned changes on EKG should be transported immediately to the emergency department. The presence of first - degree atrioventricular block, frequent PVCs, sinus tachycardia, or voltage criteria for left ventricular hypertrophy does not increase the likelihood of °CS.', options = '["First - degree atrioventricular block","Frequent PVCs","Left bundle branch block","Sinus tachycardia","Voltage criteria for left ventricular hypertrophy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '18c73fb2-bdb0-4e3d-85ba-ce1b16a6526e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A generally healthy 56 - year - old female sees you for follow - up of pneumonia diagnosed in the emergency department (ED). A chest x - ray performed in the ED showed a left lower lobe infiltrate and several compression fractures involving the thoracic vertebrae. A DXA scan performed 7 months ago showed a T - score of – 1.9. Her daily medications include a multivitamin; calcium, 1000 mg; and vitamin D (cholecalciferol), 800 IU. Today she feels well and has no concerns. This patient would be most likely to benefit from therapy for which one of the following conditions?', explanation = 'Although this patient''s T - score indicates osteopenia, the presence of fragility fractures indicates osteoporosis. The T - score is obtained by measuring bone mineral density using DXA at the spine, total hip, or femoral neck. A T - score between – 1.0 and – 2.49 indicates osteopenia, whereas a T - score of ≤ – 2.5 denotes osteoporosis. However, postmenopausal osteoporosis may be diagnosed by bone mineral density or by the presence of a fragility fracture, which is a fracture that occurs with no associated trauma or after a fall from standing height or lower. Hence, osteoporosis can be diagnosed and the patient further evaluated and treated even though her T - score is > – 2.5. Spondylolisthesis is the acquired anterior displacement of one vertebral body over another and is typically associated with degenerative changes. Spondylolysis is a cause of acute back pain resulting from a stress fracture involving the pars interarticularis of the lumbar vertebral body. It is typically found in young athletes.', options = '["Osteopenia","Osteoporosis","Spondylolisthesis","Spondylolysis"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'de4f1161-d834-4f5d-9d04-008b75321427';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A gravida 2 para 1 at 28 weeks'' gestation presents with an episode of second - trimester bleeding that spontaneously resolved. She has not had any prenatal laboratory studies during either of her pregnancies. Ultrasonography today shows a healthy fetus and a small placental abruption. Which one of the following would be most important to order at this time?', explanation = 'Blood type/Rh factor testing should be ordered when evaluating second - trimester bleeding. This patient would require a dose of Rho(D) immune globulin (RhoGAM) if found to be Rh negative. Therefore, of all the tests listed, an Rh factor test is the most time sensitive and affects the plan of care. Patients may have had unattended home births with prior pregnancies or refused laboratory tests altogether. With the potential exposure to mixing of maternal and fetal blood during the patient''s first delivery, it is crucial during this pregnancy to ensure maternal and fetal blood are compatible because there is a high risk of contact between maternal and fetal blood. An antiphospholipid antibody profile would be appropriate for evaluation of an underlying hypercoagulable disorder, such as in cases of late pregnancy loss (>10 weeks), recurrent early pregnancy loss (<10 weeks), certain preterm deliveries, or thrombosis. Although HIV testing is an important component of prenatal laboratory studies, it would not be the most important test to order at this time. A toxoplasmosis antibody test may be considered if there are signs of infection or exposure to toxoplasmosis. While cocaine use can cause placental abruption, a urine toxicology screen for cocaine is not the most pressing laboratory study to order at this time.', options = '["An antiphospholipid antibody profile","An HIV test","An Rh factor test","A toxoplasmosis antibody test","A urine toxicology screen for cocaine"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '3b609a94-6742-4e93-a2f3-7d0a9dc58e2e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A generally healthy 50 - year - old nurse presents to your clinic 1 day after sustaining an accidental needlestick containing the blood of a person with active hepatitis B virus infection who has not yet begun treatment. Your patient completed the hepatitis B (HepB) vaccine series at age 30 before beginning his first nursing job. Hepatitis serologies drawn yesterday at his place of employment were positive for hepatitis B surface antibody (>10 mIU/mL). Which one of the following would be recommended for this patient?', explanation = 'Postexposure prophylaxis with hepatitis B immune globulin or hepatitis B vaccine is not recommended in those who have completed the hepatitis B vaccine series and have proven immunity to hepatitis B virus. The presence of hepatitis B surface antibody titers of >10 mIU/mL are indicative of immunity either from previous vaccination or from previous infection with hepatitis B (both hepatitis B core and surface antibodies are reactive). Hepatitis B immune globulin would be recommended in a patient with negative hepatitis B serology testing.', options = '["No additional vaccination","Hepatitis B immune globulin (HBIG) only","Recombinant HepB vaccine only","Both HBIG and recombinant HepB vaccine"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '616bc31c-2437-48dd-bad0-c4dd49548670';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 46 - year - old male presents for an acute visit due to a 2 - week history of low back pain. He was moving furniture when the pain started, and he felt a pop in his right lower back area. The pain is severe enough that it keeps him from standing up straight an d is causing him trouble with sleeping. He does not have fever or chills, numbness, paresthesia, or weakness in his lower extremities. He has no radicular pain on a straight leg – raising test. He went to a chiropractor who did x - rays and told him he needed to get an MRI. Which one of the following, if present, would be an indication for advanced imaging?', explanation = 'Early advanced imaging for low back pain increases the probability of surgery and is associated with a higher use of opioids, a higher cost of care, higher pain scores, and more work absenteeism. While there is no consensus on what constitutes red flags for low back pain, new urinary retention is concerning for cauda equina syndrome. Other symptoms associated with cauda equina syndrome are bladder fullness and saddle anesthesia. The severity of pain does not correlate clearly with pathologic back pain. While cigarette use increases the chance of an underlying cancer, without a known history of cancer or other signs, it is not an indication for advanced imaging. While intravenous drug use increases the risk of epidural abscess, with no other signs of infection or history of infection, it is not solitarily an indication for advanced imaging. Nocturnal pain is not uncommon in benign low back pain and may be associated with a more specific underlying cause if the pain occurs in the second part of the night (early morning).', options = '["Current cigarette use","Current intravenous drug use","Disrupted sleep due to nocturnal pain","Restricted posture due to pain","New urinary retention"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'fd3bd734-958c-41be-9e10-4d8970bd658d';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'How long after intranasal administration does naloxone (Narcan) reach peak plasma concentrations?', explanation = 'After intranasal administration of naloxone, peak plasma concentrations are attained within 15 – 30 minutes, although its effect on the patient may be seen sooner. Absorption may be affected by substances or conditions that impact the nasal mucosa function or its blood flow. The half - life of naloxone is 2 hours, which is shorter than many long - acting opioids. Ongoing monitoring is important even after reversal of opioid respiratory depression is achieved.', options = '["Immediately","30 – 60 seconds","3 – 5 minutes","15 – 30 minutes","1 – 2 hours"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'd0c4c40c-8596-46ed-ab9e-0d8d7ac54ae6';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 24 - year - old male presents for evaluation of a bulge in his groin. He reports that it is larger at the end of the day and with straining but says it often goes away when he lies down. He reports a mild dull ache that limits his ability to lift lumber at w ork. On examination there is no obvious bulge in the inguinal area. When the patient bears down, a bulge becomes apparent. Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'This patient presents with an inguinal hernia that is apparent on examination. When the hernia is apparent, no further imaging is needed. Recent studies have found that nearly 50≥ of patients sent for inguinal imaging have been unnecessarily referred. When the hernia is symptomatic or limits function, surgical referral is appropriate. If the hernia is asymptomatic, then watchful waiting would be a viable option. Physical therapy would not be appropriate for this patient with a symptomatic inguinal hernia.', options = '["Inguinal ultrasonography","Scrotal ultrasonography","Abdominal and pelvic CT","Physical therapy","Surgical referral"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '229f2f3f-62bf-42c1-8710-4e4172df56d9';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 72 - year - old male presents to your office with his daughter who is concerned about her father''s recent decline in memory. His history is notable for hypertension, urinary urgency with occasional incontinence, and GERD. On examination, you notice a slow, w ide - based gait. A Mini - Mental State Examination (MMSE) score is 22/30. MRI of the brain is notable for diffuse dilation of the lateral, third, and fourth ventricles, and the diagnosis is confirmed with a high - volume lumbar puncture. Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this condition?', explanation = 'This patient presents with the classic triad symptoms associated with normal - pressure hydrocephalus: gait change, urinary incontinence, and dementia. MRI will show evidence of hydrocephalus, and gait changes will often improve with high - volume removal of cerebrospinal fluid. Treatment involves placing a ventriculoperitoneal shunt to relieve hydrocephalus. Carbidopa/levodopa, donepezil, levothyroxine, and surgery with chemotherapy are all treatments for other causes of dementia including Parkinson disease with Lewy body dementia, Alzheimer dementia, hypothyroidism, and brain tumor or neoplasm, respectively.', options = '["Carbidopa/levodopa (Sinemet), 12.5/50 mg daily","Donepezil (Aricept), 5 mg daily","Levothyroxine (Synthroid), 50 μ g daily","Ventriculoperitoneal shunt","Surgery with postoperative chemotherapy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '0c36e31e-342e-4abb-ad38-ee7906ab9f4a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 65 - year - old male presents to the emergency department with an acute onset of bloody urine confirmed to be hematuria on urinalysis. He does not have any pain, fever, or recent trauma. His medical history is significant for hypertension that is managed wit h lisinopril (Zestril). A physical examination is unremarkable. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in evaluation?', explanation = 'The American College of Physicians recommends that all adults with gross hematuria be referred for further urologic evaluation, including cystoscopy and imaging, due to the high association with malignancy. The sensitivity and specificity of cystoscopy for detecting bladder cancer are high, with a sensitivity ranging from 87≥ to 100≥ and a specificity of 64≥ to 100≥. The positive predictive value of gross hematuria for urologic malignancy in older men is high. Gross hematuria warrants immediate investigation to rule out serious underlying conditions; thus a repeat urinalysis in 1 month would not be appropriate. Initiating empiric antibiotic therapy and re - evaluating in 1 week would not be appropriate without evidence of infection. Urine cytology has limited sensitivity and specificity and should not replace cystoscopy and imaging for the initial evaluation of hematuria.', options = '["Repeating the urinalysis in 1 month","Initiating empiric antibiotic therapy and re - evaluating in 1 week","Ordering urine cytology","Referring the patient for immediate cystoscopy and imaging studies"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '0f5e2823-dcad-4a65-9412-e2886d47e724';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 40 - year - old male presents to establish care. He smokes 1½ packs of cigarettes per day and is uncertain about cutting back or quitting. While planning to enact a patient - centered strategy to help him overcome his reluctance, you recall that evidence suppo rts the application of a counseling technique that uses open - ended questions, affirmations, reflective listening, and summary statements to help foster a sense of patient autonomy and effect positive behavioral change. Which one of the following counseling strategies best fits this description?', explanation = 'Motivational interviewing (MI) is the counseling strategy that best fits the described approach. MI is an evidence - proven strategy that is particularly helpful in situations of ambivalence toward change. In primary care settings, MI has been shown to help people achieve weight loss, improve blood pressure, and reduce alcohol use (SOR A). The key elements of MI include establishing rapport, eliciting the patient''s values, asking open - ended questions, offering affirmations, practicing reflective listening, and recapping discussions with summarizing statements. The acronym OARS (open - ended questions, affirmations, reflective listening, summaries) serves as a reminder of these 4 MI components. The BATHE (background, affect, troubles, handling, empathy) model provides a structure for addressing various psychosocial problems. BATHE uses more targeted lines of questioning, in contrast to the MI approach of asking open - ended questions that give way to affirming, reflective, and summarizing statements. The five A ''s (ask, advise, assess, assist, arrange) approach provides a stepwise guide for assessing and counseling on health - related behaviors. In this strategy, the lines of questioning are targeted, rather than open - ended, leading to more directive recommendations and focused follow - up questions. The transtheoretical (stages of change) model can be helpful when patients are ambivalent, but this approach focuses more on identifying the patient''s current level of readiness to modify a particular health behavior. The stages are precontemplation, contemplation, preparation, action, and maintenance. Identifying a patient''s current stage can facilitate movement to the next stage of change and can provide a helpful framework to select another counseling strategy, such as MI.', options = '["BATHE (background, affect, troubles, handling, empathy)","The five A ’s (ask, advise, assess, assist, arrange)","Motivational interviewing","Transtheoretical (stages of change) model"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'cadd413c-8bf2-49ed-a900-253569369858';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following antibiotics would be recommended for the treatment of syphilis in a pregnant patient who has a history of penicillin allergy?', explanation = 'Parenteral penicillin G benzathine is the only therapy with documented effectiveness for treating syphilis in a pregnant person. In pregnant patients with any stage of syphilis and a reported penicillin allergy, the CDC recommends desensitization followed by treatment with penicillin G benzathine. Azithromycin and erythromycin are insufficient to cure maternal infection or treat fetal infection. There is insufficient data to recommend cephalosporins such as ceftriaxone for the treatment of maternal infections and the prevention of congenital infections. Doxycycline and tetracycline are not recommended for use in the second and third trimesters.', options = '["Azithromycin (Zithromax)","Ceftriaxone","Doxycycline","Penicillin G benzathine (Bicillin L - A) after desensitization"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '737d7fe4-eab0-48bd-a9da-0eb44f84955b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 35 - year - old female with type 1 diabetes presents with a skin lesion on her leg. The lesion began as a small, dusky red, elevated nodule with a sharply circumscribed border, and slowly enlarged to become the lesion shown below. The most likely diagnosis is', explanation = 'This patient''s most likely diagnosis is necrobiosis lipoidica diabeticorum. Its pathophysiology is poorly understood, but lesions are commonly found on the anterior and lateral surfaces of the lower legs. Lesions may begin as a small, dusky red, elevated nodule with a sharply circumscribed border. The nodule slowly enlarges, develops an irregular outline, and flattens, and has a brownish - yellow center. A reddened border may be present. Diabetic dermopathy characteristically occurs as crops of brownish atrophic lesions. In diabetic lipoatrophy the skin is depressed but otherwise normal. Diabetic rubeosis is described as reddening of the face and extremities in patients with long - standing diabetes mellitus. Eruptive xanthomas from diabetes are typically small, reddish - yellow nodules up to 0.5 cm in diameter that appear in clusters on the extensor surfaces and buttocks.', options = '["diabetic dermopathy","diabetic lipoatrophy","diabetic rubeosis","eruptive xanthoma","necrobiosis lipoidica diabeticorum"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'd143b7d1-5b49-4b86-8e5d-42bb8504b8a9';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Metformin can cause which one of the following?', explanation = 'Asymptomatic vitamin B deficiency has been reported in a significant proportion of patients taking metformin (SOR A). A randomized, placebo - controlled trial showed that patients taking metformin had a 19≥ decrease in vitamin B levels and a 7≥ increase in 12 absolute risk of vitamin B deficiency compared to the placebo group. 12 Chromatopsia, which is a visual disturbance of color perception, is associated with use of phosphodiesterase - 5 inhibitors, such as sildenafil. Metformin use is not associated with ileus. Although metformin use is contraindicated in patients with impaired renal function, metformin itself does not cause renal failure. Because diarrhea occurs relatively frequently with metformin therapy, metformin use is not commonly associated with weight gain.', options = '["Chromatopsia","Ileus","Renal failure","Vitamin B deficiency","Weight gain"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'cf8a4538-ac92-410c-9b7a-246e6177f324';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 3 - year - old female is brought to your office by her parents with fever, cough, and decreased appetite. On examination you hear crackles in the left upper lobe and a chest x - ray confirms a left upper lobe consolidation. She appears well hydrated and her vi tal signs are normal. On examination she is drinking water and interacting normally. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate antibiotic for this patient''s condition?', explanation = 'The majority of cases of community - acquired pneumonia (CAP) in children are caused by viruses. If bacterial pneumonia were suspected, then antibiotics would be warranted. Given this patient''s focal lung examination and x - ray findings, the most likely causative bacteria would be a typical pathogen such as Streptococcus pneumoniae or Haemophilus influenzae . The first - line choice of antibiotics would be amoxicillin for 7 days. Azithromycin is appropriate for treatment of atypical pneumonia. While cefdinir does treat the typical pathogens seen in CAP, it would not be recommended for first - line treatment due to its broader spectrum. Doxycycline is used to treat CAP but should not be used in a 3 - year - old. Sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim is not indicated for CAP treatment.', options = '["Amoxicillin","Azithromycin (Zithromax)","Cefdinir","Doxycycline","Sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'e5e2f56e-a6a9-487b-8102-95bdb10a7205';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 35 - year - old male presents to the urgent care clinic with pain in his right index finger after jamming it during basketball practice. An examination demonstrates a gross deformity of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint of the affected finger. There i s dorsal angulation of the proximal phalanx. Capillary refill, sensation, and pulses are all intact. Because the patient has pain with attempted movement of the finger, a digital block using 1≥ lidocaine without epinephrine is used to complete the examinat ion. Complete x - rays, including true lateral films, reveal a very small fracture of the middle phalanx involving a minimal (<20≥) area of the articular surface. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in the treatment of this patient''s finger dislocation?', explanation = 'This patient has a dorsal dislocation of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint of the finger, which is the most commonly dislocated joint in the body. Examination of the patient''s finger reveals intact neurovascular findings. Conservative management is indicated given the limited articular surface involvement. A simple, stable dorsal PIP dislocation can be managed with in - office reduction, followed by splinting in approximately 30° of flexion for 2 – 4 weeks. Buddy taping is also recommended to prevent hyperextension deformities. X - rays should be repeated directly after reduction, and again in 1 week. Neither MRI nor physical therapy are indicated. Immediate surgical referral is necessary for finger fracture - dislocations that are irreducible, unstable after reduction, or involve significant soft tissue, tendon, or neurovascular injury. Additional indications include fractures involving a large portion of the articular surface (typically >30≥), significant displacement or angulation (>15°), malrotation, comminution, and persistent subluxation or dislocation on imaging. Open fractures (exposed bone or joint) and injuries with vascular compromise or loss of function also require urgent surgical evaluation.', options = '["Discharging home, and repeating x - rays in 1 week","Reduction, followed by splinting in a flexed position and buddy taping","MRI of the finger","Referral for physical therapy with instructions to start early range - of - motion exercises","Urgent referral to an orthopedist for hand surgery"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '25b6cfe9-3286-4e5c-b833-038dc133a343';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 27 - year - old female comes to your office because she is having moderately severe, diffuse abdominal pain with nausea and approximately 5 loose, greasy stools daily. She recently returned from a 2 - week backpacking trip in Nicaragua. Stool studies are posit ive for Giardia . Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?', explanation = 'Giardia is a parasite that causes diarrheal illness. While found globally, it is especially common in areas where sanitary conditions are poor and water treatment facilities are limited. Transmission may be waterborne, foodborne, or fecal - oral. The incubation period is usually 1 – 2 weeks, and symptoms include greasy diarrhea, abdominal pain, and nausea. Fever and vomiting are uncommon. While some infections are self - limited, treatment is recommended for symptomatic individuals to improve their symptoms and prevent transmission to others. Metronidazole, nitazoxanide, or tinidazole are recommended for treatment of Giardia infection. Azithromycin, ciprofloxacin, and ivermectin are antimicrobials that are commonly used to treat other causes of traveler''s diarrhea.', options = '["Supportive care only","Azithromycin (Zithromax)","Ciprofloxacin (Cipro)","Ivermectin (Stromectol)","Metronidazole (Flagyl)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'c1127ac3-b383-46ff-a9a3-f4361be7e5a7';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 49 - year - old female with a past medical history of epilepsy presents to your office because of sadness, sleep disruption, generalized anhedonia, and a recent increase in appetite. Her Patient Health Questionnaire – 9 (PHQ - 9) score is elevated at 14. Which one of the following medications should be AVOIDED in this patient?', explanation = 'Antidepressants including bupropion, trazodone, and tricyclic antidepressants are associated with an increased risk of seizure and should be avoided in patients with epilepsy. In general, SSRIs or SNRIs are safer choices. Mirtazapine and vortioxetine would also be preferred choices.', options = '["Bupropion","Duloxetine (Cymbalta)","Fluoxetine (Prozac)","Mirtazapine (Remeron)","Sertraline (Zoloft)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '9b34a4e5-3742-4c60-875f-7adcb9ed2df7';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 20 - year - old female presents for a health maintenance examination. She has no significant past medical history and no concerns. Based on U.S. Preventive Services Task Force guidelines, screening for which one of the following would be most appropriate at this time?', explanation = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force gives a B recommendation for screening for hepatitis C in individuals 18 – 79 years of age. Cervical cancer screening is not recommended until at least age 21 (A recommendation). Evidence for screening for hyperlipidemia and skin cancer is uncertain. Current evidence is insufficient to assess the balance of the benefits and harms of visual skin examination to screen for skin cancer (I recommendation), but counseling for ultraviolet exposure is recommended for persons 6 months to 24 years of age with fair skin types (B recommendation).', options = '["Hepatitis C","Hyperlipidemia","Cervical cancer","Skin cancer"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '04dc58d0-f7dd-412d-9c81-634f560dde33';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 75 - year - old male with acute confusion presents to the emergency department and is found to have a blood pressure of 280/140 mm Hg. Which one of the following potential etiologies would provide the strongest indication for lowering his systolic blood pres sure to a target of 120 mm Hg within 20 minutes?', explanation = 'Treatment of acute aortic dissection includes aggressive lowering of the systolic blood pressure to 100 – 120 mm Hg within 20 minutes and concomitant lowering of the pulse rate to <60 beats/min to reduce shear stress on the aortic wall, minimize the risk of propagating the dissection, and reduce the risk of other complications, including rupture and aneurysmal degeneration. The optimal treatment of acute ischemic stroke, acute renal failure, hypertensive encephalopathy, and intracerebral hemorrhage requires blood pressure to be lowered more cautiously to avoid the risk of complications that may be seen with overly rapid and aggressive blood pressure – lowering.', options = '["Acute aortic dissection","Acute ischemic stroke","Acute renal failure","Hypertensive encephalopathy","Intracerebral hemorrhage"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '8b7a3354-6555-48f0-ba3d-6f99a0e7f997';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 56 - year - old male sees you because he has been falling asleep at work in the afternoon. Upon questioning he notes that he is very tired all the time. Although he is in bed 8 hours per night and wakes with an alarm, he gets up 3 times nightly to urinate. H e says that he has been told he snores. He does not have any constipation, dry skin, mood changes, stomach pain, changes in urine stream, shortness of breath, or chest pain. The patient is 173 cm (68 in) tall and weighs 95 kg (209 lb). His vital signs include a blood pressure of 140/88 mm Hg, a pulse rate of 79 beats/min, and a respiratory rate of 16/min. Which one of the following is most likely to yield the correct diagnosis?', explanation = 'The combination of obesity, loud snoring, and fatigue is suspicious for obstructive sleep apnea, and polysomnography is the definitive diagnostic study. A TSH level would be useful if hypothyroidism were suspected as the cause of this patient''s fatigue, but it is less likely because he does not have any mood changes, dry skin, or constipation. Low vitamin B , folate, and iron levels are also less likely based on this patient''s presentation. A comprehensive metabolic panel would be useful if kidney or liver function were suspected as the cause of the patient''s fatigue, but these are less likely because he does not have shortness of breath, stomach pain, or chest pain.', options = '["A serum TSH level","Vitamin B and folate levels","Iron studies","A comprehensive metabolic panel","Polysomnography"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '3d16df44-ccdf-4326-8d60-c91dbabae2c1';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 16 - year - old female presents for a routine well child examination. She has never been sexually active and does not use illicit substances. Based on guidelines from the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force, screening patients such as this for which one of the following has the strongest evidence of benefit?', explanation = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) recommends screening for anxiety in children and adolescents 8 – 18 years of age (B recommendation). The USPSTF does recommend screening for chlamydia and gonorrhea for sexually active females in this patient''s age group (B recommendation); however, this patient is not sexually active. Screening adolescents for eating disorders, elevated blood pressure, and scoliosis all have insufficient evidence to assess the benefits and harms (I recommendation).', options = '["Anxiety","Chlamydia and gonorrhea","Eating disorders","Elevated blood pressure","Scoliosis"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'b0956af5-6a98-4783-beff-14334a3734b1';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 50 - year - old female presents for evaluation of unilateral shoulder pain without a history of acute injury. She has tried ibuprofen with minimal symptomatic relief. Plain radiographs of the affected shoulder taken at an urgent care clinic last week demonst rated no abnormal findings. Which one of the following physical examination findings would best support a diagnosis of adhesive capsulitis as the primary etiology of this patient''s shoulder pain?', explanation = 'The hallmark finding of adhesive capsulitis, also known as frozen shoulder, is pain associated with restricted passive range of motion, particularly in external rotation, flexion, and abduction. Osteoarthritis of the glenohumeral joint also commonly causes pain and stiffness with limited passive range of motion; however, radiographs would show evidence of osteoarthritis, with joint space narrowing, sclerosis, osteophyte formation, and subchondral cystic change. With adhesive capsulitis, radiographs are typically normal, although characteristic findings are seen on MRI. Limited passive range of motion occurs with adhesive capsulitis and osteoarthritis because both conditions involve structural changes within the intra - articular space of the glenohumeral joint, thus resulting in mechanical restriction of the range of motion. Apprehension in a position of abduction and external rotation would suggest a diagnosis of shoulder instability. Crepitus on passive range of motion would suggest a mechanical abnormality within the shoulder girdle (either intra - or extra - articular) and is nonspecific to any one condition. Limited active range of motion in abduction with preserved passive range of motion is common to extra - articular sources of shoulder pain, such as rotator cuff tendinitis and impingement, subacromial bursitis, biceps tendinitis, and partial or complete rotator cuff tears. Weakness on manual muscle testing in abduction and external rotation would raise concern for a high - grade or full - thickness rotator cuff tear.', options = '["Apprehension in a 90° position with abduction and external rotation","Crepitus on passive abduction with preserved passive range of abduction","Restricted active range of abduction with preserved passive range of abduction","Restricted passive range of abduction and external rotation","Weakness on resisted abduction and external rotation"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '6a0f58b0-f695-49df-9d08-376894dce8c1';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 60 - year - old male with a history of type 2 diabetes presents to your office because he is concerned about an ulcer on the bottom of his right foot. He is uncertain how long the ulcer has been present. He is afebrile and otherwise asymptomatic. His most re cent hemoglobin A is 9.7≥ and was obtained 9 months ago. His medications include metformin, 2000 mg daily, and insulin glargine (Lantus), 34 units nightly. He does not regularly check his blood glucose levels. On examination, the patient has an ulcer on the plantar surface of the right foot overlying the head of the fifth metatarsal, measuring 1.0 cm in diameter. The ulcer appears deep with erythema that extends approximately 2.5 cm from the margin of the ulcer. A probe - to - bone test is positive. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next test to evaluate for osteomyelitis?', explanation = 'In a patient with diabetes mellitus and suspected osteomyelitis of the foot, initial evaluation should include a probe - to - bone test, a serum inflammatory marker such as an erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), and plain radiography. Plain radiography is the recommended initial imaging modality in the diagnosis of osteomyelitis due to its low cost, safety, and availability. If a plain radiograph suggests osteomyelitis, advanced imaging may not be necessary. While an elevated WBC count can be used to grade the severity of a diabetes - related foot infection, it can be normal in about half of patients with a severe diabetes - related foot infection and is not helpful in the diagnosis of osteomyelitis. A highly elevated ESR, however, is suggestive of an osteomyelitis infection. Superficial wound cultures are poorly sensitive and specific for identifying diabetes - related wound organisms compared to deep tissue cultures and are not used in the assessment of diabetes - related foot infections or osteomyelitis. While evaluation of peripheral vasculature and oxygenation may be warranted in the management of diabetes - related foot infections and osteomyelitis, it does not contribute to the diagnosis of osteomyelitis.', options = '["A WBC count","A culture swab","Transcutaneous oximetry","Plain radiography"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '2b062a6e-5d90-42f7-9434-d78a517d1e6a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 63 - year - old female with hypertension sees you for routine follow - up. She has been bothered by swelling in her legs for the last several months. Her blood pressure is well controlled and she does not have any shortness of breath, cough, difficulty breathi ng while lying down, or pain in her legs when walking. She thinks the swelling is better earlier in the day. Her current medications include hydrochlorothiazide, lisinopril (Zestril), estrogen, levothyroxine (Synthroid), and as - needed acetaminophen. A phys ical examination demonstrates mild pitting edema of both legs from the ankle to the distal third of each calf. There are 2+ pedal pulses and no skin changes. Examinations of the heart and lungs are normal. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'Adverse medication effects should always be considered when evaluating new symptoms, such as the association between estrogen use and peripheral edema. This patient''s age suggests that she is likely remote from menopause, which provides a reason to consider discontinuing estrogen therapy. Peripheral edema is not associated with °CE inhibitor use. In fact, combining an °CE inhibitor with a calcium channel blocker (CCB) may decrease the edema attributable to CCB use. Ankle - brachial indices are indicated for the evaluation of suspected arterial disease. Arterial disease typically presents as lower extremity pain during activity that improves with rest. Arterial disease may lead to decreased arterial pulses. Arterial disease should be ruled out in those at risk before starting compression therapy for venous disease. Venous compression ultrasonography is indicated when deep vein thrombosis (DVT) is suspected. DVT is unlikely in the presentation of chronic bilateral lower extremity edema. DVT should be considered in acute unilateral edema, and the Wells score should be used to determine if there is an intermediate or high risk. The combination of a low - risk Wells score and a negative D - dimer level safely rules out DVT. Venous duplex ultrasonography with reflux is helpful in evaluating for chronic venous insufficiency. While this patient may have chronic venous insufficiency, her current medication use could be causing her edema. This should be evaluated before pursuing additional diagnostic testing given her lack of alarm symptoms, such as signs of heart failure or lower extremity ulcerations.', options = '["Holding estrogen, and monitoring for improvement in peripheral edema","Holding lisinopril, and monitoring for improvement in peripheral edema","Bilateral ankle - brachial indices","Bilateral venous compression ultrasonography","Bilateral venous duplex ultrasonography with reflux"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '53e3652e-c30b-4442-8384-615c5c18a87c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 7 - year - old male with no significant past medical history presents with his parents for a well child visit. His BMI has consistently been above the 80th percentile. His parents have both struggled with maintaining healthy weights. To help them promote a healthy lifestyle for their child, you should tell the parents which one of the following?', explanation = 'Anticipatory guidance for lifestyle management in children should incorporate multiple approaches that address nutrition, physical activity, and behaviors that contribute to possible energy imbalance. These recommendations include 60 minutes per day of moderate to vigorous physical activity for children 6 – 17 years of age. Calorie restriction is beneficial in reducing weight in adolescents when combined with additional strategies, such as physical activity and behavioral changes. While excessive video screen time has been associated with increased pediatric obesity, screen - based physical activity (eg, video games that require whole - body movement) can help reduce weight in children with overweight and obesity. Children should consume 5 servings of fruits and vegetables per day. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends against the use of fruit juices as a substitute for whole fruit due to its high calorie content.', options = '["An hour per day of moderate or vigorous physical activity is recommended starting at age","Calorie restriction alone is sufficient in maintaining a healthy weight","Children should avoid video screen – based physical activity","Organic fruit juices can be provided to achieve the recommended daily servings of fruits and vegetables"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'df226958-7201-4807-8fd7-fcae2a07ff38';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 56 - year - old female presents with numbness of her bilateral feet. She first became aware of this during a recent pedicure when she had difficulty feeling the nail technician work on her toes and the plantar surface of her feet. Since that time, she has no ted a feeling of "walking on cotton gauze" and has started wearing slippers around her home. She had intense pruritus of her feet approximately 6 months ago that persisted for several weeks, but it was not accompanied by paresthesia. She is otherwise in go od health and participates in an aerobics class 3 days per week. She takes lisinopril (Zestril), 10 mg daily, for essential hypertension. She does not have any other symptoms. On examination, her cranial nerves, muscle strength, and reflexes are normal. Sensation is diminished over the plantar surface and toes of both feet. She has 2+ dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial pulses bilaterally. Routine laboratory studies, including a CBC, comprehensive metabolic panel, hemoglobin A , serum protein electrophoresis, and TSH, vitamin B , and folate levels, are all in normal range. She is concerned that she may be 12 developing multiple sclerosis. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'This patient demonstrates a symmetric pattern of paresthesia without red flag symptoms such as ataxia, double vision, or speech issues, which makes a lesion of the central nervous system or a nerve root less likely. Because the results of her routine laboratory studies are normal, electrodiagnostic testing would be the recommended next step. While gabapentin can be helpful in treating painful peripheral neuropathy, further workup is needed to determine the cause of this patient''s symptoms. Lyme antibody testing and vitamin level testing plus supplementation may be helpful if electrodiagnostic testing exhibits an axonal pattern. Imaging of the brain or spine, such as with MRI, is not recommended in patients without central neurologic signs or asymmetry.', options = '["Gabapentin (Neurontin), 100 mg 3 times daily","Vitamin B (pyridoxine), 50 mg daily","Lyme antibody testing","Nerve conduction testing and electromyography (EMG)","Brain MRI"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'a574b9fa-8749-4d35-bcaf-4050611e668b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 56 - year - old female presents for evaluation of right heel pain. She recently returned from a hiking trip during which she developed progressive heel discomfort. The patient''s only medication is losartan (Cozaar), which she takes for hypertension. After a thorough examination, you diagnose Achilles tendinopathy. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in diagnosis and management?', explanation = 'Achilles tendinopathy is a common injury in active individuals. The diagnosis is made clinically; therefore, additional imaging is not indicated unless there is concern for an alternate diagnosis. Current recommendations for management include physical therapy for activity modification and targeted exercises. Neither complete rest nor corticosteroid injection are currently recommended for management of Achilles tendinopathy. While platelet - rich plasma injection continues to be studied in tendon injuries, it is not currently recommended as first - line management. Furthermore, studies remain mixed as to whether platelet - rich plasma injections are superior to placebo for pain control and return to normal activity.', options = '["MRI for confirmation of diagnosis","Non – weight - bearing until pain is improved","Corticosteroid injection of the Achilles tendon","Platelet - rich plasma injection","Referral for physical therapy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'bfd0773e-c55e-43f8-b794-7ff51079b4fa';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 45 - year - old male with a new diagnosis of type 2 diabetes is anxious about managing his condition and uncertain about his ability to meet the demands of treatment and self - care. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate strategy to help him understand his diagnosis and follow through on lifestyle and/or medication changes?', explanation = 'Motivational interviewing is the communication strategy with the best evidence of leading to a change in behavior. Scare tactics have not been shown to be effective. Physicians should speak in language that the patient can understand rather than use jargon. Supplying too much detail may overwhelm the patient, especially if it is not tailored to the individual''s goals.', options = '["Emphasizing the seriousness of the condition by showing pictures of patients with complications","Explaining the diagnosis and treatment plan with medical language to ensure professional communication","Supplying only detailed written instructions about his condition immediately after the appointment","Using motivational interviewing to identify what is most important to the patient and create impetus for change"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '651a3977-075b-4f18-85f8-6c8b5ac38502';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A generally healthy 15 - year - old female presents to your office with a history of frequent, generalized abdominal pain and loose stools daily for the last few months. She has not noted any relationship to food or a specific frequency. She has not had any pr evious surgeries and is up to date on routine vaccinations. At her 14 - year - old well child visit, her height was at the 50th percentile and her weight was at the 60th percentile. Today, her height is at the 35th percentile and her weight at the 20th percent ile. She has had a weight loss of 1 kg (2 lb). Her vital signs are normal. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'Patients with classic symptoms of diarrhea, abdominal pain, weight loss, bloating, malabsorption, and failure to thrive should undergo evaluation for celiac disease. Serologic testing for IgA tissue transglutaminase (tTG) is the preferred initial screening in all age groups due to its high sensitivity (95≥) and specificity (95≥). When celiac disease is strongly suspected, total IgA levels should also be obtained because 2≥ – 3≥ of these patients will have IgA deficiency. If IgA tTG serology is positive, most patients will require esophagogastroduodenoscopy with small - bowel biopsy for confirmation, but it is not used as an initial test and some organizations state that a no - biopsy technique is safe for children with very high IgA tTG levels. This patient has classic signs of malabsorption and unexplained weight loss, indicating need for further evaluation. Reassurance would be inappropriate at this time. Fecal fat testing may be useful in the workup of suspected malabsorption symptoms, but the initial test is usually a qualitative assessment of fat in a single specimen because it is less expensive and easier to perform than 72 - hour testing. If high suspicion remains after negative initial testing, a 72 - hour fecal fat test should be performed. Carbohydrate breath testing can be used to evaluate for suspected small intestinal bacterial overgrowth (SIBO). SIBO generally occurs in individuals with abnormal anatomy or other risk factors for abnormal intestinal mobility, including diabetes mellitus or scleroderma. The majority of patients with SIBO present with bloating and flatulence.', options = '["Reassurance and dietary monitoring to evaluate for a relationship to symptoms","Fecal fat testing","An IgA tissue transglutaminase level","Carbohydrate breath testing","A referral for esophagogastroduodenoscopy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'f77d0bf3-b696-4ba9-88bc-7c83b86cfda8';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 60 - year - old male asks you about testosterone supplementation during a routine office visit. He reports that he has had decreased energy, decreased libido, and loss of upper and lower body strength over the last year. He would like to have his testosteron e level checked today. Which one of the following symptoms, if present in this patient, would be most concerning for testosterone deficiency?', explanation = 'Loss of axillary and pubic hair is one of the more specific symptoms of male hypogonadism. Memory issues have myriad etiologies; they may be secondary to attention disorders, mood disorders, sleep apnea, or other neurologic disorders. Fatigue or diminished stamina may be a symptom of male hypogonadism but also can be indicative of other endocrine, musculoskeletal, or rheumatologic disorders. Thinning hair at the temples may occur with aging and with androgenic alopecia. Thinning of the eyebrows may be related to thyroid disorders.', options = '["Difficulties with memory","Fatigue or diminished physical stamina","Loss of axillary and pubic hair","Thinning of hair at the temples","Thinning or loss of eyebrows"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '527fc5b2-a43f-4f05-9d82-c8996d9ef93a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 3 - year - old female is brought to your office by her parents for a preschool examination. She had a normal birth and is up to date on her vaccinations. On examination she appears to be healthy, and her development is appropriate for her age. She is in the 50th percentile for height and weight. You note a grade 1 – 2/6 continuous murmur best heard in the infraclavicular region when she is upright. The murmur changes slightly in intensity with head movement and is absent when she is supine. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'A venous hum is an innocent heart murmur that is caused by vein vibration. It is commonly heard in children and may appear between 3 and 6 years of age. It is typically audible only when the child is upright, and changes with head movement. In a child with a venous hum, reassurance of the parents is appropriate, and no follow - up is necessary.', options = '["Reassuring the parents that this is a benign venous hum that needs no follow - up","Scheduling a follow - up appointment in 1 month to recheck the murmur","Recommending that the patient undergo echocardiography when she reaches adulthood","Sending the patient for evaluation for repair of a patent ductus arteriosus","Referral to a pediatric cardiologist"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '208ed983-b7e8-4d5a-b5af-78147372e06e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 40 - year - old female presents to your office after an episode of anaphylaxis. She has a known tree nut allergy and developed oral swelling, dyspnea, and chest pain after eating a muffin from a coffee shop. Her symptoms initially improved after she used her epinephrine auto - injector but began to worsen 10 minutes later. She used a second dose of her auto - injector 10 minutes prior to presentation and is feeling much better. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'This patient experienced anaphylaxis due to her tree nut allergy. Her anaphylaxis was refractory and required 2 doses of epinephrine for treatment. Although she is feeling better, patients with refractory anaphylaxis should be transferred to a higher level of care, such as an emergency department, for further evaluation and management. Patients who have had severe or refractory anaphylaxis are at risk for a biphasic reaction and should be observed for 6 – 12 hours before discharge. Although medications such as H - and H - blockers and corticosteroids can be helpful in 1 2 the postanaphylaxis care of patients, they are not the mainstay of therapy for patients who have had severe anaphylaxis.', options = '["Starting famotidine (Pepcid), 20 mg daily, and follow - up in 1 week","Starting prednisone, 40 mg for 5 days, and follow - up in 5 days","Starting fexofenadine (Allegra), 180 mg daily, and immediate follow - up with an allergist","Transfer to the emergency department (ED) with observation for 1 – 2 hours prior to discharge","Transfer to the ED with observation for 6 – 12 hours prior to discharge"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '7e1db207-fde4-4c34-b84c-74bfed380114';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 42 - year - old male has been admitted to the hospital for hypotension and electrolyte disturbances due to chronic diarrhea. He was stabilized in the ICU and transferred to the inpatient floor. His gastroenterologist is asking for a colonoscopy with biopsies . His medical history is significant for congenital heart disease with a mechanical aortic valve replacement, an embolic stroke resulting in right hemiparesis, a deep vein thrombosis, and a solitary kidney. He is currently anticoagulated with warfarin and has an INR of 2.6. He has a creatinine level of 2.8 mg/dL (N 0.7 – 1.3) and a glomerular filtration rate of 28 mL/min/1.73 m . In addition to holding warfarin for the planned colonoscopy, how should you manage this patient’s anticoagulation while he is hospitalized?', explanation = 'This patient requires a procedure with a high likelihood of bleeding and should not be anticoagulated at the time of the procedure. He also has a high likelihood of thromboembolic disease and should receive bridging with a heparin drip until his INR has normalized for the planned procedure. With his mechanical heart valve, the correct INR goal is 2.5 – 3.5. Reversal with vitamin K is not necessary because he is stable and not actively bleeding. He is not a candidate for enoxaparin due to his glomerular filtration rate. Heparin, 5000 units subcutaneously, is a prophylactic dose, not a treatment dose.', options = '["Resuming warfarin post procedure with a goal INR of 2.0 – 3.0","Vitamin K for reversal, and resuming warfarin post procedure with a goal INR of 2.5 – 3.5","Enoxaparin (Lovenox), 1.5 mg/kg daily","Heparin, 5000 units subcutaneously 3 times daily","A heparin drip titrated to achieve therapeutic aPTT or anti - factor Xa levels"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'e28175ae-311a-4040-87c7-a3ab65d76029';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 4 - year - old male is brought to the emergency department by his parents after tripping and falling on his hand in an outstretched position. An x - ray reveals a buckle (torus) fracture of the distal radial metaphysis. Which one of the following management strategies would be most appropriate?', explanation = 'Buckle (torus) fractures are incomplete compression fractures that cause cortical bulging of the bone without cortical disruption. They are common in children because of the elasticity of their bones. Distal radius buckle fractures should be treated with short arm immobilization using a short arm splint, soft cast, or wrap for 3 weeks. Complete immobilization with a cast is unnecessary. According to the Choosing Wisely campaign, follow - up radiography is unnecessary unless the patient continues to experience pain or tenderness.', options = '["A short arm splint for 3 weeks with follow - up radiography","A short arm splint for 3 weeks with follow - up radiography only if pain or tenderness persists","A short arm cast for 6 weeks with follow - up radiography","A short arm cast for 6 weeks with follow - up radiography only if pain or tenderness persists"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '07a7ab1e-4ca0-49bd-8d69-c793f55cbd33';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 19 - year - old female presents for a wellness visit while home on college break. According to the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force, which one of the following screenings is indicated?', explanation = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) recommends screening for unhealthy drug use in adults ≥18 years of age (B recommendation). Unhealthy drug use is defined as using psychoactive medications for purposes other than as prescribed or illegally obtaining drugs for personal use. For this patient''s age group, the USPSTF has determined the evidence to be insufficient to recommend for or against screening for cavities or periodontal disease, dyslipidemia, skin cancer, or suicide risk (I recommendation).', options = '["Cavities or periodontal disease","Dyslipidemia","Skin cancer","Suicide risk","Unhealthy drug use"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '6a2c1829-06e2-4ee9-aa97-b7d88a0c148b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 33 - year - old oyster fisherman presents because of a 3 - day history of diarrhea. He describes frequent, large - volume, watery stool that is milky white. His vital signs are normal and he appears nontoxic. Infection with which one of the following pathogens is most likely?', explanation = 'In patients presenting with large - volume rice - water or milky - white stools, the most likely pathogen is Vibrio species. Patients with this presentation should be tested for infection regardless of exposure to undercooked shellfish or brackish waters. Guidelines from the Infectious Diseases Society of America recommend testing for infection with Clostridioides difficile , enteropathogenic Escherichia coli , enterotoxigenic E coli , and Yersinia enterocolitica in patients with diarrhea and fever, bloody or mucoid stools, signs of sepsis, or severe abdominal cramping or tenderness.', options = '["Clostridioides difficile","Enteropathogenic Escherichia coli","Enterotoxigenic E coli","Vibrio species","Yersinia enterocolitica"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'bfe2d8a2-ed4e-41f7-91fd-28f1b6cde800';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 35 - year - old female with Down syndrome presents for a health maintenance examination. She does not have any new symptoms or concerns today. Her only medication is an etonogestrel implant (Nexplanon) that was placed 2 years ago. She is monogamous with a ma le sex partner. On examination you note normal vital signs with a BMI of 28 kg/m . At her most recent laboratory evaluation 2 years ago, she had an LDL - cholesterol level of 104 mg/dL, a fasting glucose level of 89 mg/dL, and a TSH level of 2.67 μ U/mL (N 0. 4 – 4.2). Which one of the following screening evaluations should you order today?', explanation = 'In 2017, the U.S. nonprofit group Global Down Syndrome Foundation convened a workgroup to create an evidence - based guideline for clinicians and adults with Down syndrome and their supporters. This guideline was published in 2020 and includes responses to 10 questions that were created using the Population/Intervention/Comparator/Outcome (PICO) format. They address screening for conditions known to be of higher prevalence in individuals with Down syndrome. In the United States, hypothyroidism is common in individuals with Down syndrome, with an estimated prevalence of approximately 50≥ in adults >30 years of age. Screening is therefore recommended with TSH testing every 1 – 2 years starting at age 21. This patient''s TSH level was last checked 2 years ago and is due today. Dementia occurs on average at younger ages in those with Down syndrome than those without Down syndrome; however, it is rare before the age of 40. If any concerning symptoms arise in this age group, a thorough investigation for alternative causes is recommended. Routine screening for dementia is recommended beginning at age 40 for individuals with Down syndrome. A validated tool such as the National Task Group – Early Detection Screen for Dementia should be used. Cardiovascular disease prevention is recommended for individuals with Down syndrome per U.S. Preventive Services Task Force guidelines. This patient''s LDL - cholesterol level was last checked 2 years ago and is not due for recheck today. The prevalence of osteoporosis in individuals with Down syndrome has been estimated with a wide degree of variation (1.4≥ – 45.1≥). There is no evidence that DXA screening at ages younger than recommended for adults without Down syndrome (age 65) is of benefit. Although atlantoaxial instability (AAI) is known to have a higher prevalence in those with Down syndrome than those without Down syndrome, no studies have assessed the use of cervical spine radiography for diagnosing AAI. Screening radiography is therefore not recommended; instead, it is recommended that clinicians remain alert for signs and symptoms of cervical myelopathy, such as incontinence, altered gait, brisk reflexes, and clonus.', options = '["The National Task Group – Early Detection Screen for Dementia tool","A fasting lipid panel","TSH testing","A DXA scan","Cervical spine radiography"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'b0e477fe-aa9a-4077-af70-8753a376891c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'You are participating in a continuing medical education (CME) course at a Colorado ski resort that is 9600 ft (2926 m) above sea level. You and your travel companions have had intermittent issues with headaches, loss of appetite, and difficulty sleeping. O n the third day, one of your companions starts to experience shortness of breath that is not relieved with rest. Their symptoms worsen throughout the day and they become slightly tachycardic. Later that evening, they develop a cough that produces frothy sp utum. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'The risk for acute mountain sickness increases when sleeping above altitudes of about 8200 ft (2499 m). Symptoms can include difficulty sleeping, headaches, and decreased appetite. This patient has more severe symptoms of high - altitude pulmonary edema (HAPE), which is a medical emergency, and should begin supplemental oxygen and descend to a lower altitude if possible. Acetazolamide can be used to prevent acute mountain sickness, but it is not a treatment. Dexamethasone is a supplemental treatment for high - altitude cerebral edema. Nifedipine can be used in the prevention of HAPE and as a treatment in emergency situations in which descent or a hyperbaric chamber is not available. In this case, the patient is at a modern ski resort and descent should be feasible. COVID - 19 infection is unlikely in this scenario.', options = '["Acetazolamide","Dexamethasone","Nifedipine","A COVID - 19 test","Oxygen supplementation, and descending to a lower elevation"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'c7d488f5-6be4-4452-9272-68e0177fb6e2';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following antibiotics is most commonly associated with Stevens - Johnson syndrome?', explanation = 'Antibiotics are the most common cause of Stevens - Johnson syndrome (SJS) and toxic epidermal necrolysis, accounting for more than one - quarter of cases worldwide. Sulfonamide antibiotics, such as sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim, are associated with the majority of antibiotic - associated SJS cases worldwide. Antibiotic stewardship is always important, and consideration for both relatively benign and life - threatening side effects should be considered with every prescription written.', options = '["Cephalexin","Ciprofloxacin","Fosfomycin","Nitrofurantoin","Sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '2be847c2-a16b-439a-9a87-23c70738c561';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'During an annual visit, a 62 - year - old female reports an episode of vaginal spotting that lasted for a few days in May. It is now July and she has not had another recurrence. A transvaginal ultrasound shows an endometrial stripe of 4 mm, no fibroids, and no polyps. Which one of the following would be most appropriate regarding follow - up evaluation?', explanation = 'Transvaginal ultrasonography or endometrial biopsy are both appropriate initial diagnostic tests for postmenopausal bleeding. An ultrasound showing an endometrial stripe ≤4 mm is associated with a >99≥ negative predictive value for endometrial cancer and no further evaluation is needed unless the bleeding is recurrent. If bleeding is persistent or recurrent, then a tissue sample would be appropriate. If an endometrial biopsy is not helpful and bleeding continues to persist or recur, then further evaluation with hysteroscopy and curettage would be indicated.', options = '["No further evaluation","Endometrial biopsy","Hysteroscopy and biopsy","Dilation and curettage","Repeat ultrasonography in 1 year"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '77f5eadd-fa8e-4f93-921b-43f73f5f7181';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 25 - year - old male presents with shoulder pain after having fallen on his arm in an outstretched position. He reports a sensation of catching and popping in the shoulder. With the patient seated and hands placed on his hips, you apply force to the elbow an d direct the humerus anteriorly and superiorly, while asking the patient to resist your motion, which produces pain in the affected shoulder. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', explanation = 'This patient''s history of a catching or popping sensation combined with a positive anterior slide test, as described in the physical examination, is highly suggestive of a glenoid labral tear. This combination of history and the positive anterior slide test has a positive likelihood ratio of 6.0 in diagnosing a glenoid labral tear. Acromioclavicular joint arthritis presents with superior shoulder pain and tenderness over the acromioclavicular joint, often with a positive cross - body adduction test. Adhesive capsulitis is characterized by diffuse shoulder pain and restricted passive range of motion. Glenohumeral osteoarthritis usually presents with a gradual onset of pain and loss of motion, particularly in older patients. A rotator cuff tear typically presents with pain and weakness, especially with overhead activities, and positive findings on the empty can and external rotation tests. Acromioclavicular joint arthritis, adhesive capsulitis, glenohumeral osteoarthritis, and rotator cuff tears are not associated with catching or popping sensations, and the crank and anterior slide tests are not specific for these conditions.', options = '["Acromioclavicular joint arthritis","Adhesive capsulitis","Glenohumeral osteoarthritis","A glenoid labral tear","A rotator cuff tear"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '4cf5a6ce-d8aa-4805-bcdc-3b8fb50687e7';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'According to the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force, which one of the following is the recommended next step for adults who screen positive for unhealthy alcohol use?', explanation = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommends screening all adults for unhealthy alcohol use and implementing brief counseling interventions for those who screen positive (B recommendation). The screening, brief intervention, and referral to treatment (SBIRT) approach has been shown to decrease the number of patients with risky drinking after the intervention. Motivational interviewing is often used for brief counseling in primary care settings. Cognitive behavioral therapy, mindfulness - based therapy, and interpersonal psychotherapy are different psychotherapy approaches that are used as longer - term counseling methods and would not be appropriate for use as brief counseling interventions for adults with unhealthy alcohol use. Patients identified as having alcohol use disorder (AUD) by DSM - 5 criteria should be referred for treatment.', options = '["Brief counseling interventions","Cognitive behavioral therapy","Mindfulness - based therapy","Interpersonal psychotherapy","Referral for alcohol use disorder treatment"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '1375d721-bf6b-49da-af67-f10ed62e92bc';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 30 - year - old female presents with constipation and severe anal pain following bowel movements. On examination, you observe an anal fissure. In addition to increasing fluids, fiber, and warm sitz baths, which one of the following would be effective and least likely to result in side effects?', explanation = 'For anal fissures, topical sphincter relaxants applied externally around the anus 2 – 4 times per day help reduce sphincter tone and promote healing. Topical calcium channel blockers such as diltiazem are best tolerated. Topical nitroglycerin is also effective but is associated with more side effects such as headaches and lightheadedness, which results in 1 in 5 patients stopping therapy. Botulinum toxin is also effective. Topical capsaicin is an irritant. Oral calcium channel blockers are not effective for treatment of anal fissures.', options = '["Topical calcium channel blockers","Topical capsaicin","Topical nitroglycerin","Oral calcium channel blockers"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '72c30cfb-921f-4efc-ae9b-71bcd0e7cd5b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following interventions lowers the risk of diverticulitis?', explanation = 'Diverticulitis is an inflammation of diverticula caused by a protrusion through the intestinal wall. Risk factors include constipation, a low - fiber diet, increasing age, red meat consumption, smoking, obesity, lack of exercise, aspirin and NSAID use, and genetic susceptibility. Consuming a vegetarian diet may help to prevent diverticulitis. Red meat intake, long - term NSAID use, and tobacco use are risk factors for diverticulitis. After years of research, it was concluded that consumption of nuts, seeds, and popcorn is not a risk factor for diverticulitis (SOR B). The incidence of diverticulitis is increasing, yet screening is not recommended. Tenderness located in the left lower quadrant of the abdomen is the most specific finding of diverticulitis. Evaluation includes a CBC, a basic metabolic panel, a C - reactive protein level, and urine analysis. CT with contrast is the imaging modality of choice if the diagnosis is uncertain. Treatment is based on severity and includes oral and intravenous antibiotics, bowel rest and a clear liquid diet, and surgical management for abscess formation or peritonitis as well as for prevention of recurrences.', options = '["Avoiding consumption of popcorn, nuts, and seeds","Regular consumption of red meat","A vegetarian diet","Long - term NSAID use"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '91fc3da1-d462-4723-bd69-8c4ba85f2b16';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An 82 - year - old male presents to your office because he has been experiencing severe, stabbing pain that feels like an electric shock on the left side of his face in his cheek, lips, and chin. The episodes are usually triggered by light touch or eating and last for a few seconds. Which one of the following cranial nerves is associated with this disorder?', explanation = 'Trigeminal neuralgia is characterized by severe paroxysms of pain in the distribution of 1 or more branches of cranial nerve V. Impairment of cranial nerve VII results in paralysis of facial muscles, such as Bell palsy. Impairment of cranial nerve X may cause dysphagia and dysphonia, cranial nerve XI involvement results in neck weakness, and cranial nerve XII damage leads to tongue paralysis.', options = '["V","VII","X","XI","XII"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'beb00c5f-e303-4c55-a753-9fbfe9fbc44c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following social determinants of health has a protective effective against Alzheimer disease and related types of dementia?', explanation = 'Social determinants of health (SDOH) are the conditions in which people are born, work, live, and age as well as the wider set of forces and systems that shape the conditions of daily life. Several SDOH affect cognition and risk of Alzheimer disease and related dementias (ADRDs). For example, higher levels of social engagement have a protective effect against ADRDs. Conversely, SDOH such as decreasing BMI with older age, early - life adversity, low education level, food insecurity, midlife obesity, manual labor, and low socioeconomic status are associated with a greater risk of ADRDs.', options = '["Decreasing BMI with older age","Early - life adversity","Low education level","Social engagement"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '9ba461d9-f7ae-4114-a002-21bf635e9ad0';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 72 - year - old male with a history of type 2 diabetes comes to your office for evaluation of muscle aches and fatigue. His current medications include rosuvastatin (Crestor), dapagliflozin (Farxiga), and semaglutide (Ozempic). Over the past month he has noticed increasing pain in his hips, thighs, and shoulders without any apparent trigger. He feels so stiff in the morning that it is becoming difficult to get out of bed. On examination his strength is diminished (4/5) in the proximal muscle groups. You do not note any swelling or redness of any joints, muscles, or extremities. He has normal reflexes and no clonus. Laboratory Findings Hemoglobin A 6.4≥ 1c Hemoglobin 12.2 g/dL (N 13.2 – 16.6) Creatinine 1.1 mg/dL (N 0.7 – 1.3) Potassium 4.2 mEq/L (N 3.5 – 5.1) Creatine kinase 84 U/L (N 55 – 170) Erythrocyte sedimentation rate 88 mm/hr (N 0 – 20) C - reactive protein 9.2 mg/L (N 0 – 0.3) Antinuclear antibody <1:40 (N <1:40) Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient''s myalgias?', explanation = 'These findings are concerning for polymyalgia rheumatica (PMR), an inflammatory condition that typically affects adults ≥50 years of age. This patient''s proximal muscle pain, fatigue, and decreased proximal muscle strength are consistent with this diagnosis, as are the elevated inflammatory markers (erythrocyte sedimentation rate and C - reactive protein level) and mild anemia. A normal creatine kinase level is expected in patients with PMR. PMR is diagnosed clinically and treated with oral glucocorticoids. Rapid improvement with therapy is expected; if improvement does not occur, an alternate diagnosis should be explored. Giant cell arteritis, also known as temporal arteritis, is associated with PMR. It causes temporal headaches, visual changes, and constitutional symptoms. Early identification and treatment are essential to prevent permanent vision change. Fibromyalgia does not cause elevated inflammatory markers. Polymyositis and statin - induced myopathy may cause myalgias but are typically associated with elevations in creatine kinase, which this patient does not have. Almost all patients with systemic lupus erythematosus have an elevated antinuclear antibody titer, which this patient also does not have.', options = '["Fibromyalgia","Polymyalgia rheumatica","Polymyositis","Statin - induced myopathy","Systemic lupus erythematosus"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '4f83d3ea-3fe6-4f62-a3cf-81907631285b';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommends which one of the following regarding screening asymptomatic adolescents and adults for herpes simplex virus?', explanation = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force concluded with moderate certainty that the harms outweighed the benefits for routine, population - based serologic screening for infection with herpes simplex virus (HSV) in asymptomatic adolescents and adults, including pregnant patients (D recommendation). High false - positive rates are common in asymptomatic patients who undergo serologic testing for infection with HSV. In addition, treatment is not recommended in asymptomatic patients with a positive test.', options = '["No testing","HSV - 1 antibody testing","HSV - 2 antibody testing","HSV - 1 and HSV - 2 antibody testing","HSV - 1 and HSV - 2 antigen testing"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '5d58c50f-4e5c-4ad5-8286-060cb50c23a5';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 2 - year - old child is brought to the urgent care clinic by their parents with a 2 - day history of abdominal pain and vomiting. The child has been irritable over the past 2 days with intermittent abdominal pain and several episodes of associated emesis, and just had a bloody stool that the parents describe as resembling jelly. The child appears uncomfortable but is alert and afebrile, with normal blood pressure. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', explanation = 'Intussusception is a condition in which a part of the intestine slides or "telescopes" into an adjacent section. It presents with a classic triad of intermittent abdominal pain, emesis, and blood - tinged mucous stools that are sometimes called "red currant jelly" stools. It most commonly occurs at the ileocolic junction and typically affects infants and toddlers. The initial evaluation begins with ultrasonography. An enema with air or contrast can both confirm the diagnosis and reverse the intussusception. If this procedure does not relieve the condition, surgical correction is necessary. Necrotizing enterocolitis is a severe intestinal infection that typically presents with severe abdominal pain, lethargy, and unstable vital signs. Pyloric stenosis is notable for projectile vomiting, but not bloody stools. Volvulus typically involves a sudden onset of vomiting and abdominal pain and even distension, but without bloody stools.', options = '["Intussusception","Necrotizing enterocolitis","Pyloric stenosis","Volvulus"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '2885210e-eb81-4a12-ab88-1e1c2b746c64';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A generally healthy 54 - year - old male with a 20 - pack - year smoking history presents to discuss smoking cessation. His first grandchild was just born and he is eager for help in quitting cigarette smoking. He quit smoking 2 years ago using nicotine gum (Nicor ette Gum), but resumed smoking 5 months later. He has also explored telephone helplines and support groups, but did not find them beneficial. He currently smokes 1 pack of cigarettes per day. Which one of the following would be most likely to help this patient quit smoking?', explanation = 'Seven pharmacotherapies are approved by the FDA for smoking cessation, including bupropion, varenicline, and 5 forms of nicotine replacement therapy (NRT). All of these have been shown to be beneficial in smoking cessation compared to placebo. Compared to NRT and bupropion, varenicline appears to be the most effective monotherapy with a number needed to treat of 7. Recent meta - analyses suggest that a combination of pharmacotherapies is more effective than monotherapy. Varenicline plus NRT is more likely to result in sustained smoking cessation compared to bupropion plus NRT.', options = '["Nicotine gum only","Extended - release bupropion (Wellbutrin SR) only","Varenicline only","Nicotine gum plus extended - release bupropion","Nicotine gum plus varenicline"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '01b45414-4b3a-41e4-aba1-1d0deaba7623';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 60 - year - old female returns to discuss management of her recurrent nephrolithiasis. She has a history of calcium stones and just recently passed her fourth stone this year despite appropriate lifestyle changes, including a fluid intake of 3 L per day and a diet high in fiber and low in animal protein. She would like a medication to help prevent the development of more kidney stones. She has a past medical history of asthma for which she takes a budesonide/formoterol inhaler (Symbicort) as needed. Today, he r vital signs and a physical examination are normal. A recent basic metabolic panel was normal. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate prevention strategy?', explanation = 'Lifestyle changes such as appropriate fluid intake (2.5 – 3.0 L of liquid per day), a diet high in fiber and low in animal protein, lower sodium intake (<4 – 5 g per day), and moderate calcium intake (1200 mg per day) can help reduce recurrence of calcium stones. However, if patients continue to develop recurrent calcium stones, it is reasonable to initiate pharmacologic therapy. Appropriate medications include high - dose thiazide diuretics, allopurinol, and potassium citrate. Furosemide would not be appropriate as it has been associated with kidney stone formation. Magnesium oxide has not been shown to decrease the risk of stone development. Tamsulosin can be used to help with stone expulsion, but it does not help to prevent stones.', options = '["Lifestyle modifications only","Furosemide (Lasix), 20 mg daily","Hydrochlorothiazide, 50 mg daily","Magnesium oxide, 400 mg twice daily","Tamsulosin (Flomax), 0.4 mg daily"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'd7412697-0e38-4e6e-a86e-bd2588261e72';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 72 - year - old female is brought to the emergency department after her neighbor found her on the floor in her home. She is drowsy and confused, and unable to provide any history. An initial laboratory evaluation reveals the following: Glucose 95 mg/dL BUN 9 mg/dL (N 6 – 20) Creatinine 0.9 mg/dL (N 0.5 – 1.1) Estimated glomerular filtration rate 63 mL/min/1.73 m Sodium 118 mEq/L (N 135 – 145) Potassium 3.0 mEq/L (N 3.3 – 5.0) Chloride 88 mEq/L (N 101 – 115) Bicarbonate 22 mEq/L (N 16 – 30) Anion gap 8 mEq / L (N 5 – 14) Calcium 8.8 mg/dL (N 8.4 – 10.5) Which one of the following would be the most appropriate intervention at this time?', explanation = 'This patient presents with symptomatic severe hyponatremia (sodium level <125 mEq/L). The most appropriate intervention at this time is a 100 - mL bolus of 3≥ hypertonic saline (SOR B), which may be repeated up to 2 times at 10 - minute intervals with the goal of increasing the sodium level by 4 – 6 mEq/L. Serum sodium levels should be monitored after every bolus and every 6 hours during the first 24 hours of treatment (SOR C). Avoiding rapid correction of severe hyponatremia is important to prevent osmotic demyelination syndrome. Depending on risk factors, sodium correction should be limited to 8 – 12 mEq/L over 24 hours or 18 mEq/L over 48 hours (SOR C). The use of normal saline is appropriate treatment for nonsevere hypovolemic hyponatremia (a sodium level ≥125 mEq/L but <135 mEq/L). Intravenous desmopressin (DDAVP) is indicated for treatment of diabetes insipidus, which usually presents with high - normal sodium levels or hypernatremia. Desmopressin may also be given with 5≥ dextrose in water if overcorrection of severe hyponatremia has occurred.', options = '["Free water restriction","Normal saline infusion","3≥ hypertonic saline bolus","Intravenous desmopressin (DDAVP)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '1b0464bd-788c-4f38-b60a-a9b2bb33a261';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 35 - year - old construction worker presents to your office with an acute onset of lower back pain that began 3 days ago. The patient describes the pain as a burning sensation that radiates down his left leg. He has no bowel or bladder dysfunction and has be en in good health. A straight leg – raising test is positive at 45° on the left without motor deficit. Which one of the following does evidence support as the first step in treatment of this patient''s condition?', explanation = 'In the absence of red flags (fracture, malignancy, epidural abscess, or cauda equina syndrome), the approach to acute lumbar radiculopathy should be conservative. Most patients improve over the first 2 weeks, and there is level B evidence that mobilization and manipulation is of benefit. Bed rest was previously recommended, but current data supports allowing the patient to be as active as the pain allows. While corticosteroids, NSAIDs, and muscle relaxants are often used, evidence to do so is lacking. In the subacute stage, neurodynamic mobilization and strength training could be added. If there is no improvement over 6 weeks, then MRI should be ordered.', options = '["Bed rest for 3 days","Mobilization and manipulation","A short - term corticosteroid","Cyclobenzaprine","MRI"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '73cf69d3-14af-40a2-b647-8d4838c7ea2d';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 46 - year - old male with chronic hypertension presents to your clinic for routine follow - up. Due to issues with insurance coverage, he has not been taking his antihypertensive medications for the last 2 months. Today, he is asymptomatic and an examination i s normal, except for a blood pressure of 162/100 mm Hg, which is confirmed on repeat testing. In addition to addressing insurance and social determinants of health, which one of the following would be most appropriate for this patient?', explanation = 'The vast majority of patients treated for essential hypertension will require 2 or more agents to achieve adequate blood pressure control. Combination therapy with a calcium channel blocker and an °CE inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker (ARB) would be most appropriate for this patient with stage 2 hypertension. Stage 2 hypertension is defined as a systolic blood pressure ≥160 mm Hg or a diastolic blood pressure ≥100 mm Hg (or a systolic blood pressure >20 mm Hg above goal or a diastolic blood pressure >10 mm Hg above goal). Race - based prescribing, which advises preferential use of thiazide or calcium channel blockers for Black patients, has demonstrated insufficient blood pressure control and is thus falling out of favor. β - Blockers are not used as first - line treatment for hypertension, but they may be indicated in patients with specific comorbidities, such as coronary artery disease or heart failure. Aldosterone antagonists are also not typically used as first - line treatment for hypertension, but they may be used if multiple other drug classes cannot achieve adequate blood pressure control. Monotherapy is unlikely to produce adequate blood pressure control in this patient.', options = '["Monotherapy with a calcium channel blocker (CCB)","Monotherapy with a thiazide - like diuretic","Combination therapy with a CCB and an °CE inhibitor","Combination therapy with a diuretic and a β - blocker","Combination therapy with a diuretic and an aldosterone antagonist"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'b2171d72-5deb-490b-8b74-abf4e6b332c5';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 14 - year - old female presents to your office with her mother who is concerned about her daughter''s recent 15 - lb weight loss and severe fatigue. After ruling out other etiologies, you diagnose anorexia nervosa. Which one of the following findings, if present in this patient, would indicate the need for inpatient care?', explanation = 'A potassium level of 2.6 mEq/L would indicate the need for inpatient care of this patient''s anorexia nervosa. Eating disorders can often be treated in the outpatient setting with a multidisciplinary care team including physicians, therapists, and dietitians. However, certain findings, including severe hypokalemia, require higher levels of care. While hair loss, muscle atrophy, parotid gland enlargement, and elevated sodium can all be found in patients with eating disorders, severe electrolyte abnormalities can lead to life - threatening cardiac complications and require immediate treatment.', options = '["Hair loss","Muscle atrophy","Parotid gland enlargement","A potassium level of 2.6 mEq/L (N 3.5 – 4.9)","A sodium level of 146 mEq/L (N 134 – 145)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '21ba2cd8-ea73-45ca-9f3e-25a3c5df5b30';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 30 - year - old female presents to your office for an annual wellness visit. She reports a family history of Lynch syndrome and recently tested positive herself. Which one of the following should you recommend regarding colon cancer screening in this patient?', explanation = 'Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCC), formerly called Lynch syndrome, is a hereditary cancer syndrome that increases the risk for several types of cancer, especially colon cancer. Guidelines recommend that patients with HNPCC should start colon cancer screening with colonoscopy between 20 and 25 years of age and repeat every 1 – 2 years. Patients at average risk for colon cancer should begin colon cancer screening at age 45. Fecal occult blood testing, stool DNA testing, and sigmoidoscopy are not adequate screening tests in this high - risk population. Lynch syndrome is associated with increased risk for several other cancers including endometrial, ovarian, stomach, small - bowel, and pancreatic.', options = '["Fecal occult blood testing annually","Stool DNA testing (Cologuard) every 3 years","Colonoscopy starting this year","Colonoscopy starting at age 45","Sigmoidoscopy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '523cb31c-000b-4236-a9ea-e0a57086a31a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 53 - year - old male without a significant past medical history presents to the emergency department for evaluation of abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. Pertinent findings on presentation include notable tenderness in the epigastrium and a lipase level > 3 times the upper limit of normal. He is admitted for acute pancreatitis. Intravenous lactated Ringer solution, antiemetics, and pain control are initiated. At the time of your evaluation he has normal vital signs and reports improved symptoms, although yo u still note abdominal tenderness. When entering admission orders for this patient, which one of the following diets would be most appropriate?', explanation = 'Pancreatitis is associated with an intense inflammatory response that increases caloric needs, and nutrition management is a key component of care. Acute pancreatitis is also associated with reduced perfusion of the intestinal mucosa, leading to tissue damage and increased intestinal permeability. Enteral feeding provides calories and increases splanchnic blood flow, leading to improved integrity of the bowel wall and improved gut motility. Patients with acute pancreatitis benefit from early enteral feeding within 24 hours of admission. A Cochrane review found that enteral nutrition has been associated with lower mortality, less multiple organ failure, and less systemic infection compared with parenteral nutrition. In severe acute pancreatitis, the benefits of enteral nutrition appear to be even more notable with a relative risk of death of 0.18 (95≥ CI 0.06 to 0.58). Liquid and soft diets have no evidence of benefit over a low - fat solid diet, and some studies found a shorter length of stay in patients started on solid diets rather than liquid diets. If patients cannot tolerate an oral diet within 72 hours, enteral nutrition should be provided via nasogastric or nasojejunal tube. Parenteral nutrition should be administered in patients who cannot tolerate tube feeding. Low - carbohydrate diets are not recommended because they are often high in fat and may worsen pancreatic inflammation.', options = '["Full liquids","Low - carbohydrate","Low - fat","NPO"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '026ae9b5-7af1-416f-b750-e74833e1df1f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A healthy 57 - year - old female presents for an annual health maintenance visit. Her last menstrual period was 2 years ago. She exercises 5 times per week, does not smoke, and rarely drinks alcohol. Her BMI is 23 kg/m . Her 80 - year - old mother has no history of fractures, but takes alendronate (Fosamax), 70 mg weekly. According to the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force, which one of the following would be the preferred strategy to screen for osteoporosis in this patient?', explanation = 'According to the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF), women ≥65 years of age should be screened for osteoporosis using DXA bone mineral density testing, regardless of fracture risk assessment. Postmenopausal women <65 years of age with 1 or more additional risk factors such as smoking, excessive alcohol consumption, or parental history of hip fracture should also be screened with DXA. This patient does not have any significant risk factors. Tools such as FRAX can be used to help counsel patients regarding the future risk of fracture, but they are not intended to be used to determine who should receive further screening with DXA.', options = '["Using the FRAX tool now to determine the need for DXA screening","Using the FRAX tool at age 65 to determine the need for DXA screening","Screening now with DXA","Screening at age 65 with DXA"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'ec635015-3131-486b-8269-3b0d7ff17916';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'You are evaluating a patient with acute - on - chronic kidney disease and a serum potassium level of 6.5 mEq/L (N 3.3 – 5.0). In addition to peaked T waves, which one of the following additional electrocardiogram changes is most likely to be present?', explanation = 'Hyperkalemia (potassium level >5.0 mEq/L) can occur with impaired renal excretion, transcellular shifts, and increased potassium intake. Management of severe hyperkalemia includes using diagnostic EKG to identify cardiac conditions requiring emergent treatment. EKG changes associated with hyperkalemia include peaked T waves, prolonged PR interval, loss of P waves, and prolonged QRS interval. Hyperkalemia resulting in prolonged QRS interval, bradycardia, and junctional rhythm is associated with adverse events, including ventricular fibrillation, cardiopulmonary resuscitation, and death within 6 hours of measurement. Findings associated with hypokalemia (potassium level <3.5 mEq/L) include flattened T waves, prolonged QT interval, ST segment depression, U waves, and T - wave inversion. Delta waves are not associated with potassium disorders but are present in Wolff - Parkinson - White syndrome.', options = '["Delta waves","Prolonged QRS interval","Prolonged QT interval","ST segment depression","U waves"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'ea4d5b75-0e8c-4237-84c7-fadc7c16371c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 15 - year - old male comes to your clinic 30 minutes after being hit in the face by a baseball during practice. He is alert and answers questions appropriately. After clearing the blood, you find that his upper front tooth (No. 8) is quite loose and the root is visible. The tooth is lying lower than his other teeth. The tooth appears intact and without fracture. There is no crepitus or pain when palpating the alveolar and mandibular bones. You immediately call his dentist to arrange an emergency appointment. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step prior to sending the patient to the dentist''s office?', explanation = 'For dislodged or fully avulsed permanent teeth, immediate reimplantation or repositioning is recommended (SOR C). Time is imperative in saving teeth. If reimplantation does not occur within 1 hour, there is little likelihood that it will be successful. If possible, replace the tooth in its anatomic position and have the patient bite down on a washcloth or gauze to keep it in place. It is not advised to remove a loose tooth, as the safest medium for the tooth is the socket. If the tooth is fully avulsed, hold it by the crown, rinse with saline, and reimplant. A tooth that cannot be reimplanted should be placed in a saline solution or milk. Antibiotic treatment is not imperative at this time. Without evidence of a dental or bony fracture, immediate imaging is not necessary as it would delay reimplantation and referral to a dentist.', options = '["No intervention is needed","Repositioning the tooth in the socket and having the patient bite down on gauze","Gently removing the tooth and placing it in saline or milk","Ceftriaxone, 1 g intramuscularly","Imaging of the facial bones"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '34fef27d-05ba-40b8-81ae-d498f14c7b35';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 50 - year - old female presents for follow - up of laboratory studies. At her last visit, she presented with palpitations, anxiety, and unintentional weight loss. An examination was notable for exophthalmos. Her laboratory results show a very low TSH level wit h elevated free T and normal total T levels. A radioactive iodine uptake scan demonstrates a high, homogeneous uptake of iodine. Which one of the following medications is the most appropriate treatment for this condition?', explanation = 'This patient has hyperthyroidism, specifically Graves disease. Diffusely high radioactive iodine uptake differentiates Graves disease from other thyroid conditions, including toxic adenoma (high uptake concentrated in one spot), toxic multinodular goiter (high uptake in multiple spots), and thyroiditis (low uptake). Treatment options for Graves disease include antithyroid medications, radioactive iodine ablation, and surgical thyroidectomy. The most appropriate treatment is usually determined based on the risks and benefits of each option and patient preference. Methimazole is the preferred antithyroid medication for treatment of Graves disease due to its improved safety profile compared to propylthiouracil, which has a greater risk of severe liver injury. Pregnant patients in the first trimester should be treated with propylthiouracil because it has a lower teratogenic risk than methimazole. Levothyroxine is used to treat hypothyroidism. Prednisone is used to treat severe hyperthyroidism, such as thyroid storm. A calcium channel blocker such as verapamil would be indicated if a β - blocker is contraindicated or not tolerated.', options = '["Levothyroxine (Synthroid)","Methimazole","Prednisone","Propylthiouracil","Verapamil"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'b73fc254-c228-4b63-8acf-8798d2512ff3';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An 85 - year - old male on the third day of hospitalization for the treatment of pneumonia develops symptoms of altered mental status. Evaluation of his medications does not identify a reason for his altered mental status. The nursing staff has been unable to successfully redirect him to keep him calm. Which one of the following medications would be appropriate for the management of the patient''s delirium?', explanation = 'Delirium is a syndrome characterized by an acute, fluctuating disturbance of attention, awareness, and cognition. Initial efforts should focus on identifying and addressing any underlying causes while providing redirection. However, if no reversible cause is found, managing delirium using medications becomes the most appropriate next step to ensure the patient''s safety. While there are no FDA - approved medications for the management of delirium, second - generation antipsychotics such as olanzapine are preferred for this indication. Haloperidol is a less preferred option, compared to a second - generation antipsychotic. It is known to cause QT prolongation and other concerning side effects in older patients. Lithium is indicated for chronic management of bipolar disorder and does not have a role in the acute management of this patient''s delirium. The side effects of benzodiazepines such as lorazepam make them undesirable for managing delirium, particularly in an older adult. Oxycodone is an opioid analgesic that would likely provide some degree of sedation but would not be appropriate for managing this patient''s delirium.', options = '["Haloperidol","Lithium","Lorazepam (Ativan)","Olanzapine (Zyprexa)","Oxycodone"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'dee3ae65-c3e9-4b3c-ace7-0fbb2c5eafad';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An 84 - year - old male with a history of coronary artery disease, mild cognitive impairment, and type 2 diabetes is admitted to your hospital for a hip fracture after a recent fall. On examination the patient has normal speech but is confused. He is clearly u nable to articulate his understanding of the risks and benefits of surgery. You should do which one of the following to determine this patient''s decision - making capacity regarding surgery?', explanation = 'This patient clearly lacks the capacity to make decisions, and a surrogate decision - maker should be consulted. If designated, a durable power of attorney for health care should make decisions for this patient. Structured assessments for determining decision - making capacity or cognitive function may help in uncertain cases but are not necessary in this situation. Psychiatry consultation is rarely necessary to determine decision - making capacity and would not be appropriate in this situation. Decision - making capacity is determined by the treating clinician, not the court.', options = '["Administer the Aid to Capacity Evaluation assessment tool","Administer the Montreal Cognitive Assessment evaluation tool","Document a lack of capacity and consult his designated durable power of attorney","Consult with psychiatry","Defer to the court"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '28f7b3f1-d2c1-4d3b-8c0a-e48b5f2ff4a2';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 36 - year - old backcountry skier becomes separated from her group during a blizzard. The ski patrol locates her several hours later, sitting on the ground and not moving or shivering. She is conscious but confused. Which one of the following would be the most important initial step?', explanation = 'Hypothermia is a potentially life - threatening condition that physicians and first responders should be able to promptly recognize and treat. While core temperature is useful for academic purposes or in a hospital, it is impractical to obtain and unimportant in the field. A simplified hypothermia assessment for field use evaluates the patient''s level of consciousness, presence or absence of shivering, level of alertness, and spontaneous movements to categorize the severity of hypothermia. This patient is not moving or shivering, and although she is conscious she is not alert. This patient is experiencing moderate hypothermia and requires immediate intervention. A patient with moderate hypothermia should be kept horizontal, have large warming packs placed in the axillae and around the upper chest, be wrapped in an insulated vapor barrier (the burrito method), and be prepared for transport to the nearest medical facility, ideally one with an ICU. Warm fluids and high - calorie foods can be used for a patient who is cold stressed or has mild hypothermia. Wet clothes should not be removed in the field unless shelter is available and rescue is more than 30 minutes away because this risks further lowering the patient''s core temperature. Intubation is not necessary because the patient is protecting her airway and is conscious. Furthermore, it would not warm her.', options = '["Obtaining a core body temperature","Providing a warm drink and high - calorie snack, and reconnecting her with her group","Having her remove her wet clothes and wrapping her in an insulated vapor barrier","Placing large heat pads around her upper body and wrapping her in an insulated vapor barrier","Performing emergency rapid sequence field intubation and preparing for evacuation"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '1a465b3e-2e32-4278-8a08-b4b3b16bd2e7';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 63 - year - old male presents for his annual health maintenance examination. He maintains a healthy lifestyle, eats well, and exercises regularly. A physical examination is normal. His most recent prostate cancer screening revealed a PSA level of 4.6 ng/mL ( N 0.3 – 4.0), and his previous result 2 years ago was normal. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', explanation = 'Prostate cancer screening recommendations vary, and there is little evidence that routine screening for prostate cancer improves patient - oriented outcomes. While the American Academy of Family Physicians does not recommend routine prostate - specific antigen (PSA) – based screening for prostate cancer, the American Urology Association (AUA) recommends prostate cancer screening with PSA testing for those 45 – 50 years of age. For those 50 – 69 years of age, the AUA recommends screening every 2 – 4 years between ages 50 - 69. The AUA also recommends obtaining a follow - up PSA level for individuals with newly elevated PSA before considering additional biomarkers, imaging, or biopsy. While this is based on expert opinion, the authors note that PSA may normalize in as many as 40≥ of individuals. The authors also suggest a higher threshold for biopsy based on age, with 4.5 ng/mL being the upper limit of normal for this patient''s age group. The Choosing Wisely AUA initiative recommends against using empiric antibiotics to treat elevated PSA levels in asymptomatic individuals. A digital rectal examination is not recommended as a screening method alone or in addition to a screening PSA.', options = '["Repeating PSA testing in 4 – 8 weeks","Empiric antibiotic therapy","A digital rectal examination","Biopsy of the prostate","MRI of the prostate"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'e5d2e81d-5442-4c9e-b47c-81836f071673';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'An otherwise healthy 37 - year - old female presents because of a 4 - day history of multiple episodes of watery, nonbloody diarrhea. She has no fever, chills, abdominal pain, or vomiting. She does not have a history of recent antibiotic use, hospitalization, or travel, but does say that her teenage son recently returned from a spring break trip and has similar symptoms. Physical examination findings include dry mucous membranes and tachycardia. The abdomen is soft with mild generalized tenderness on deep palpati on. Which one of the following next steps would be most appropriate at this time?', explanation = 'Testing for fecal calprotectin, lactoferrin, and leukocytes is of limited value in evaluating a nontoxic patient with acute diarrhea, including infectious diarrhea. Testing for fecal occult blood and infection with Clostridioides difficile is also not recommended in these patients. Detecting fecal calprotectin in a patient with inflammatory bowel disease and bacterial diarrhea lacks consistency and is not recommended. Although the presence of fecal lactoferrin can be associated with a bacterial etiology, its lack of specificity makes it less useful. Fecal leukocytes disintegrate easily in stool samples, reducing test sensitivity. Indications for obtaining stool testing for acute infection include the presence of severe abdominal pain or tenderness, bloody or mucoid stools, clinical findings of sepsis, fever ≥38.3 °C (101.0 °F), immunocompromised state, recent hospitalization, recent antibiotic therapy, and diarrhea that lasts >7 days.', options = '["No testing","Fecal calprotectin","Fecal lactoferrin","Fecal leukocytes"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'a9920c29-8571-485f-86d0-c384bd3141d2';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following dog bite wounds should be considered for primary closure instead of being left to heal by secondary intention?', explanation = 'Dog bite wounds may be primarily closed if desired for cosmetic reasons such as wounds to the face. However, dog bite wounds that carry a higher risk of infection such crush injuries, wounds to the hand, and puncture wounds, should be left to heal by secondary intention. Other factors that increase the risk of infection include delayed presentation (>6 – 12 hours for bites to the arm or leg and >12 – 24 hours for bites to the face) and bites in people who are immunosuppressed, including those with diabetes mellitus.', options = '["A crush injury to the arm","A gaping wound to the hand","A linear wound to the face","A puncture wound to the leg"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '4251dcbd-485a-443f-8a95-506194948230';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 32 - year - old female comes to your office with her husband after a recent weeklong episode of elevated mood and energy that meets the diagnostic criteria for a manic episode. They both say that she has never had any episodes of depression, low mood, or anh edonia. This patient’s presentation is most consistent with which one of the following disorders?', explanation = 'Bipolar I disorder does not require a history of a major depressive episode and may be diagnosed and treated based on just 1 manic episode. The diagnosis of bipolar II disorder requires at least 1 hypomanic and 1 major depressive episode. Borderline person ality disorder may coexist with bipolar I disorder but the diagnosis is based on the presence of unstable personal relationships and severe impulsivity. Cyclothymic disorder presents with a history of both hypomanic and depressive symptoms that do not meet the full criteria for hypomanic or major depressive episodes. Disruptive mood dysregulation disorder is a condition diagnosed between the ages of 6 and 18, characterized by severe recurrent outbursts of temper.', options = '["Bipolar I","Bipolar II","Borderline personality","Cyclothymic","Disruptive mood dysregulation"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'abfb5c37-a1d0-4169-8b34-743f32f81b20';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following findings on a HINTS (head - impulse, nystagmus, test of skew) examination suggests a central etiology for a patient with vertigo?', explanation = 'The HINTS (head - impulse, nystagmus, test of skew) examination can help determine whether the etiology of vertigo is peripheral or central. When performed by trained clinicians, it is highly sensitive and specific in identifying central causes such as acute stroke. For a test of skew the patient looks straight ahead while each eye is covered and uncovered. Vertical deviation of a covered eye after uncovering suggests a central etiology. Findings that are suggestive of peripheral causes of vertigo include spo ntaneous nystagmus that is unidirectional and horizontal, suppression of nystagmus with visual fixation, and saccade (rapid movement of both eyes where the gaze overcorrects to keep focused on the examiner) when the patient’s head is thrust 10° to the righ t and left while the patient’s eyes are fixed on the examiner’s nose.', options = '["Saccade when the patient’s head is thrust 10° to the right and left while the patient’s eyes are fixed on the examiner’s nose","Spontaneous nystagmus that is unidirectional and horizontal","Suppression of nystagmus with visual fixation","Vertical deviation upon uncovering a covered eye while the patient is looking straight ahead"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '3c09aa67-c599-4854-80a9-a29e2a32c1b7';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following medications is most likely to interfere with the results of screening for primary hyperaldosteronism?', explanation = 'Primary aldosteronism is a common cause of resistant hypertension, although it is largely underrecognized. Initial screening is accomplished through simultaneous measurement of plasma aldosterone and renin levels. An elevated plasma aldosterone to renin ra tio identifies patients with probable aldosteronism who may then undergo confirmatory testing if clinically indicated; in some cases, additional testing is not needed to reach a diagnosis. Medications that most significantly impact the renin - angiotensin - al dosterone system, particularly mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists such as spironolactone, ideally should be withheld for a minimum of 4 weeks prior to testing for primary aldosteronism. Other antihypertensive medication classes, including °CE inhibitor s, angiotensin receptor blockers, diuretics, β - blockers, and dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers, also may interfere with test results, although less significantly than mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists.', options = '["Amlodipine (Norvasc)","Hydrochlorothiazide","Lisinopril (Zestril)","Metoprolol","Spironolactone (Aldactone)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '711c47f1-f948-414d-820e-06849f55d2c3';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 52 - year - old female sees you for a health maintenance examination. Which one of the following findings on fundoscopic examination would be most concerning for glaucoma?', explanation = 'Glaucoma is defined as a group of eye diseases that damage the optic nerve. It is often, but not always, accompanied by increased intraocular pressure. An increased cup to disc ratio (cupping) is an abnormality that is associated with glaucoma. This has be en defined as a ratio >0.3 – 0.5. Retinal vessel changes are not associated with glaucoma. Papilledema is a swelling of the optic disc that is generally caused by increased intracranial pressure.', options = '["Constricted retinal vessels","Dilated retinal vessels","A diminished cup to disc ratio","An elevated cup to disc ratio","Papilledema"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'e3b4e9e7-9a4d-4013-8703-a568203bbcbb';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 34 - year - old female with intellectual disability, hypothyroidism, and bipolar disorder presents for routine follow - up. Her case worker notes that she has been excessively thirsty and urinating more than usual over the past several months despite limiting her fluids. She also wakes at night to urinate. Laboratory studies prior to her visit reveal a therapeutic lithium level, as well as normal creatinine, electrolyte, and blood glucose levels. Which one of the following is most likely present in this patient’s case?', explanation = 'This patient is at risk for both psychogenic polydipsia due to intellectual disability and nephrogenic diabetes insipidus due to lithium therapy. The combination of ongoing polydipsia, polyuria despite fluid restriction, and nocturia suggests diabetes insipidus rather than psychogenic polydipsia. Diabetes insipidus is a loss of free water in the urine due to a lack of antidiuretic hormone (central) or insensitivity to antidiuretic hormone in the kidney (nephrogenic). Interstit ial cystitis and overactive bladder can cause urinary frequency but not polydipsia. Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH) is associated with a low sodium level and does not cause polyuria.', options = '["Diabetes insipidus","Interstitial cystitis","Overactive bladder","Psychogenic polydipsia","Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '7bfe9b6e-9866-4533-93c1-5e85e219dd75';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 30 - year - old female with obesity and tobacco use disorder presents for evaluation of a persistent painful lump in her axilla. After an appropriate evaluation you diagnose mild hidradenitis suppurativa. In addition to weight loss and smoking cessation counseling, which one of the following treatment options would be most appropriate?', explanation = 'For patients with mild hidradenitis suppurativa, topical clindamycin is recommended as first - line treatment and often works well as monotherapy (SOR B). Patients with hidradenitis suppurativa who have overweight and smoke should be advised that weight loss and smoking cessation have been shown to decrease severity of disease and improve treatment response (SOR A). For patients with moderate disease, oral tetracyclines in addition to topical clindamycin are recommended as first - line therapy. Although intrale sional triamcinolone may be considered for procedural management of mild hidradenitis suppurativa, topical triamcinolone is not recommended. Other oral antibiotics that have shown benefit include clindamycin and rifampin, although azithromycin is not a rec ommended treatment option. While NSAIDs such as topical diclofenac and oral meloxicam may help to alleviate discomfort associated with active lesions, they are not part of the routine management of hidradenitis suppurativa.', options = '["Topical clindamycin gel (Cleocin T)","Topical diclofenac gel","Topical triamcinolone cream","Oral azithromycin (Zithromax)","Oral meloxicam"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '31ae0297-c31b-4fee-9ca0-db3de4e9e63f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 70 - year - old female sees you at the request of her surgeon to discuss anticoagulation management prior to a scheduled cholecystectomy. She has a past medical history of atrial fibrillation, stage 3a chronic kidney disease, hypertension, depression, and cerebrovascular disease. She had an isc hemic stroke 1 year ago. Her current medications include the following: Amlodipine (Norvasc) Losartan (Cozaar) Metoprolol succinate (Toprol - XL) Sertraline (Zoloft) Warfarin Her vital signs include a blood pressure of 140/82 mm Hg, a heart rate of 90 beats/min, and an oxygen saturation of 96≥ on room air. A cardiovascular examination reveals an irregularly irregular rhythm. The remainder of the examination findings are unremar kable. An INR today is 2.2. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate perioperative anticoagulation therapy for this patient?', explanation = 'Continuing warfarin is not recommended prior to elective procedures or surgeries in patients who are taking warfarin for stroke prevention secondary to atrial fibrillation. The BRIDGE trial excluded patients who had an ischemic stroke within the previous 1 2 weeks but included those with more distant strokes. For such patients, cessation of warfarin without bridging with low - molecular - weight heparin or antiplatelet agents is the appropriate management strategy. There is no evidence that using a lower target INR is appropriate.', options = '["Continuing warfarin with a goal INR of 1.4 – 1.6","Discontinuing warfarin 5 days prior to surgery and bridging with aspirin","Discontinuing warfarin 5 days prior to surgery and bridging with clopidogrel (Plavix)","Discontinuing warfarin 5 days prior to surgery and bridging with low - molecular - weight heparin","Discontinuing warfarin 5 days prior to surgery without bridging therapy"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'f4f57925-a7b1-4798-94db-324f5d2e13b4';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 30 - year - old female with obesity and tobacco use disorder presents for evaluation of a persistent painful lump in her axilla. After an appropriate evaluation you diagnose mild hidradenitis suppurativa. In addition to weight loss and smoking cessation counseling, which one of the following treatment options would be most appropriate?', explanation = 'For patients with mild hidradenitis suppurativa, topical clindamycin is recommended as first - line treatment and often works well as monotherapy (SOR B). Patients with hidradenitis suppurativa who have overweight and smoke should be advised that weight loss and smoking cessation have been shown to decrease severity of disease and improve treatment response (SOR A). For patients with moderate disease, oral tetracyclines in addition to topical clindamycin are recommended as first - line therapy. Although intrale sional triamcinolone may be considered for procedural management of mild hidradenitis suppurativa, topical triamcinolone is not recommended. Other oral antibiotics that have shown benefit include clindamycin and rifampin, although azithromycin is not a rec ommended treatment option. While NSAIDs such as topical diclofenac and oral meloxicam may help to alleviate discomfort associated with active lesions, they are not part of the routine management of hidradenitis suppurativa.', options = '["Topical clindamycin gel (Cleocin T)","Topical diclofenac gel","Topical triamcinolone cream","Oral azithromycin (Zithromax)","Oral meloxicam"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = 'cc808a4d-e4a7-4f07-856e-8e67ae74d506';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 39 - year - old female presents with a sudden onset of palpitations. Her vital signs include a blood pressure of 114/68 mm Hg and a pulse rate of 166 beats/min. She is cooperative and alert. An EKG shows regular narrow complex tachycardia with normal intervals. She has tried vagal maneuvers with no improvement. Which one of the following would be the mos t appropriate treatment at this time?', explanation = 'If vagal maneuvers are not effective in the management of stable supraventricular tachycardia (SVT), the most appropriate next step is treatment with intravenous adenosine at an initial dose of 6 mg. Atropine is a treatment option for bradycardia, particul arly in the setting of heart block. Diltiazem or metoprolol may be used acutely in atrial fibrillation or in the prevention of SVT. Synchronized cardioversion is indicated in patients with SVT who become hypotensive or unresponsive.', options = '["Adenosine","Atropine","Diltiazem (Cardizem)","Metoprolol","Synchronized cardioversion Item #191 Item #191"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '10c10b80-14a4-4919-af98-45ce42dfbaea';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 30 - year - old female with a medical history of anxiety and seasonal allergies presents for evaluation of palpitations and a racing heartbeat that has worsened over the last 3 – 4 days. Recently, her escitalopram (Lexapro) dosage was increased to 20 mg daily and she started using fluticasone propionate nasal spray (Flonase) a nd oral cetirizine (Zyrtec), 10 mg daily. A CBC, comprehensive metabolic panel, and TSH level are normal. A urine pregnancy test is negative. An EKG today shows a heart rate of 85 beats/min and a QTc interval of 500 milliseconds. Which one of the followin g would be the most appropriate next step?', explanation = 'This patient’s EKG shows a prolonged QTc interval (>460 milliseconds for women). QT prolongation can indicate polymorphic ventricular tachycardia characterized by palpitations. QT prolongation can be congenital or acquired. Escitalopram and other antidepre ssants are associated with QT prolongation. Any QT - prolonging medications should be discontinued, and a subsequent EKG should be obtained once the drug levels are expected to be minimal. Reassurance only would not be the most appropriate next step as QT prolongation can lead to torsades de pointes, a potentially fatal arrhythmia (SOR C). Cetirizine and fluticasone are not known to prolong the QT interval. Echocardiography would not be the next step in management.', options = '["Reassurance only","Discontinuing cetirizine","Discontinuing escitalopram","Discontinuing fluticasone","Echocardiography"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '194c59c1-2904-4c8a-a1a2-b5240ff7fb72';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following medications has been shown to increase the resolution of metabolic dysfunction – associated steatotic liver disease (MASLD), formerly known as nonalcoholic fatty liver disease?', explanation = 'Although lifestyle modification remains the first - line treatment of metabolic dysfunction – associated steatotic liver disease (formerly known as nonalcoholic fatty liver disease), pioglitazone increases the resolution of nonalcoholic steatohepatitis, especi ally in patients with advanced fibrosis. Pioglitazone may cause weight gain and should be avoided in patients with heart failure, and it carries a small risk for bladder cancer. Glyburide, metformin, repaglinide, and vitamin D (cholecalciferol) do not impr ove steatohepatitis or fibrosis.', options = '["Glyburide","Metformin","Pioglitazone (Actos)","Repaglinide","Vitamin D (cholecalciferol)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '60f0975c-3c48-43aa-b0f2-0b92811941d2';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'In patients with posttraumatic stress disorder, which one of the following medications is most effective for the treatment of midsleep awakening due to hyperarousal or nightmares?', explanation = 'The α - blocker prazosin can be effective in the treatment of midsleep awakening due to hyperarousal or nightmares by decreasing sympathetic nervous tone. Due to their toxicity profiles, tricyclic antidepressants such as amitriptyline are usually not initiat ed in patients with posttraumatic stress disorder (PTSD) until multiple first - line treatments have failed. Benzodiazepines such as clonazepam are generally avoided in patients with PTSD due to potential misuse and chronic long - term effects. SSRIs such as f luoxetine and SNRIs such as venlafaxine are the most effective pharmacologic treatments for overall reduction of PTSD symptoms. However, they are not used specifically for nighttime trauma - related nightmares.', options = '["Amitriptyline","Clonazepam (Klonopin)","Fluoxetine (Prozac)","Prazosin (Minipress)","Extended - release venlafaxine (Effexor XR)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '0ae93324-a0f4-44ff-88f1-abdc39a7a106';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Laser - assisted in - situ keratomileusis (LASIK) surgery is performed to treat', explanation = 'Laser - assisted in - situ keratomileusis (LASIK) surgery involves the surgical removal of an anterior corneal flap, stromal ablation, and replacement of the flap. LASIK and photorefractive keratectomy (PRK) are considered the standard surgical procedures for the correction of myopia and other refractive errors, such as hyperopia and astigmatism. Ninety - eight percent of patients achieve a visual acuity of 20/40 or better. Common complications include glare symptoms, dry eye, undercorrection, and overcorrection. Significant serious complications include keratitis, epithelial ingrowth, or flap dissection. Refractive surgery does not correct age - related farsightedness (presbyopia), which is due to loss of lens elasticity, rather than a corneal problem. LASIK is not used to treat cataracts, closed - angle glaucoma, or retinal detachment.', options = '["cataracts","closed - angle glaucoma","myopia","presbyopia","retinal detachment"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '5b83e9f4-ae40-47fe-b2c4-207e9b999b6e';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 39 - year - old female presents for a postpartum visit 2 months after a preterm delivery that was complicated by chronic hypertension and a bicornuate uterus. She does not smoke cigarettes. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate contraceptive for this patient?', explanation = 'This patient has a structural abnormality of the uterus and IUDs are contraindicated. Furthermore, even well - controlled hypertension is a relative contraindication to estrogen - containing contraceptives such as combination pills and the vaginal ring, due to associated vascular risks in a patient older than 35 years. Nonhormonal methods and progesterone - only contraceptive pills, depot injections, and implants remain options. The etonogestrel implant is the most effective of these options.', options = '["Oral levonorgestrel/ethinyl estradiol","An etonogestrel/ethinyl estradiol vaginal ring (NuvaRing)","An etonogestrel subdermal implant (Nexplanon)","A levonorgestrel IUD (Mirena)","A copper IUD (Paragard)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'fd90633f-eff9-42e2-b4c3-a6c3fd7e458a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 24 - year - old female sees you for treatment of significant depression and associated hypomanic symptoms. She has been experiencing racing thoughts, agitation, and a decreased need for sleep. Which one of the following is CONTRAINDICATED in this patient?', explanation = 'Antidepressant monotherapy is contraindicated in patients with depression who have mixed features of associated hypomania or mania because it may precipitate or worsen mania. First - line treatment is mood stabilizers such as lithium, anticonvulsants, and an tipsychotics.', options = '["Cariprazine (Vraylar) monotherapy","Quetiapine (Seroquel) monotherapy","Sertraline (Zoloft) monotherapy","Lurasidone (Latuda) plus valproic acid","Quetiapine plus lithium"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'f5ce2ae8-7de9-4d7e-8884-b0ddf25b432a';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommends screening which one of the following groups for obstructive sleep apnea (OSA)?', explanation = 'In November 2022, the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force concluded that the current evidence was insufficient to assess the balance of benefits and harms of screening for obstructive sleep apnea (OSA) in the general adult population (I recommendation). Th is applies to all adults ≥18 years of age without signs of OSA or with unrecognized symptoms of OSA. This recommendation also includes persons who are unaware of or are unconcerned by their symptoms.', options = '["All adults >50 years of age","All adults who have ≥1 first - degree relative with documented OSA","All adults who have a BMI ≥35 kg/m","All adults who have hypertension","No groups should be routinely screened"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '9f66d260-ec18-4c75-b30c-9473607fa1b0';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A physically active 25 - year - old male presents with foot pain after an injury. X - rays are obtained. A proximal fracture at which one of the following metatarsals would be at the greatest risk for nonunion?', explanation = 'Proximal fifth metatarsal fractures are categorized by zones. Zone 2 is located at the metaphyseal - diaphyseal junction at the fourth and fifth metatarsal joint. Zone 3 fractures are located at the proximal 1.5 cm of the diaphysis. Because of poor blood supply, fractures in zone 2 or zone 3 of the fifth metatarsal have a risk for slow healing and nonunion. Surgical management of these fractures should be considered in active patients to decrease the risk for nonunion (SOR B).', options = '["First","Second","Third","Fourth","Fifth"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '24779fd9-64a1-41a6-abc4-c1a3add94d7c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following is a possible adverse effect of short - term systemic corticosteroids?', explanation = 'Even short courses of systemic corticosteroids are associated with many possible adverse effects, including mood and sleep disturbance, hyperglycemia, elevated blood pressure, sepsis, fracture, and venous thromboembolism. Hair loss, hyperkalemia, hypoglyce mia, and hypotension are not among the side effects of short - term corticosteroid use.', options = '["Hair loss","Hyperkalemia","Hypoglycemia","Hypotension","Mood disturbance"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '00387cab-eec0-43ac-9c7a-7566854a7469';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 78 - year - old male with a history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, ongoing tobacco use, and carotid endarterectomy presents to the emergency department with bloody diarrhea and severe lower abdominal pain. Which one of the following is the most likely dia gnosis?', explanation = 'The differential diagnosis for the painful rectal bleeding in this patient includes inflammatory bowel disease, infectious colitis, hemorrhoids, and ischemic colitis. The patient''s multiple risk factors for vascular disease place him at higher risk for isc hemic colitis. The differential diagnosis for painless rectal bleeding includes angiodysplasia, arteriovenous malformation, colon cancer, diverticular bleeding, and post - polypectomy bleeding. Irritable bowel syndrome does not cause rectal bleeding.', options = '["Angiodysplasia","Arteriovenous malformation","Colon cancer","Irritable bowel syndrome","Ischemic colitis"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'b33374a6-ef44-408b-bb5b-38b951502f53';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 39 - year - old female presents for a postpartum visit 2 months after a preterm delivery that was complicated by chronic hypertension and a bicornuate uterus. She does not smoke cigarettes. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate contraceptive for this patient?', explanation = 'This patient has a structural abnormality of the uterus and IUDs are contraindicated. Furthermore, even well - controlled hypertension is a relative contraindication to estrogen - containing contraceptives such as combination pills and the vaginal ring, due to associated vascular risks in a patient older than 35 years. Nonhormonal methods and progesterone - only contraceptive pills, depot injections, and implants remain options. The etonogestrel implant is the most effective of these options.', options = '["Oral levonorgestrel/ethinyl estradiol","An etonogestrel/ethinyl estradiol vaginal ring (NuvaRing)","An etonogestrel subdermal implant (Nexplanon)","A levonorgestrel IUD (Mirena)","A copper IUD (Paragard)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = '021042d7-3fdd-454a-a71a-17d969aae765';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 52 - year - old male presents to the emergency department with a sudden onset of what he describes as the worst headache of his life. You are concerned about the possibility of an intracranial hemorrhage. After performing an examination to rule out neurologic deficits, which one of the follo wing would be the most appropriate next step in evaluation?', explanation = 'A patient describing a headache as the worst headache of their life can be a red - flag symptom of an intracranial hemorrhage, and CT of the head without contrast is the recommended next step in evaluation. Contrast should not be used because it can obscure the signs of bleeding. If a subarachnoid hemorrhage is suspected, CT of the head should be completed before performing a lumbar puncture to ensure there is no evidence of intracranial hemorrhage or midline shift.', options = '["CT of the head without contrast","CT of the head with contrast","MRI of the head with and without contrast","A lumbar puncture"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '71f0cfb3-189e-4701-84c0-0a8f0c2527e1';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A physically active 25 - year - old male presents with foot pain after an injury. X - rays are obtained. A proximal fracture at which one of the following metatarsals would be at the greatest risk for nonunion?', explanation = 'Proximal fifth metatarsal fractures are categorized by zones. Zone 2 is located at the metaphyseal - diaphyseal junction at the fourth and fifth metatarsal joint. Zone 3 fractures are located at the proximal 1.5 cm of the diaphysis. Because of poor blood supply, fractures in zone 2 or zone 3 of the fifth metatarsal have a risk for slow healing and nonunion. Surgical management of these fractures should be considered in active patients to decrease the risk for nonunion (SOR B).', options = '["First","Second","Third","Fourth","Fifth"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '8d7edb1e-9ebe-4a1c-aad6-5a50f8eabe58';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following is associated with at least 6 months of exclusive breastfeeding in infants?', explanation = 'Exclusively breastfeeding infants for at least 6 months confers multiple health benefits to both the mother and the infant. Breastfeeding persons have decreased risks for breast and ovarian cancers, postpartum depression, hypertension, cardiovascular disea se, and type 2 diabetes. Breastfed infants have decreased risks for atopic dermatitis and gastroenteritis. Other potential infant benefits, based on observational studies, include lower risks for childhood leukemia, hypertension, obesity, otitis media, sud den infant death syndrome, and type 1 and 2 diabetes.', options = '["Higher incidence of infant peanut allergy","Higher infant HDL - cholesterol levels","Lower risk for infant atopic dermatitis","Lower maternal incidence of endometrial cancer","Lower maternal incidence of hypothyroidism"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'ccaffaea-b234-4e24-8464-c3fcb5b1e419';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A previously healthy 38 - year - old female presents with an acute onset of near - syncope and shortness of breath. An examination reveals a BMI of 34 kg/m , a temperature of 36.9 °C (98.4 °F), an oxygen saturation of 92≥ on room air, a respiratory rate of 24/min, a heart rate of 105 beats/min, and a blood pressure of 118/70 mm Hg. She has some tenderness and swelling of her left lower leg. Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in diagnosis?', explanation = 'This patient’s case is highly concerning for acute pulmonary embolism. She has a high (>50≥) pretest probability of a pulmonary embolus based on both the Wells criteria and Geneva score. Patients with a high pretest probability of pulmonary embolism should have CT angiography (CTA) as the initial test, while patients with a low to intermediate risk should start with a D - dimer level. An arterial blood gas measurement may be helpful but is less likely to yield the specific diagnosis. Echocardiography may be p art of the evaluation of pulmonary embolus if there are signs of heart strain, but it is not the most appropriate next step. A ventilation - perfusion (V/Q) scan is less sensitive and specific than CTA and takes longer to perform, but it would be indicated i f CTA is contraindicated or not available.', options = '["An arterial blood gas measurement","A D - dimer level","Echocardiography","CT angiography of the chest","A ventilation - perfusion (V/Q) scan"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = 'ce2e87d1-5f2a-49b9-89c2-9bd17e8f064c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 68 - year - old male presents with dependent edema and an ulcer over the medial malleolus secondary to venous insufficiency. The dorsalis pedis pulse is intact. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate management of this patient’s edema and ulcer?', explanation = 'Graduated compression stockings are the mainstay of treatment for chronic venous insufficiency. The compression is generally highest at the ankle with decreasing pressures at the calf. While compression stockings with <20 mm Hg tension may be helpful for c omfort, they are not considered adequate for venous insufficiency. Insufficiency significant enough to cause venous ulcers should be treated with 30 – 40 mm Hg pressure stockings, which have been shown to be effective for >90≥ of ulcers if a patient is 70≥ – 8 0≥ compliant with usage. Varicosities with swelling and discomfort may be helped by 20 – 30 mm Hg pressure compression stockings. Compression stockings with >50 mm Hg of pressure are not as well tolerated and are generally used in patients with lymphedema. U nna boots have significant variability of pressures and are not generally recommended for this condition.', options = '["A nongraduated compression stocking with 10 – 20 mm Hg pressure at the ankle","A graduated compression stocking with 30 – 40 mm Hg pressure at the ankle","A graduated compression stocking with 50 – 60 mm Hg pressure at the ankle","An Unna boot Hypocalcemia can cause which one of the following-,"Constipation","Hypertension","Paresthesias","Respiratory suppression","Tachycardia"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'c3745c51-0d8d-42c2-b7d2-7e53f3185287';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 60 - year - old patient presents with a 3 - month history of gustatory dysfunction and says that nothing tastes normal. Which one of the following nutritional deficiencies could be responsible for this patient’s taste disorder?', explanation = 'Disorders of taste and smell are reported by as many as one - fifth of those ≥40 years of age and one - third of those ≥80 years of age. These disorders affect patients’ quality of life and safety. The differential diagnosis is extensive. Of the options listed , only a deficiency of vitamin B can cause a taste disturbance (SOR C). 3', options = '["Calcium","Selenium","Vitamin B","Vitamin D","Vitamin E"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 2 WHERE id = 'f3aaedc6-b783-471a-a4c9-412d13a198e6';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A physically active 25 - year - old male presents with foot pain after an injury. X - rays are obtained. A proximal fracture at which one of the following metatarsals would be at the greatest risk for nonunion?', explanation = 'Proximal fifth metatarsal fractures are categorized by zones. Zone 2 is located at the metaphyseal - diaphyseal junction at the fourth and fifth metatarsal joint. Zone 3 fractures are located at the proximal 1.5 cm of the diaphysis. Because of poor blood supply, fractures in zone 2 or zone 3 of the fifth metatarsal have a risk for slow healing and nonunion. Surgical management of these fractures should be considered in active patients to decrease the risk for nonunion (SOR B).', options = '["First","Second","Third","Fourth","Fifth"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '9423a020-3a57-4a65-bcd7-6f1220eab4cb';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 78 - year - old male with a history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, ongoing tobacco use, and carotid endarterectomy presents to the emergency department with bloody diarrhea and severe lower abdominal pain. Which one of the following is the most likely dia gnosis?', explanation = 'The differential diagnosis for the painful rectal bleeding in this patient includes inflammatory bowel disease, infectious colitis, hemorrhoids, and ischemic colitis. The patient''s multiple risk factors for vascular disease place him at higher risk for isc hemic colitis. The differential diagnosis for painless rectal bleeding includes angiodysplasia, arteriovenous malformation, colon cancer, diverticular bleeding, and post - polypectomy bleeding. Irritable bowel syndrome does not cause rectal bleeding.', options = '["Angiodysplasia","Arteriovenous malformation","Colon cancer","Irritable bowel syndrome","Ischemic colitis"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = 'd179f573-4f52-4b39-9086-9feccab09865';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following medications is most likely to interfere with the results of screening for primary hyperaldosteronism?', explanation = 'Primary aldosteronism is a common cause of resistant hypertension, although it is largely underrecognized. Initial screening is accomplished through simultaneous measurement of plasma aldosterone and renin levels. An elevated plasma aldosterone to renin ra tio identifies patients with probable aldosteronism who may then undergo confirmatory testing if clinically indicated; in some cases, additional testing is not needed to reach a diagnosis. Medications that most significantly impact the renin - angiotensin - al dosterone system, particularly mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists such as spironolactone, ideally should be withheld for a minimum of 4 weeks prior to testing for primary aldosteronism. Other antihypertensive medication classes, including °CE inhibitor s, angiotensin receptor blockers, diuretics, β - blockers, and dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers, also may interfere with test results, although less significantly than mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists.', options = '["Amlodipine (Norvasc)","Hydrochlorothiazide","Lisinopril (Zestril)","Metoprolol","Spironolactone (Aldactone)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '4c53cd4d-bc0b-4e17-b96b-2b18b3fffff3';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A healthy 15 - year - old female is brought to your office for a well adolescent visit. She does not have any health concerns or preexisting medical conditions. Based on the guidelines from the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force, which one of the following would be most appropriate for this patient?', explanation = 'The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) recommends depression screening for adolescents beginning at age 12 (B recommendation). The American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) recommends routine vision screening from 12 months to 5 years of age and only risk - based vision screening in adolescents as vision conditions are less likely to begin in older children. The USPSTF recommends vision screening at least once in all children ages 3 – 5 (B recommendation). Iron deficiency screening is not recommended in ad olescents; however, the AAP recommends universal hemoglobin or hematocrit screening at 12 months of age while the USPSTF states that there is insufficient evidence (I recommendation). While the AAP recommends dyslipidemia screening in children ages 9 – 11, t he USPSTF currently states there is insufficient evidence for screening for ≤20 years of age (I recommendation). The USPSTF recommends against cervical cancer screening before age 21 (D recommendation). Furthermore, cytology is recommended for those age 21 and older while high - risk HPV testing is not recommended until age 30.', options = '["A vision examination","Depression screening","A CBC","A lipid panel","HPV testing"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = 'c0a9d535-4418-4c22-8ca8-c88bd3a08c6c';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A patient presents with right - sided facial weakness. You suspect Bell palsy, but an assessment suggests a central brain lesion. A central brain lesion would result in which one of the following findings on the affected side?', explanation = 'Patients with Bell palsy present with acute weakness or paralysis of the face caused by dysfunction of peripheral cranial nerve VII (the facial nerve). A central lesion should be suspected if the patient is able to wrinkle the forehead on the affected side during the examination. This is also true if the patient is able to close both eyes tightly. While central nervous system lesions such as multiple sclerosis, stroke, or tumor can also cause facial nerve palsy, some motor neurons to the forehead cross sides at the level of the brain stem, so the fibers in the facial nerve going to the forehead come from both cerebral hemispheres. Therefore, central lesions affecting the facial nerve will not paralyze the forehead on the affected side. This causes unilateral facial paralysis with sparing of the forehead. Expected findings on the affected side in Bell palsy include inability to close the eye, normal extraocular movements, flattening of the nasolabial fold, and drooping of the mouth.', options = '["Ability to wrinkle the forehead","Inability to close the eye","Normal extraocular movements","Flattening of the nasolabial fold","Drooping of the mouth"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 0 WHERE id = '3b3aab2d-fcea-4ffb-93d1-78514a62b8f5';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following medications is most likely to interfere with the results of screening for primary hyperaldosteronism?', explanation = 'Primary aldosteronism is a common cause of resistant hypertension, although it is largely underrecognized. Initial screening is accomplished through simultaneous measurement of plasma aldosterone and renin levels. An elevated plasma aldosterone to renin ra tio identifies patients with probable aldosteronism who may then undergo confirmatory testing if clinically indicated; in some cases, additional testing is not needed to reach a diagnosis. Medications that most significantly impact the renin - angiotensin - al dosterone system, particularly mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists such as spironolactone, ideally should be withheld for a minimum of 4 weeks prior to testing for primary aldosteronism. Other antihypertensive medication classes, including °CE inhibitor s, angiotensin receptor blockers, diuretics, β - blockers, and dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers, also may interfere with test results, although less significantly than mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists.', options = '["Amlodipine (Norvasc)","Hydrochlorothiazide","Lisinopril (Zestril)","Metoprolol","Spironolactone (Aldactone)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '07172953-da39-4052-81bc-0d956411a4ed';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Which one of the following community design features can be used to encourage people to walk more?', explanation = 'Public transportation systems encourage users to walk to stops or through stations, and people are more likely to use public transportation if it is designed to be comfortable and convenient. In contrast, research has shown that people are less likely to w alk when everyday destinations are located more than a half - mile away from home. Safety concerns can be a barrier to walking, and high - speed roadways in neighborhoods increase pedestrian risk. Convenient alternatives, such as moving sidewalks and escalator s, also discourage walking.', options = '["Frequently sought destinations (eg, school, work, stores) located at least 1 mile away from residential areas","High - quality public transit systems","High - speed roadways that route traffic through neighborhoods","Moving sidewalks and escalators"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '997084e4-e99f-4051-be81-0bd39fb9b106';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 62 - year - old female sees you for follow - up of bilateral lower extremity edema that worsens throughout the day. A BNP level, TSH level, comprehensive metabolic panel, urinalysis, chest x - ray, EKG, and lower extremity venous ultrasound have all been normal. Which one of the following diagnoses should you consider in this patient?', explanation = 'Obstructive sleep apnea is an increasingly recognized possible etiology of lower extremity edema and should be considered during the evaluation of this patient. While the exact pathophysiology is unknown, nocturnal hypoxemia is thought to lead to increased sympathetic tone resulting in systemic hypertension. This nocturnal hypoxemia can lead to neuroendocrine activation and salt and water retention. Celiac disease, Cushing syndrome, Lyme disease, and Raynaud disease are not associated with lower extremity e dema.', options = '["Celiac disease","Cushing syndrome","Lyme disease","Obstructive sleep apnea","Raynaud disease"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 3 WHERE id = '9a1c78ee-3b41-4765-a109-4d69536c5f5f';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'A 73 - year - old female presents with chronic diarrhea. You suspect microscopic colitis and order colonoscopy. Based on the suspected diagnosis, you should expect which one of the following colonoscopy findings?', explanation = 'In a patient with microscopic colitis, the most common finding on colonoscopy is normal mucosa. Because the mucosa appears normal, microscopic colitis needs to be diagnosed with biopsy. Granulomas may be found in patients with Crohn disease. Ulcerations ar e found in ulcerative colitis. Pseudomembranes are found in Clostridioides difficile infection. Granulomatous changes and pseudomembranes may also require biopsy for diagnosis.', options = '["Granulomas","Normal mucosa","Patchy ulcerations","Pseudomembranes"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 1 WHERE id = '9d446b64-7c04-4eff-935a-730b9b39c606';
UPDATE public.questions SET question_text = 'Of the following, which one is the most effective abortive treatment for cluster headache?', explanation = 'Cluster headache is a type of primary headache in the category of trigeminal autonomic cephalgia, and abortive therapy consists of 100≥ high - flow oxygen and triptans. Its typical onset is age 30 and it is 2 – 3 times more common in males than females. The pa in is severe and unilateral in the orbital, supraorbital, or temporal locations. It is associated with at least one of the following symptoms on the ipsilateral side: conjunctival injection or lacrimation, nasal congestion or rhinorrhea, miosis or ptosis, eyelid swelling, and sweating of the forehead and face. The pain can last from 30 minutes to almost 3 hours. Hydromorphone and ketorolac can be used to mask other types of pain but are ineffective in stopping cluster headache. Ondansetron stops vomiting, but its side effects include heada che. Propranolol can be used to prevent migraine.', options = '["Hydromorphone ( Dilaudid)","Ketorolac","Ondansetron","Propranolol","Sumatriptan (Imitrex)"]'::jsonb, correct_index = 4 WHERE id = '2dd2dad5-2c82-441f-93da-b08d62af183a';
